{"title_page": "Death Becomes Her", "text_new": "{{short description|1992 film by Robert Zemeckis}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Death Becomes Her\n| image          = Death Becomes Her.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| alt            = \n| director       = [[Robert Zemeckis]]\n| producer       = Robert Zemeckis<br />[[Steve Starkey]]\n| writer         = [[Martin Donovan (screenwriter)|Martin Donovan]]<br />[[David Koepp]]\n| starring       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Meryl Streep]]\n* [[Bruce Willis]]\n* [[Goldie Hawn]]\n* [[Isabella Rossellini]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Alan Silvestri]]\n| cinematography = [[Dean Cundey]]\n| editing        = [[Arthur Schmidt (film editor)|Arthur Schmidt]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1992|7|31}}\n| runtime        = 104 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $55 million\n| gross          = $149 million<ref>{{cite web| title = Death Becomes Her at Box Office Mojo| url = http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=deathbecomesher.htm\n| accessdate = October 4, 2010}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Death Becomes Her''''' is a 1992 American [[fantasy comedy]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/59224?cxt=filmography|title=AFI&#124;Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com}}</ref> directed by [[Robert Zemeckis]], written by [[David Koepp]] and [[Martin Donovan (screenwriter)|Martin Donovan]], and starring [[Meryl Streep]], [[Bruce Willis]], and [[Goldie Hawn]]. The film focuses on a pair of rivals (Streep and Hawn), who drink a magic potion that promises [[Elixir of life|eternal youth]], but experience unpleasant side effects when they physically die, becoming walking, talking corpses in the process.\n\n''Death Becomes Her'' won the [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects]]. The film received mixed reviews from critics, but was a commercial success, grossing $149&nbsp;million worldwide. It has developed a strong [[cult following]], particularly among the [[LGBT]] community.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Please review [[WP:FILMPLOT]] before adding text. Count should not exceed 700 words. -->\nIn 1978, narcissistic, manipulative actress Madeline Ashton performs in an awful musical version of ''[[Sweet Bird of Youth]]'' on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. She invites long-time friend Helen Sharp, an aspiring writer, backstage along with Helen's fianc\u00e9, plastic surgeon Ernest Menville. Ernest is smitten with Madeline, and breaks off his engagement with Helen to marry her. Seven years later, Helen is obese, depressed and committed to a psychiatric hospital where she begins plotting revenge on Madeline.\n\nAnother seven years later, Madeline and Ernest live in Beverly Hills, but they are miserable: Madeline's acting career is declining and Ernest is an alcoholic reduced to working as a [[Embalming#Specialist embalming|reconstructive mortician]]. Receiving an invitation to a party celebrating Helen's new book, Madeline rushes to a spa where she regularly receives facial treatments. Understanding Madeline's situation, the spa owner gives her the business card of Lisle Von Rhuman, a mysterious, glamorous, wealthy socialite specializing in youth rejuvenation.\n\nMadeline and Ernest attend the party for Helen's novel, ''Forever Young'', and discover that somehow, Helen is slim, youthful, and beautiful. Dumbfounded and depressed by Helen's appearance, and upon secretly witnessing Helen tell Ernest that she blames her for his career decline, Madeline visits her young lover, but discovers he is with a woman his age. Dejected, Madeline drives to Lisle's home. Lisle, claiming to be 71, but looking decades younger, reveals the secret of her beauty and youth\u2014an expensive [[Elixir of life|potion that promises eternal life and an everlasting youthful appearance]]. Madeline purchases and drinks the potion and is rejuvenated, regaining her beauty. As a condition of purchase, Lisle warns Madeline to disappear from public life after ten years to keep the existence of the potion secret, and to take good care of her body.\n\nHelen seduces Ernest and convinces him to kill Madeline. When Madeline returns home, she and Ernest argue, during which she falls down the stairs, breaking her neck. Believing Madeline dead, Ernest phones Helen for advice, initially not seeing Madeline stand and approach him with her head twisted backward. At Madeline's request, Ernest drives her to the emergency room. Madeline is told she is technically dead, and faints. She is taken to the [[morgue]] due to her body having no pulse and a temperature below 80&nbsp;\u00b0F. After rescuing Madeline, Ernest considers her resurrection a miracle and uses his skills as a mortician to repair her body at home.\n\nHelen demands information about Madeline's situation. Overhearing Helen and Ernest discussing their plot to kill her, Madeline shoots Helen with a shotgun. Although the blast creates a hole in her abdomen, Helen survives, revealing that she drank the same potion. The two briefly fight before apologizing and reconciling their friendship. Fed up with the pair, Ernest prepares to leave, but Helen and Madeline convince him to do one last repair on their bodies. They realize they will need regular maintenance and scheme to have Ernest drink the potion to ensure he will always be available.\n\nAfter bringing Ernest to Lisle, she offers to give him the potion free of charge in exchange for his surgical skills. Ernest refuses to drink it when he realizes the pitfalls of immortality. He pockets the potion and flees, but becomes trapped on the roof. Helen and Madeline implore Ernest to drink the potion to survive an impending fall. Ernest, realizing that they only need him for their own selfish reasons, refuses and drops the potion to the ground, but after falling he lands in Lisle's pool and escapes. Lisle banishes Madeline and Helen from her group, leaving the pair to rely on each other for companionship and maintenance.\n\nThirty-seven years later, Madeline and Helen attend Ernest's funeral, where he is eulogized as having lived an adventurous and fulfilling life with a large family and friends. The two women are parodies of their former selves, with cracked, peeling paint and putty covering most of their grey and rotting flesh. Helen trips at the top of a staircase. When Madeline hesitates to help her, Helen grabs Madeline and the two tumble down the stairs, breaking to pieces. As their disembodied heads totter down together, Helen sardonically asks Madeline where she parked their car.\n<!-- Please review [[WP:FILMPLOT]] before adding text. Count should not exceed 700 words. -->\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Meryl Streep]] as Madeline Ashton\n* [[Bruce Willis]] as Dr. Ernest Menville\n* [[Goldie Hawn]] as Helen Sharp \n* [[Isabella Rossellini]] as Lisle von Rhoman\n* [[Ian Ogilvy]] as Chagall\n* [[Adam Storke]] as Dakota Williams\n* [[Alaina Reed Hall]] as Psychologist\n* [[Michelle Johnson (actress)|Michelle Johnson]] as Anna Jones\n* [[Mary Ellen Trainor]] as Vivian Adams\n* [[Susan Kellermann]] as ER nurse\n* [[William Frankfather]] as Mr. Roy Franklin\n* [[John Ingle]] as Eulogist\n* [[Debra Jo Rupp]] as Patient\n* [[Fabio Lanzoni|Fabio]] as Lisle's bodyguard\n* [[Sydney Pollack]] as Emergency Department Doctor (uncredited){{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Special effects===\n''Death Becomes Her'' was a technologically complex movie to make, and represented a major advancement in the use of [[computer generated imagery|computer-generated]] effects, under the pioneering direction of [[Industrial Light and Magic]].<ref name=\"ilm.com\">{{cite web| url=https://www.ilm.com/vfx/death-becomes-her/| title=Death Becomes Her (Universal Pictures)| publisher=ilm.com| access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite article| url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1992-08-21/features/9201170039_1_roger-rabbit-special-effects-director-robert-zemeckis| title=Special Effects, Acting Bring 'Death' to Life| author=Judd Blaise| publisher=Sun Sentinel| date=1992-08-21|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> For example, it was the first film where computer-generated skin texture was used, in the shot where Madeline resets her neck after her head is smashed with a shovel by Helen.<ref name=\"ilm.com\"/> Creating the sequences where Madeline's head is dislocated and facing the wrong way around involved a combination of [[blue screen technology]], an [[animatronic]] model created by [[Amalgamated Dynamics]], and prosthetic make-up effects on Meryl Streep to create the look of a twisted neck.<ref>{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xRNVHaaUAp8| title=Death Becomes Her (1992) Vintage Bonus Clip: Meryl's Mom & Special Effects (HD)| | publisher=Youtube| date=2016-06-23| access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fIgJgGOEahk| title=DEATH BECOMES HER Recreating Meryl BTS Special Edition| author=Amalgamated Dynamics Inc.| publisher=Youtube| date=2015-07-25| access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref>\n\nThe digital advancements pioneered on ''Death Becomes Her'' would be incorporated into Industrial Light and Magic's next project, ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]'', released by Universal only a year later. Both films shared cinematographer [[Dean Cundey]] and production designer [[Rick Carter]], in addition to ILM.<ref>{{cite article| url=http://www.indiewire.com/2013/06/5-versions-of-jurassic-park-you-never-saw-97110/| title=5 Versions of 'Jurassic Park' You Never Saw| author=Drew Taylor| publisher=indiewire.com| date=2013-06-11| access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref>\n\nThe production had a fair number of mishaps. For example, in a scene where Helen Sharp and Madeline Ashton are battling with shovels, [[Meryl Streep]] accidentally cut [[Goldie Hawn]]'s face, leaving a faint scar. Streep admitted that she disliked working on a project that focused so heavily on special effects, saying:\n\n{{cquote|My first, my last, my only. I think it's tedious. Whatever concentration you can apply to that kind of comedy is just shredded. You stand there like a piece of machinery\u2014they should get machinery to do it. I loved how it turned out. But it's not fun to act to a lampstand. \"Pretend this is Goldie, right here! Uh, no, I'm sorry, Bob, she went off the mark by five centimeters, and now her head won't match her neck!\" It was like being at the dentist.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,275733_4,00.html |date=2000-03-24 |title=Depth Becomes Her |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=2007-01-25}}</ref>}}\n\n===Filming locations===\nThe film was made entirely in [[Los Angeles]] and used several locations also frequently used in film and television, including the [[Greystone Mansion]] (Ernest's funeral home) and the [[Ebell of Los Angeles]] (Helen's book party).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://ebellla.org/filming/| title=The Ebell of Los Angeles - Filming| publisher=ebellla.org| access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> The exterior of Madeline and Ernest's mansion is located at 1125 Oak Grove Avenue in [[San Marino, California|San Marino]], but the interior was a set built on a soundstage.<ref>{{cite article| url=http://www.iamnotastalker.com/2017/10/13/madeline-and-ernests-mansion-from-death-becomes-her/| title=Madeline and Ernest's Mansion from 'Death Becomes Her'| publisher=iamnotastalker.com| date=2017-10-13| access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|sure=yes|date=March 2018}} The ending scene where Helen and Madeline tumble down a set of stairs outside a chapel was filmed at [[Mount St. Mary's University (Los Angeles)]] in [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://moviemaps.org/locations/87| title=Movies Filmed at Mount Saint Mary's University - Chalon Campus| publisher=moviemaps.org| access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref>\n\n===Editing===\nThe theatrical version of ''Death Becomes Her'' omitted or shortened many scenes featured in the rough cut of the movie.<ref name=\"SS\">{{cite web| url=http://www.simplystreep.com/content/career/films/1992deathbecomesher.html| title=Death Becomes Her| publisher=simplystreep.com| access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=March 2018}} Robert Zemeckis decided this was needed to accelerate the pace of the film and eliminate extraneous jokes. Most dramatically, the original ending was entirely redone after test audiences reacted negatively to it.<ref>{{cite article| url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/07/31/death-becomes-her-25th-anniversary-12-things-you-may-not-know-about-the-classic-comedy-6808575/| title=Death Become Her 25th Anniversary: 12 things you may not know about the classic comedy| author=Jon O'Brien| publisher=metro.co.uk| date=2017-07-31| access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref> The ending featured Ernest, after he has fled Lisle's party, meeting a bartender ([[Tracey Ullman]]), who helps him fake his death to evade Madeline and Helen. The two women encounter Ernest and the bartender 27 years later, living happily as a retired couple.<ref name=\"LAT\">{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-08-09/entertainment/ca-6132_1_ullman-ending| title=A look inside Hollywood and the movies.: THE VANISHING: 'Death Becomes Her' and the Lost Ullman Ending| author=David J. Fox| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| date=1992-08-09| access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref> Zemeckis thought the ending was too happy and opted for the darker ending featured in the final cut.<ref name=\"LAT\"/> Ullman was one of five actors with speaking roles in the film to be eliminated.<ref name=\"LAT\"/> Other scenes that were eliminated included one in which Madeline talks to her agent ([[Jonathan Silverman]]) and one in which Ernest removes a frozen Madeline from the kitchen freezer he has stored her in.<ref name=\"SS\"/> None of the scenes have been released publicly, but sequences can still be viewed in the original theatrical trailer.<ref>{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0jPuZLUY4II| title=Death Becomes Her (1992) Meryl Streep, Bruce Willis - Official Trailer (HD)| publisher=YouTube.com| date=2016-04-11| access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Anchor|Score|Soundtrack}} \nThe score was composed by American film composer [[Alan Silvestri]], who also composed scores of other films directed by Zemeckis.<ref>{{cite web |title=10 of the Most Underrated Horror Scores! |url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/20063/ |accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Release and reception==\n\nThe film opened at number one at the box office with $12,110,355 on the same weekend as and ahead of ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (film)|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'' and ''[[Bebe's Kids]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title= Weekend Box Office `Honors' Tops in a Lackluster Bunch|newspaper= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=1994-05-10|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1994-05-10/entertainment/ca-56005_1_weekend-box-office|accessdate=2010-12-28|first=Robert W.|last=Welkos}}</ref> It went on to earn over $58.4&nbsp;million domestically and $90.6&nbsp;million internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=deathbecomesher.htm|title=Death Becomes Her (1992) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref>\n\nThe film's release on DVD was called \"appallingly bad\",<ref name=\"Michael\">{{cite web|url=http://www.michaeldvd.com.au/Reviews/DeathBecomesHer.asp|title=Death Becomes Her|publisher=Michael Demtschyna|accessdate=November 13, 2012}}</ref> \"horrible\" and \"sloppy\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/10/12/death_becomes_her_1992_dvd_review.shtml|title=BBC - Films - review - Death Becomes Her DVD|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=November 13, 2012}}</ref> due to the quality of its transfer, which has been said to suffer from excessive grain, blur, and muted colors.<ref name=\"Michael\"/> Many online DVD forum users speculated that the DVD transfer was taken from the [[Laserdisc]] edition of the film and called for a restorative release. The film was initially distributed in an open-matte, [[4:3|fullscreen]] edition with an aspect ratio of [[Aspect ratio (image)|1.33:1]] in the United States before a widescreen version with its intended ratio ([[Aspect ratio (image)|1.85:1]]) was released and subsequently distributed worldwide. The latter version has also been mistakenly labelled [[Anamorphic widescreen|anamorphic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guidohenkel.com/2012/07/a-stroll-down-the-dvd-memory-lane/|title=A stroll down the DVD memory lane: Guido Henkel|publisher=Guido Henkel|accessdate=November 13, 2012}}</ref> It was later released in North America on [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] from [[Shout Factory]] on April 26, 2016.\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite news|title=Death Becomes Her|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1992-07-26|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117901657.html|accessdate=2010-10-03|first=Todd|last=McCarthy}}{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Death Becomes Her|work= [[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=1992-08-14|url= http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,311403,00.html|accessdate=2010-10-03}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a rating of 52% based on reviews from 48 critics with the consensus: \"Hawn and Streep are as fabulous as ''Death Becomes Her''{{'}}s innovative special effects; Zemeckis' satire, on the other hand, is as hollow as the world it mocks.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Death Becomes Her (1992)|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/death_becomes_her/|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url=https://m.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Gene Siskel]] and [[Roger Ebert]] both gave the film a 'thumbs down', commenting that while the film had great special effects, it lacked any real substance or character depth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/atm/reviews.html?sec=1&subsec=759|title=''Death Becomes Her'' review}}{{dead link|date=September 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Anchor|Awards and nominations}}\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2011}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|- valign=\"bottom\"\n! Award\n! Role\n! Result\n|-\n| [[Academy Awards]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award]]\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Special Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]] (Meryl Streep)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=9| [[Saturn Award]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Fantasy Film|Best Fantasy Film]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Director|Best Director]] (Robert Zemeckis)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Writing|Best Writing]] (Martin Donovan, David Koepp)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] (Bruce Willis)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] (Meryl Streep)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Music|Best Music]] (Alan Silvestri)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Make-up|Best Make-up]] (Dick Smith, Kevin Haney)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] (Isabella Rossellini)\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Special Effects|Best Special Effects]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n===Legacy===\n''Death Becomes Her'' has acquired a significant cult following, especially in the [[LGBT]] community.<ref name=\"Julia Pugachevsky\">{{cite article| url=http://www.newnownext.com/newnownext-style-death-becomes-her-is-ruling-our-lives-and-our-wardrobes/06/2013/| title=\"Death Becomes Her\" Is Ruling Our Lives: NewNowNext Style| author=Julia Pugachevsky| publisher=newnownext.com| date=2013-06-21| access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref> An article in ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' titled \"The Gloriously Queer Afterlife of 'Death Becomes Her'\" called the film a \"gay cult classic\" and \"a touchstone of the queer community\".<ref name=\"Kristy Puchko\">{{cite magazine| url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/08/death-becomes-her-25th-anniversary-meryl-streep-goldie-hawn-gay-classic| title=The Glorious Queer Afterlife of 'Death Becomes Her'| author=Kristy Puchko| magazine=Vanity Fair| date=2017-08-03| access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref> The movie is screened in bars during [[LGBT Pride Month|Pride Month]], while the characters of Madeline and Helen are favorites of drag performers. In this vein, the movie inspired a ''Death Becomes Her''-themed runway show on [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 7)|season 7]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]''.<ref name=\"Julia Pugachevsky\"/> The winner of season 5, [[Jinkx Monsoon]], has cited the movie as an inspiration to become a drag queen. They have participated in ''Death Becomes Her''-themed photoshoots,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/17/death-becomes-jinkx_n_3287753.html| title=Jinkx Monsoon and Ivy Winters Star in Ricky Middlesworth's 'Death Becomes Her' (PHOTOS)| author=Christopher Rudolph| work=Huffington Post| date=2013-05-17| access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref> and in 2018 they played Madeline in a drag stage show parody called \"Drag Becomes Her\".<ref>{{cite article| url=https://www.todaytix.com/insider/los-angeles/posts/jinkx-monsoon-talks-spoofing-meryl-streep-in-drag-becomes-her| title=Jinkx Monsoon Talks Spoofing Meryl Streep in 'Drag Becomes Her'| author=Ashley Lee| publisher=todaytix.com| date=2018-04-19| access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\nTom Campbell, an executive producer of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'', reflected on the appeal of the movie to gay audiences: {{cquote|They're fighting for beauty. They're against the system. They're also villains, but we understand their complexity. We root for the undead divas because they're trying to win a game that's rigged against them, and\u2014to borrow an apocryphal quote from [[Ginger Rogers]]\u2014they sort of have to do it 'backwards and in high heels.'<ref name=\"Kristy Puchko\"/>}}\n\nIn December 2017, [[Kristin Chenoweth]] was announced to be starring in a Broadway musical adaptation of ''Death Becomes Her''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/death-becomes-her-musical_us_5a316aaee4b07ff75affb6a4|title='Death Becomes Her' is About to Become a Broadway Musical| author=Curtis M. Wong| work=Huffington Post| date=2017-12-13| access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Death Becomes Her}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0104070|title=Death Becomes Her}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=19219|title=Death Becomes Her}}\n\n{{Robert Zemeckis}}\n\n[[Category:1990s black comedy films]]\n[[Category:1992 films]]\n[[Category:American black comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert Zemeckis]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Alan Silvestri]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1978]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1985]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1992]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2029]]\n[[Category:Films set in country houses]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Visual Effects Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Fiction about immortality]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by David Koepp]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1992 film by Robert Zemeckis}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Death Becomes Her\n| image          = Death Becomes Her.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| alt            = \n| director       = [[Robert Zemeckis]]\n| producer       = Robert Zemeckis<br />[[Steve Starkey]]\n| writer         = [[Martin Donovan (screenwriter)|Martin Donovan]]<br />[[David Koepp]]\n| starring       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Meryl Streep]]\n* [[Bruce Willis]]\n* [[Goldie Hawn]]\n* [[Isabella Rossellini]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Alan Silvestri]]\n| cinematography = [[Dean Cundey]]\n| editing        = [[Arthur Schmidt (film editor)|Arthur Schmidt]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1992|7|31}}\n| runtime        = 104 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $55 million\n| gross          = $149 million<ref>{{cite web| title = Death Becomes Her at Box Office Mojo| url = http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=deathbecomesher.htm\n| accessdate = October 4, 2010}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Death Becomes Her''''' is a 1992 American [[black comedy]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/59224?cxt=filmography|title=AFI&#124;Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com}}</ref> directed by [[Robert Zemeckis]], written by [[David Koepp]] and [[Martin Donovan (screenwriter)|Martin Donovan]], and starring [[Meryl Streep]], [[Bruce Willis]], and [[Goldie Hawn]]. The film focuses on a pair of rivals (Streep and Hawn), who drink a magic potion that promises [[Elixir of life|eternal youth]], but experience unpleasant side effects when they physically die, becoming walking, talking corpses in the process.\n\n''Death Becomes Her'' won the [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects]]. The film received mixed reviews from critics, but was a commercial success, grossing $149&nbsp;million worldwide. It has developed a strong [[cult following]], particularly among the [[LGBT]] community.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Please review [[WP:FILMPLOT]] before adding text. Count should not exceed 700 words. -->\nIn 1978, narcissistic, manipulative actress Madeline Ashton performs in an awful musical version of ''[[Sweet Bird of Youth]]'' on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. She invites long-time friend Helen Sharp, an aspiring writer, backstage along with Helen's fianc\u00e9, plastic surgeon Ernest Menville. Ernest is smitten with Madeline, and breaks off his engagement with Helen to marry her. Seven years later, Helen is obese, depressed and committed to a psychiatric hospital where she begins plotting revenge on Madeline.\n\nAnother seven years later, Madeline and Ernest live in Beverly Hills, but they are miserable: Madeline's acting career is declining and Ernest is an alcoholic reduced to working as a [[Embalming#Specialist embalming|reconstructive mortician]]. Receiving an invitation to a party celebrating Helen's new book, Madeline rushes to a spa where she regularly receives facial treatments. Understanding Madeline's situation, the spa owner gives her the business card of Lisle Von Rhuman, a mysterious, glamorous, wealthy socialite specializing in youth rejuvenation.\n\nMadeline and Ernest attend the party for Helen's novel, ''Forever Young'', and discover that somehow, Helen is slim, youthful, and beautiful. Dumbfounded and depressed by Helen's appearance, and upon secretly witnessing Helen tell Ernest that she blames her for his career decline, Madeline visits her young lover, but discovers he is with a woman his age. Dejected, Madeline drives to Lisle's home. Lisle, claiming to be 71, but looking decades younger, reveals the secret of her beauty and youth\u2014an expensive [[Elixir of life|potion that promises eternal life and an everlasting youthful appearance]]. Madeline purchases and drinks the potion and is rejuvenated, regaining her beauty. As a condition of purchase, Lisle warns Madeline to disappear from public life after ten years to keep the existence of the potion secret, and to take good care of her body.\n\nHelen seduces Ernest and convinces him to kill Madeline. When Madeline returns home, she and Ernest argue, during which she falls down the stairs, breaking her neck. Believing Madeline dead, Ernest phones Helen for advice, initially not seeing Madeline stand and approach him with her head twisted backward. At Madeline's request, Ernest drives her to the emergency room. Madeline is told she is technically dead, and faints. She is taken to the [[morgue]] due to her body having no pulse and a temperature below 80&nbsp;\u00b0F. After rescuing Madeline, Ernest considers her resurrection a miracle and uses his skills as a mortician to repair her body at home.\n\nHelen demands information about Madeline's situation. Overhearing Helen and Ernest discussing their plot to kill her, Madeline shoots Helen with a shotgun. Although the blast creates a hole in her abdomen, Helen survives, revealing that she drank the same potion. The two briefly fight before apologizing and reconciling their friendship. Fed up with the pair, Ernest prepares to leave, but Helen and Madeline convince him to do one last repair on their bodies. They realize they will need regular maintenance and scheme to have Ernest drink the potion to ensure he will always be available.\n\nAfter bringing Ernest to Lisle, she offers to give him the potion free of charge in exchange for his surgical skills. Ernest refuses to drink it when he realizes the pitfalls of immortality. He pockets the potion and flees, but becomes trapped on the roof. Helen and Madeline implore Ernest to drink the potion to survive an impending fall. Ernest, realizing that they only need him for their own selfish reasons, refuses and drops the potion to the ground, but after falling he lands in Lisle's pool and escapes. Lisle banishes Madeline and Helen from her group, leaving the pair to rely on each other for companionship and maintenance.\n\nThirty-seven years later, Madeline and Helen attend Ernest's funeral, where he is eulogized as having lived an adventurous and fulfilling life with a large family and friends. The two women are parodies of their former selves, with cracked, peeling paint and putty covering most of their grey and rotting flesh. Helen trips at the top of a staircase. When Madeline hesitates to help her, Helen grabs Madeline and the two tumble down the stairs, breaking to pieces. As their disembodied heads totter down together, Helen sardonically asks Madeline where she parked their car.\n<!-- Please review [[WP:FILMPLOT]] before adding text. Count should not exceed 700 words. -->\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Meryl Streep]] as Madeline Ashton\n* [[Bruce Willis]] as Dr. Ernest Menville\n* [[Goldie Hawn]] as Helen Sharp \n* [[Isabella Rossellini]] as Lisle von Rhoman\n* [[Ian Ogilvy]] as Chagall\n* [[Adam Storke]] as Dakota Williams\n* [[Alaina Reed Hall]] as Psychologist\n* [[Michelle Johnson (actress)|Michelle Johnson]] as Anna Jones\n* [[Mary Ellen Trainor]] as Vivian Adams\n* [[Susan Kellermann]] as ER nurse\n* [[William Frankfather]] as Mr. Roy Franklin\n* [[John Ingle]] as Eulogist\n* [[Debra Jo Rupp]] as Patient\n* [[Fabio Lanzoni|Fabio]] as Lisle's bodyguard\n* [[Sydney Pollack]] as Emergency Department Doctor (uncredited){{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Special effects===\n''Death Becomes Her'' was a technologically complex movie to make, and represented a major advancement in the use of [[computer generated imagery|computer-generated]] effects, under the pioneering direction of [[Industrial Light and Magic]].<ref name=\"ilm.com\">{{cite web| url=https://www.ilm.com/vfx/death-becomes-her/| title=Death Becomes Her (Universal Pictures)| publisher=ilm.com| access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite article| url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1992-08-21/features/9201170039_1_roger-rabbit-special-effects-director-robert-zemeckis| title=Special Effects, Acting Bring 'Death' to Life| author=Judd Blaise| publisher=Sun Sentinel| date=1992-08-21|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> For example, it was the first film where computer-generated skin texture was used, in the shot where Madeline resets her neck after her head is smashed with a shovel by Helen.<ref name=\"ilm.com\"/> Creating the sequences where Madeline's head is dislocated and facing the wrong way around involved a combination of [[blue screen technology]], an [[animatronic]] model created by [[Amalgamated Dynamics]], and prosthetic make-up effects on Meryl Streep to create the look of a twisted neck.<ref>{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xRNVHaaUAp8| title=Death Becomes Her (1992) Vintage Bonus Clip: Meryl's Mom & Special Effects (HD)| | publisher=Youtube| date=2016-06-23| access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fIgJgGOEahk| title=DEATH BECOMES HER Recreating Meryl BTS Special Edition| author=Amalgamated Dynamics Inc.| publisher=Youtube| date=2015-07-25| access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref>\n\nThe digital advancements pioneered on ''Death Becomes Her'' would be incorporated into Industrial Light and Magic's next project, ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]'', released by Universal only a year later. Both films shared cinematographer [[Dean Cundey]] and production designer [[Rick Carter]], in addition to ILM.<ref>{{cite article| url=http://www.indiewire.com/2013/06/5-versions-of-jurassic-park-you-never-saw-97110/| title=5 Versions of 'Jurassic Park' You Never Saw| author=Drew Taylor| publisher=indiewire.com| date=2013-06-11| access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref>\n\nThe production had a fair number of mishaps. For example, in a scene where Helen Sharp and Madeline Ashton are battling with shovels, [[Meryl Streep]] accidentally cut [[Goldie Hawn]]'s face, leaving a faint scar. Streep admitted that she disliked working on a project that focused so heavily on special effects, saying:\n\n{{cquote|My first, my last, my only. I think it's tedious. Whatever concentration you can apply to that kind of comedy is just shredded. You stand there like a piece of machinery\u2014they should get machinery to do it. I loved how it turned out. But it's not fun to act to a lampstand. \"Pretend this is Goldie, right here! Uh, no, I'm sorry, Bob, she went off the mark by five centimeters, and now her head won't match her neck!\" It was like being at the dentist.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,275733_4,00.html |date=2000-03-24 |title=Depth Becomes Her |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=2007-01-25}}</ref>}}\n\n===Filming locations===\nThe film was made entirely in [[Los Angeles]] and used several locations also frequently used in film and television, including the [[Greystone Mansion]] (Ernest's funeral home) and the [[Ebell of Los Angeles]] (Helen's book party).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://ebellla.org/filming/| title=The Ebell of Los Angeles - Filming| publisher=ebellla.org| access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> The exterior of Madeline and Ernest's mansion is located at 1125 Oak Grove Avenue in [[San Marino, California|San Marino]], but the interior was a set built on a soundstage.<ref>{{cite article| url=http://www.iamnotastalker.com/2017/10/13/madeline-and-ernests-mansion-from-death-becomes-her/| title=Madeline and Ernest's Mansion from 'Death Becomes Her'| publisher=iamnotastalker.com| date=2017-10-13| access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|sure=yes|date=March 2018}} The ending scene where Helen and Madeline tumble down a set of stairs outside a chapel was filmed at [[Mount St. Mary's University (Los Angeles)]] in [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://moviemaps.org/locations/87| title=Movies Filmed at Mount Saint Mary's University - Chalon Campus| publisher=moviemaps.org| access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref>\n\n===Editing===\nThe theatrical version of ''Death Becomes Her'' omitted or shortened many scenes featured in the rough cut of the movie.<ref name=\"SS\">{{cite web| url=http://www.simplystreep.com/content/career/films/1992deathbecomesher.html| title=Death Becomes Her| publisher=simplystreep.com| access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=March 2018}} Robert Zemeckis decided this was needed to accelerate the pace of the film and eliminate extraneous jokes. Most dramatically, the original ending was entirely redone after test audiences reacted negatively to it.<ref>{{cite article| url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/07/31/death-becomes-her-25th-anniversary-12-things-you-may-not-know-about-the-classic-comedy-6808575/| title=Death Become Her 25th Anniversary: 12 things you may not know about the classic comedy| author=Jon O'Brien| publisher=metro.co.uk| date=2017-07-31| access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref> The ending featured Ernest, after he has fled Lisle's party, meeting a bartender ([[Tracey Ullman]]), who helps him fake his death to evade Madeline and Helen. The two women encounter Ernest and the bartender 27 years later, living happily as a retired couple.<ref name=\"LAT\">{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-08-09/entertainment/ca-6132_1_ullman-ending| title=A look inside Hollywood and the movies.: THE VANISHING: 'Death Becomes Her' and the Lost Ullman Ending| author=David J. Fox| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| date=1992-08-09| access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref> Zemeckis thought the ending was too happy and opted for the darker ending featured in the final cut.<ref name=\"LAT\"/> Ullman was one of five actors with speaking roles in the film to be eliminated.<ref name=\"LAT\"/> Other scenes that were eliminated included one in which Madeline talks to her agent ([[Jonathan Silverman]]) and one in which Ernest removes a frozen Madeline from the kitchen freezer he has stored her in.<ref name=\"SS\"/> None of the scenes have been released publicly, but sequences can still be viewed in the original theatrical trailer.<ref>{{cite video| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0jPuZLUY4II| title=Death Becomes Her (1992) Meryl Streep, Bruce Willis - Official Trailer (HD)| publisher=YouTube.com| date=2016-04-11| access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Anchor|Score|Soundtrack}} \nThe score was composed by American film composer [[Alan Silvestri]], who also composed scores of other films directed by Zemeckis.<ref>{{cite web |title=10 of the Most Underrated Horror Scores! |url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/20063/ |accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Release and reception==\n\nThe film opened at number one at the box office with $12,110,355 on the same weekend as and ahead of ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (film)|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'' and ''[[Bebe's Kids]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title= Weekend Box Office `Honors' Tops in a Lackluster Bunch|newspaper= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=1994-05-10|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1994-05-10/entertainment/ca-56005_1_weekend-box-office|accessdate=2010-12-28|first=Robert W.|last=Welkos}}</ref> It went on to earn over $58.4&nbsp;million domestically and $90.6&nbsp;million internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=deathbecomesher.htm|title=Death Becomes Her (1992) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref>\n\nThe film's release on DVD was called \"appallingly bad\",<ref name=\"Michael\">{{cite web|url=http://www.michaeldvd.com.au/Reviews/DeathBecomesHer.asp|title=Death Becomes Her|publisher=Michael Demtschyna|accessdate=November 13, 2012}}</ref> \"horrible\" and \"sloppy\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/10/12/death_becomes_her_1992_dvd_review.shtml|title=BBC - Films - review - Death Becomes Her DVD|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=November 13, 2012}}</ref> due to the quality of its transfer, which has been said to suffer from excessive grain, blur, and muted colors.<ref name=\"Michael\"/> Many online DVD forum users speculated that the DVD transfer was taken from the [[Laserdisc]] edition of the film and called for a restorative release. The film was initially distributed in an open-matte, [[4:3|fullscreen]] edition with an aspect ratio of [[Aspect ratio (image)|1.33:1]] in the United States before a widescreen version with its intended ratio ([[Aspect ratio (image)|1.85:1]]) was released and subsequently distributed worldwide. The latter version has also been mistakenly labelled [[Anamorphic widescreen|anamorphic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guidohenkel.com/2012/07/a-stroll-down-the-dvd-memory-lane/|title=A stroll down the DVD memory lane: Guido Henkel|publisher=Guido Henkel|accessdate=November 13, 2012}}</ref> It was later released in North America on [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] from [[Shout Factory]] on April 26, 2016.\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film received mixed reviews.<ref>{{cite news|title=Death Becomes Her|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1992-07-26|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117901657.html|accessdate=2010-10-03|first=Todd|last=McCarthy}}{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Death Becomes Her|work= [[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=1992-08-14|url= http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,311403,00.html|accessdate=2010-10-03}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a rating of 52% based on reviews from 48 critics with the consensus: \"Hawn and Streep are as fabulous as ''Death Becomes Her''{{'}}s innovative special effects; Zemeckis' satire, on the other hand, is as hollow as the world it mocks.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Death Becomes Her (1992)|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/death_becomes_her/|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url=https://m.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Gene Siskel]] and [[Roger Ebert]] both gave the film a 'thumbs down', commenting that while the film had great special effects, it lacked any real substance or character depth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/atm/reviews.html?sec=1&subsec=759|title=''Death Becomes Her'' review}}{{dead link|date=September 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Anchor|Awards and nominations}}\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2011}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|- valign=\"bottom\"\n! Award\n! Role\n! Result\n|-\n| [[Academy Awards]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award]]\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Special Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]] (Meryl Streep)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=9| [[Saturn Award]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Fantasy Film|Best Fantasy Film]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Director|Best Director]] (Robert Zemeckis)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Writing|Best Writing]] (Martin Donovan, David Koepp)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] (Bruce Willis)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] (Meryl Streep)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Music|Best Music]] (Alan Silvestri)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Make-up|Best Make-up]] (Dick Smith, Kevin Haney)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] (Isabella Rossellini)\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Special Effects|Best Special Effects]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n===Legacy===\n''Death Becomes Her'' has acquired a significant cult following, especially in the [[LGBT]] community.<ref name=\"Julia Pugachevsky\">{{cite article| url=http://www.newnownext.com/newnownext-style-death-becomes-her-is-ruling-our-lives-and-our-wardrobes/06/2013/| title=\"Death Becomes Her\" Is Ruling Our Lives: NewNowNext Style| author=Julia Pugachevsky| publisher=newnownext.com| date=2013-06-21| access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref> An article in ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' titled \"The Gloriously Queer Afterlife of 'Death Becomes Her'\" called the film a \"gay cult classic\" and \"a touchstone of the queer community\".<ref name=\"Kristy Puchko\">{{cite magazine| url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/08/death-becomes-her-25th-anniversary-meryl-streep-goldie-hawn-gay-classic| title=The Glorious Queer Afterlife of 'Death Becomes Her'| author=Kristy Puchko| magazine=Vanity Fair| date=2017-08-03| access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref> The movie is screened in bars during [[LGBT Pride Month|Pride Month]], while the characters of Madeline and Helen are favorites of drag performers. In this vein, the movie inspired a ''Death Becomes Her''-themed runway show on [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 7)|season 7]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]''.<ref name=\"Julia Pugachevsky\"/> The winner of season 5, [[Jinkx Monsoon]], has cited the movie as an inspiration to become a drag queen. They have participated in ''Death Becomes Her''-themed photoshoots,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/17/death-becomes-jinkx_n_3287753.html| title=Jinkx Monsoon and Ivy Winters Star in Ricky Middlesworth's 'Death Becomes Her' (PHOTOS)| author=Christopher Rudolph| work=Huffington Post| date=2013-05-17| access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref> and in 2018 they played Madeline in a drag stage show parody called \"Drag Becomes Her\".<ref>{{cite article| url=https://www.todaytix.com/insider/los-angeles/posts/jinkx-monsoon-talks-spoofing-meryl-streep-in-drag-becomes-her| title=Jinkx Monsoon Talks Spoofing Meryl Streep in 'Drag Becomes Her'| author=Ashley Lee| publisher=todaytix.com| date=2018-04-19| access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\nTom Campbell, an executive producer of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'', reflected on the appeal of the movie to gay audiences: {{cquote|They're fighting for beauty. They're against the system. They're also villains, but we understand their complexity. We root for the undead divas because they're trying to win a game that's rigged against them, and\u2014to borrow an apocryphal quote from [[Ginger Rogers]]\u2014they sort of have to do it 'backwards and in high heels.'<ref name=\"Kristy Puchko\"/>}}\n\nIn December 2017, [[Kristin Chenoweth]] was announced to be starring in a Broadway musical adaptation of ''Death Becomes Her''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/death-becomes-her-musical_us_5a316aaee4b07ff75affb6a4|title='Death Becomes Her' is About to Become a Broadway Musical| author=Curtis M. Wong| work=Huffington Post| date=2017-12-13| access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Death Becomes Her}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0104070|title=Death Becomes Her}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=19219|title=Death Becomes Her}}\n\n{{Robert Zemeckis}}\n\n[[Category:1990s black comedy films]]\n[[Category:1992 films]]\n[[Category:American black comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert Zemeckis]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Alan Silvestri]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1978]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1985]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1992]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2029]]\n[[Category:Films set in country houses]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Visual Effects Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Fiction about immortality]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by David Koepp]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "2601:18a:0:9070:d9e2:3846:cae8:478d", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Death_Becomes_Her"}
{"title_page": "Indiana State Road 121", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|state=IN\n|type=IN\n|route=121\n|map=Map of Indiana State Road 121.svg\n|length_mi=19.503\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"indot\"/>\n|established=\n|section1=Southern segment\n|length_mi1=15.296\n|length_ref1=<ref name=\"indot\"/>\n|direction_a1=South\n|terminus_a1={{Jct|state=IN|US|52}}\n|direction_b1=North\n|terminus_b1={{Jct|state=IN|SR|44}} in [[Connersville, Indiana|Connersville]]\n|section2=Northern segment\n|length_mi2=4.207\n|length_ref2=<ref name=\"indot\"/>\n|direction_a2=South\n|terminus_a2={{Jct|state=IN|US|27|SR|227}} in [[Richmond, Indiana|Richmond]]\n|direction_b2=North\n|terminus_b2={{Jct|state=OH|OH|121}}\n|counties=[[Fayette County, Indiana|Fayette]], [[Franklin County, Indiana|Franklin]], [[Wayne County, Indiana|Wayne]]\n|previous_type=IN\n|previous_route=120\n|next_type=IN\n|next_route=124\n}}\n\n'''State Road 121''' ('''SR&nbsp;121''') is a part of the [[Indiana State Road]] that exists in two sections. The first  runs between [[Metamora, Indiana|Metamora]] and [[Connersville, Indiana|Connersville]] and the second from [[Richmond, Indiana|Richmond]] to the Ohio state line in US state of [[Indiana]].  The {{convert| 19.52 |mi|km|2}} of SR&nbsp;121 that lie within Indiana serve as a minor highway. None of the highway is listed on the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]]. The entire route is rural two-lane highway that passes through farmland, residential and commercial properties.\n\n==Route description==\nNo segment of State Road 121 in Indiana is included in the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]] (NHS).<ref name=\"NHS Map of Indiana\">{{INDOT ref|title=NHS Map|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref>  The NHS is a network of highways that are identified as being most important for the economy, mobility and defense of the nation.<ref name=NHS>{{INDOT ref|title=NHS|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref> The highway is maintained by the [[Indiana Department of Transportation]] (INDOT) like all other state roads in the state. The department tracks the traffic volumes along all state roads as a part of its maintenance responsibilities using a metric called [[average annual daily traffic]] (AADT). This measurement is a calculation of the traffic level along a segment of roadway for any average day of the year. In 2010, INDOT figured that lowest traffic levels were 1,170&nbsp;vehicles and 40&nbsp;commercial vehicles used the highway daily at the Franklin\u2013Fayette County line. The peak traffic volumes were 9,470&nbsp;vehicles and 260&nbsp;commercial vehicles AADT along the section of SR&nbsp;121 that is concurrent with SR&nbsp;227, on North&nbsp;J&nbsp;Street in Richmond.<ref name=\"AADT\">{{INDOT ref|title=Traffic Counts|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Southern segment===\nThe southern segment of SR&nbsp;121 begins at US&nbsp;52 and heads north as a rural two-lane curvy highway. The highway passes through most farmland and enters the town of [[Laurel, Indiana|Laurel]], making a few sharp curves. The route passes through residential properties through town and makes another set of sharp curves leaving town. The highway heads northeast towards [[Connersville, Indiana|Connersville]], on the way passing through farmland. The route enters Connersville from the southwest concurrent with Grand Avenue. The highway passes through residential and commercial properties, before ending at [[Indiana State Road 44|SR&nbsp;44]].<ref name=\"google maps #1\">{{google maps|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=IN-121+N&daddr=N+Grand+Ave&hl=en&ll=39.520463,-85.170822&spn=0.31145,0.572662&sll=39.639719,-85.141693&sspn=0.004858,0.008948&geocode=FXj5WQIdwDrs-g%3BFczbXAIdCdXs-g&t=h&mra=me&mrsp=1,0&sz=17&z=11|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"INDOT 2012\">{{INDOT map|year=2012|section=J10 & H10}}</ref>\n\n===Northern segment===\nThe northern segment of SR&nbsp;121 begins at an intersection between [[U.S. Route 27 in Indiana|US&nbsp;27]] and [[Indiana State Road 227|SR&nbsp;227]], just north of downtown Richmond. SR&nbsp;121 heads east concurrent with SR&nbsp;227, on North&nbsp;J&nbsp;Street. The two state roads leaves J&nbsp;Street for Middleboro Pike and heads northeast. The concurrent with SR&nbsp;227 ends when SR&nbsp;121 turns east onto New Paris Pike. The highway heads mostly east towards [[New Paris, Ohio]] and crosses over [[Interstate 70 in Indiana|Interstate 70]] on the way. SR&nbsp;121 ends at the Ohio state line and becomes [[Ohio State Route 121]].<ref name=\"google maps #2\">{{google maps|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=N+J+St&daddr=IN-121+N%2FNew+Paris+Pike&hl=en&ll=39.851116,-84.817886&spn=0.019373,0.035791&sll=39.852401,-84.820204&sspn=0.019372,0.035791&geocode=FWLrXwIdWLLw-g%3BFdgQYAIdQNjx-g&mra=me&mrsp=1,0&sz=15&t=m&z=15|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"INDOT 2012\"/>\n\n==History==\nSR 121 was commissioned in 1931 routed between Richmond and the Ohio state line. In 1932 a second segment was added to the state road system routed between US 52 and Connersville. The northern segment at the time of commissioning was a hard driving surface and the southern segment was a dirt driving surface.<ref name=map1930>{{INDOT map|year=1931|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=map1931>{{INDOT map|year=1931|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=1932-1>{{INDOT map|year=1932-1|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=1932-9>{{INDOT map|year=1932-9|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref> Between 1966 and 1967 the southern segment of SR 121 within Fayette County was paved.<ref name=1966map>{{INDOT map|year=1966|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=1967map>{{INDOT map|year=1967|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref> By 1970 the rest of SR 121, the section within Franklin County, was paved.<ref name=1969map>{{INDOT map|year=1969|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=1970map>{{INDOT map|year=1970|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{Jcttop|length_ref=<ref name=\"indot\">{{INDOT ref|title=RPB-2016 |access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{INint\n|county=Franklin\n|location=Laurel Township\n|ctdab=Franklin\n|mile=0.000\n|road={{jct|state=IN|US|52|city2=Rushville|city1=Brookville}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of SR&nbsp;121}}\n{{INint\n|county=Fayette\n|location=Connersville\n|road={{jct|state=IN|SR|44|city1=Rushville|city2=Liberty}}\n|mile=15.296\n|notes=Northern terminus of the southern section of SR&nbsp;121}}\n{{Jctgap}}\n{{INint\n|county=Wayne\n|cspan=3\n|location=Richmond\n|lspan=2\n|mile=15.297\n|road={{jct|state=IN|US|27|SR|227|dir2=south|city1=Winchester|city2=Liberty|city3=Boston}}\n|type=concur\n|notes=Southern terminus of the southern section of SR&nbsp;121; Western end of SR&nbsp;227 concurrency}}\n{{INint\n|road={{jct|state=IN|SR|227|city1=Union City|dir1=north}}\n|type=concur\n|mile=15.744\n|notes=Eastern end of SR&nbsp;227 concurrncy}}\n{{INint\n|location=Wayne Township\n|ctdab=Wayne\n|mile=19.503\n|road={{Jct|state=OH|OH|121|location1=[[Greenville, Ohio|Greenville]] ([[Ohio]])}}|dir1=north}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of SR&nbsp;121}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120324015439/http://highwayexplorer.com/EndsPage.php?id=1121&section=1 Indiana Highway Ends - SR 121]\n\n[[Category:State highways in Indiana|121]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Fayette County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Franklin County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Wayne County, Indiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n|state=IN\n|type=IN\n|route=121\n|map=Map of Indiana State Road 121.svg\n|length_mi=19.503\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"indot\"/>\n|established=\n|section1=Southern segment\n|length_mi1=15.296\n|length_ref1=<ref name=\"indot\"/>\n|direction_a1=South\n|terminus_a1={{Jct|state=IN|US|52}}\n|direction_b1=North\n|terminus_b1={{Jct|state=IN|SR|44}} in [[Connersville, Indiana|Connersville]]\n|section2=Northern segment\n|length_mi2=4.207\n|length_ref2=<ref name=\"indot\"/>\n|direction_a2=South\n|terminus_a2={{Jct|state=IN|US|27|SR|227}} in [[Richmond, Indiana|Richmond]]\n|direction_b2=North\n|terminus_b2={{Jct|state=OH|OH|121}}\n|counties=[[Fayette County, Indiana|Fayette]], [[Franklin County, Indiana|Franklin]], [[Wayne County, Indiana|Wayne]]\n|previous_type=IN\n|previous_route=120\n|next_type=IN\n|next_route=124\n}}\n\n'''State Road 121''' ('''SR&nbsp;121''') is a part of the [[Indiana State Road]] that exists in two sections. The first  runs between [[Metamora, Indiana|Metamora]] and [[Connersville, Indiana|Connersville]] and the second from [[Richmond, Indiana|Richmond]] to the Ohio state line in US state of [[Indiana]].  The {{convert| 19.52 |mi|km|2}} of SR&nbsp;121 that lie within Indiana serve as a minor highway. None of the highway is listed on the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]]. The entire route is rural two-lane highway that passes through farmland, residential and commercial properties.\n\n==Route description==\nNo segment of State Road 121 in Indiana is included in the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]] (NHS).<ref name=\"NHS Map of Indiana\">{{INDOT ref|title=NHS Map|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref>  The NHS is a network of highways that are identified as being most important for the economy, mobility and defense of the nation.<ref name=NHS>{{INDOT ref|title=NHS|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref> The highway is maintained by the [[Indiana Department of Transportation]] (INDOT) like all other state roads in the state. The department tracks the traffic volumes along all state roads as a part of its maintenance responsibilities using a metric called [[average annual daily traffic]] (AADT). This measurement is a calculation of the traffic level along a segment of roadway for any average day of the year. In 2010, INDOT figured that lowest traffic levels were 1,170&nbsp;vehicles and 40&nbsp;commercial vehicles used the highway daily at the Franklin\u2013Fayette County line. The peak traffic volumes were 9,470&nbsp;vehicles and 260&nbsp;commercial vehicles AADT along the section of SR&nbsp;121 that is concurrent with SR&nbsp;227, on North&nbsp;J&nbsp;Street in Richmond.<ref name=\"AADT\">{{INDOT ref|title=Traffic Counts|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Southern segment===\nThe southern segment of SR&nbsp;121 begins at US&nbsp;52 and heads north as a rural two-lane curvy highway. The highway passes through most farmland and enters the town of [[Laurel, Indiana|Laurel]], making a few sharp curves. The route passes through residential properties through town and makes another set of sharp curves leaving town. The highway heads northeast towards [[Connersville, Indiana|Connersville]], on the way passing through farmland. The route enters Connersville from the southwest concurrent with Grand Avenue. The highway passes through residential and commercial properties, before ending at [[Indiana State Road 44|SR&nbsp;44]].<ref name=\"google maps #1\">{{google maps|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=IN-121+N&daddr=N+Grand+Ave&hl=en&ll=39.520463,-85.170822&spn=0.31145,0.572662&sll=39.639719,-85.141693&sspn=0.004858,0.008948&geocode=FXj5WQIdwDrs-g%3BFczbXAIdCdXs-g&t=h&mra=me&mrsp=1,0&sz=17&z=11|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"INDOT 2012\">{{INDOT map|year=2012|section=J10 & H10}}</ref>\n\n===Northern segment===\nThe northern segment of SR&nbsp;121 begins at an intersection between [[U.S. Route 27 in Indiana|US&nbsp;27]] and [[Indiana State Road 227|SR&nbsp;227]], just north of downtown Richmond. SR&nbsp;121 heads east concurrent with SR&nbsp;227, on North&nbsp;J&nbsp;Street. The two state roads leaves J&nbsp;Street for Middleboro Pike and heads northeast. The concurrent with SR&nbsp;227 ends when SR&nbsp;121 turns east onto New Paris Pike. The highway heads mostly east towards [[New Paris, Ohio]] and crosses over [[Interstate 70 in Indiana|Interstate 70]] on the way. SR&nbsp;121 ends at the Ohio state line and becomes [[Ohio State Route 121]].<ref name=\"google maps #2\">{{google maps|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=N+J+St&daddr=IN-121+N%2FNew+Paris+Pike&hl=en&ll=39.851116,-84.817886&spn=0.019373,0.035791&sll=39.852401,-84.820204&sspn=0.019372,0.035791&geocode=FWLrXwIdWLLw-g%3BFdgQYAIdQNjx-g&mra=me&mrsp=1,0&sz=15&t=m&z=15|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"INDOT 2012\"/>\n\n==History==\nSR 121 was commissioned in 1931 routed between Richmond and the Ohio state line. In 1932 a second segment was added to the state road system routed between US 52 and Connersville. The northern segment at the time of commissioning was a hard driving surface and the southern segment was a dirt driving surface.<ref name=map1930>{{INDOT map|year=1931|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=map1931>{{INDOT map|year=1931|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=1932-1>{{INDOT map|year=1932-1|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=1932-9>{{INDOT map|year=1932-9|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref> Between 1966 and 1967 the southern segment of SR 121 within Fayette County was paved.<ref name=1966map>{{INDOT map|year=1966|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=1967map>{{INDOT map|year=1967|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref> By 1970 the rest of SR 121, the section within Franklin County, was paved.<ref name=1969map>{{INDOT map|year=1969|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=1970map>{{INDOT map|year=1970|access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{Jcttop|length_ref=<ref name=\"indot\">{{INDOT ref|title=RPB-2016 |access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{INint\n|county=Franklin\n|location=Laurel Township\n|ctdab=Franklin\n|mile=0.000\n|road={{jct|state=IN|US|52|city2=Rushville|city1=Brookville}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of SR&nbsp;121}}\n{{INint\n|county=Fayette\n|location=Connersville\n|road={{jct|state=IN|SR|44|city1=Rushville|city2=Liberty}}\n|mile=15.296\n|notes=Northern terminus of the southern section of SR&nbsp;121}}\n{{Jctgap}}\n{{INint\n|county=Wayne\n|cspan=3\n|location=Richmond\n|lspan=2\n|mile=15.297\n|road={{jct|state=IN|US|27|SR|227|dir2=south}}\n|type=concur\n|notes=Southern terminus of the southern section of SR&nbsp;121; Western end of SR&nbsp;227 concurrency}}\n{{INint\n|road={{jct|state=IN|SR|227|dir1=north}}\n|type=concur\n|mile=15.744\n|notes=Eastern end of SR&nbsp;227 concurrncy}}\n{{INint\n|location=Wayne Township\n|ctdab=Wayne\n|mile=19.503\n|road={{Jct|state=OH|OH|121|dir1=north}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of SR&nbsp;121}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120324015439/http://highwayexplorer.com/EndsPage.php?id=1121&section=1 Indiana Highway Ends - SR 121]\n\n[[Category:State highways in Indiana|121]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Fayette County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Franklin County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Wayne County, Indiana]]\n", "name_user": "74.215.85.134", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eMajor intersections)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indiana_State_Road_121"}
{"title_page": "Sonja Henie", "text_new": "{{short description|Norwegian figure skater}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2017}}<!--many paragraphs have no citations-->\n{{distinguish|text=American basketball player [[Sonja Henning]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox figure skater\n|name                = Sonja Henie\n|image               =Sonja Henie 1936.jpg\n|caption             =Henie at the 1936 Olympics\n|fullname            = Sonja Henie\n|altname             = \n|country             = \n|formercountry       =\n|birth_date          = {{birth date|df=yes|1912|4|8}}\n|birth_place         = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n|hometown            =\n|residence           = \n|death_date          =  {{death date and age|df=yes|1969|10|12|1912|4|8}}\n|death_place         = en route to [[Oslo, Norway]]\n| height = {{convert|1.55|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|formerpartner       = [[Jack Dunn (figure skater)|Jack Dunn]] <br/> [[Stewart Reburn]]\n|coach               = \n|formercoach         = Howard Nicholson \n|choreographer       =\n|formerchoreographer =\n|skating club        = Oslo SK\n|retired             = \n|medaltemplates      = <!-- see [[Template:MedalRelatedTemplates]] -->\n{{MedalCountry | {{NOR}}}}\n{{MedalSport | Ladies' [[Figure skating]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Winter Olympic Games|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1928 Winter Olympics|1928 St. Moritz]]|[[Figure skating at the 1928 Winter Olympics \u2013 Ladies' singles|Singles]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1932 Winter Olympics|1932 Lake Placid]]|[[Figure skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Ladies' singles|Singles]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1936 Winter Olympics|1936 Garmisch-Partenkirchen]]|[[Figure skating at the 1936 Winter Olympics \u2013 Ladies' singles|Singles]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Figure Skating Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1927 World Figure Skating Championships|1927 Oslo]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1928 World Figure Skating Championships|1928 London]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1929 World Figure Skating Championships|1929 Budapest]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1930 World Figure Skating Championships|1930 New York]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1931 World Figure Skating Championships|1931 Berlin]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1932 World Figure Skating Championships|1932 Montreal]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1933 World Figure Skating Championships|1933 Stockholm]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1934 World Figure Skating Championships|1934 Oslo]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1935 World Figure Skating Championships|1935 Vienna]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1936 World Figure Skating Championships|1936 Paris]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1926 World Figure Skating Championships|1926 Stockholm]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Figure Skating Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1931 European Figure Skating Championships|1931 St. Moritz]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1932 European Figure Skating Championships|1932 Paris]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1933 European Figure Skating Championships|1933 London]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1934 European Figure Skating Championships|1934 Prague]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1935 European Figure Skating Championships|1935 St. Moritz]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1936 European Figure Skating Championships|1936 Berlin]]|Singles}}\n}}\n\n'''Sonja Henie''' (8 April 1912 \u2013 12 October 1969) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[figure skating|figure skater]] and film star. She was a three-time [[List of Olympic medalists in figure skating|Olympic Champion]] ([[Figure skating at the 1928 Winter Olympics|1928]], [[Figure skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics|1932]], [[Figure skating at the 1936 Winter Olympics|1936]]) in women's Singles, a ten-time [[World Figure Skating Championships|World Champion]] (1927\u20131936) and a six-time [[European Figure Skating Championships|European Champion]] (1931\u20131936). Henie won more Olympic and World titles than any other ladies' figure skater. At the height of her acting career, she was one of the highest-paid stars in [[Cinema in the United States|Hollywood]] and starred in a series of box-office hits, including ''[[Thin Ice (1937 film)|Thin Ice]]'' (1937), [[Happy Landing (1938 film)]], ''[[My Lucky Star (1938 film)|My Lucky Star]]'' (1938), ''[[Second Fiddle (1939 film)|Second Fiddle]]'' (1939) and ''[[Sun Valley Serenade]]'' (1941).<ref>[http://www.snl.no/Sonja_Henie '&#39;Sonja Henie'&#39; (Store norske leksikon)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008193416/http://snl.no/Sonja_Henie |date=8 October 2012 }}. Snl.no (13 March 2014). Retrieved on 19 August 2015.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nHenie was born in 1912 in Kristiania (now [[Oslo]]) Norway; she was the only daughter of [[Wilhelm Henie]] (1872\u20131937), a prosperous Norwegian [[fur clothing|furrier]], and his wife, Selma Lochmann-Nielsen (1888\u20131961). In addition to the income from the fur business, both of Henie's parents had inherited wealth. Wilhelm Henie had been a one-time [[UCI Track Cycling World Championships|World Cycling Champion]] and the Henie children were encouraged to take up a variety of sports at a young age. Henie initially showed talent at [[skiing]], then followed her older brother, Leif, to take up [[figure skating]]. As a girl Henie also was a nationally ranked [[tennis]] player, and a skilled [[swimming (sport)|swimmer]] and [[equestrianism|equestrienne]]. Once Henie began serious training as a figure skater, her formal schooling ended. She was educated by tutors, and her father hired the best experts in the world, including the famous Russian ballerina, [[Tamara Karsavina]], to transform his daughter into a sporting celebrity.<ref>[http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Sonja_Henie/utdypning '&#39;Sonja Henie/utdypning'&#39; (Store norske leksikon)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008193424/http://snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Sonja_Henie/utdypning |date=8 October 2012 }}. Snl.no. Retrieved on 19 August 2015.</ref>\n\n===Competitive career===\nHenie won her first major competition, the senior Norwegian championships, at the age of 10. She then placed eighth in a field of eight at the [[1924 Winter Olympics]], at the age of eleven.<ref name=sr>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/he/sonja-henie-1.html Sonja Heni] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100309082541/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/he/sonja-henie-1.html |date=9 March 2010 }}. sports-reference.com</ref> During the 1924 program, she skated over to the side of the rink several times to ask her coach for directions, but by the next Olympiad, she needed no such assistance.\n\nHenie won the first of an unprecedented ten consecutive World Figure Skating Championships in 1927 at the age of fourteen. The results of 1927 World Championships, where Henie won in 3\u20132 decision (or 7 vs. 8 ordinal points) over the defending Olympic and World Champion [[Herma Szabo]] of [[Austria]], was controversial, as three of the five judges that gave Henie first-place ordinals were Norwegian (1 + 1 + 1 + 2 + 2 = 7 points) while Szabo received first-place ordinals from an Austrian and a German Judge (1 + 1 + 2 + 2 + 2 = 8 points). Henie went on to win first of her three [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] gold medals the following year, became one of the [[List of Olympic medalists in figure skating by age#Youngest champions|youngest]] figure skating Olympic champions. She defended her Olympic titles in 1932 and in 1936, and her world titles annually until 1936.<ref name=sr/> She also won six consecutive European championships from 1931 to 1936. Henie's unprecedented three Olympic gold medals haven't been matched by any ladies' single skater since; neither are her achievements as ten-time consecutive World Champion. While [[Irina Slutskaya]] of Russia won her seventh European Championship in 2006 to become the most successful ladies' skater in European Championships, Henie retains record of most consecutive titles, sharing it with [[Katarina Witt]] of [[Eastern Germany]]/[[Germany]] (1983\u20131988).\n\nTowards the end of her career, she began to be strongly challenged by younger skaters including [[Cecilia Colledge]], [[Megan Taylor]], and [[Hedy Stenuf]]. However, she held off these competitors and went on to win her third Olympic title at the [[1936 Winter Olympics]], albeit in very controversial circumstances with Cecilia Colledge finishing a very close second. Indeed, after the school figures section at the 1936 Olympic competition, Colledge and Henie were virtually neck and neck with Colledge trailing by just a few points. As Sandra Stevenson recounted in her article in ''[[The Independent]]'' of 21 April 2008, \"the closeness [of the competition] infuriated Henie, who, when the result for that section was posted on a wall in the competitors' lounge, swiped the piece of paper and tore it into little pieces. The draw for the free skating [then] came under suspicion after Henie landed the plum position of skating last, while Colledge had to perform second of the 26 competitors. The early start was seen as a disadvantage, with the audience not yet whipped into a clapping frenzy and the judges known to become freer with their higher marks as the event proceeded. Years later, a fairer, staggered draw was adopted to counteract this situation\".\n\nDuring her competitive career, Henie traveled widely and worked with a variety of foreign coaches. At home in Oslo, she trained at [[Frogner|Frogner Stadium]], where her coaches included Hj\u00f8rdis Olsen and Oscar Holte. During the latter part of her competitive career she was coached primarily by the American Howard Nicholson in [[London]]. In addition to traveling to train and compete, she was much in demand as a performer at figure skating exhibitions in both Europe and North America. Henie became so popular with the public that police had to be called out for crowd control on her appearances in various disparate cities such as [[Prague]] and [[New York City]]. It was an open secret that, in spite of the strict [[amateur sports|amateurism]] requirements of the time, Wilhelm Henie demanded \"expense money\" for his daughter's skating appearances. Both of Henie's parents had given up their own pursuits in Norway\u2014leaving Leif to run the fur business\u2014in order to accompany Sonja on her travels and act as her managers.\n\nHenie is credited with being the first figure skater to adopt the short skirt costume in figure skating, wear white boots,<ref name=\"Jacobs\">{{cite news |last1=Jacobs |first1=Laura |title=Sonja Henie's Ice Age |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/02/sonja-henie-ice-skating-queen |accessdate=3 September 2018 |work=Vanity Fair |date=11 February 2014}}</ref> and make use of dance [[choreography]]. Her innovative skating techniques and glamorous demeanor transformed the sport permanently and confirmed its acceptance as a legitimate sport in the Winter Olympics.<ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/siforwomen/top_100/4/ ''100 Greatest Female Athletes''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060911201834/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/siforwomen/top_100/4/ |date=11 September 2006 }} (''Sports Illustrated'')</ref>\n\n===Professional and film career===\n[[File:Sonja Henie on Time Magazine 1939.jpg|right|thumb|Sonja Henie appeared on the cover of [[Time (magazine)|''Time'' magazine]] on July 17, 1939.]]\n\nAfter the 1936 [[World Figure Skating Championships]], Henie gave up her amateur status and took up a career as a professional performer in acting and live shows.<ref name=sr/> While still a girl, Henie had decided that she wanted to move to [[California]] and become a movie star when her competitive days were over, without considering that her thick accent might hinder her acting ambitions.\n\nIn 1936, following a successful ice show in [[Los Angeles]] orchestrated by her father to launch her film career, Hollywood studio chief [[Darryl Zanuck]] signed her to a long term contract at [[Twentieth Century Fox]], which made her one of the highest-paid actresses of the time. After the success of her first film, ''[[One in a Million (1936 film)|One in a Million]]'' (1936), Henie's position was assured and she became increasingly demanding in her business dealings with Zanuck. Henie also insisted on having total control of the skating numbers in her films such as ''[[Second Fiddle (1939 film)|Second Fiddle]]'' (1939).\n\nHenie tried to break the musical comedy mould with the anti-Nazi film ''[[Everything Happens at Night]]'' (1939) and ''[[It's a Pleasure (film)|It's a Pleasure]]'' (1945), a skating variation of the often-told ''[[A Star Is Born (1937 film)|A Star Is Born]]'' tale about alcoholic-star-in-decline-helps-newcomer-up. It was her only film shot in [[Technicolor]], but it was not as huge at the box office as her other films and also proved her limitations as a dramatic actress in her one only dramatic film.\n\nWhen Zanuck realized her limits in the pseudo-dramatic vein, he cast her in more musical comedies; ''[[Sun Valley Serenade]]'' (1941) with [[Glenn Miller]], [[John Payne (actor)|John Payne]], [[The Nicholas Brothers]], and hit songs such as \"[[In the Mood]]\", \"[[Chattanooga Choo Choo]]\", \"[[It Happened in Sun Valley]]\", and \"[[I Know Why (And So Do You)]]\", followed by ''[[Iceland (film)|Iceland]]'' (1942) with [[Jack Oakie]], Payne, and the hit song \"[[There Will Never Be Another You]]\", and finally ''[[Wintertime (film)|Wintertime]]'' (1943) with [[Cesar Romero]], [[Carole Landis]], [[Cornel Wilde]], and Oakie. Sonja had by now developed a comedy flair and these films were all among the top box-office hits for [[20th Century-Fox]] the respective years.\n\nIn addition to her film career at Fox from 1936 to 1943, Henie formed a business arrangement with [[Arthur Wirtz]], who produced her touring ice shows under the name of \"Hollywood Ice Revue\". Wirtz also acted as Henie's financial advisor. At the time, figure skating and ice shows were not yet an established form of entertainment in the United States. Henie's popularity as a film actress attracted many new fans and instituted skating shows as a popular new entertainment. Throughout the 1940s, Henie and Wirtz produced lavish musical ice skating extravaganzas at [[Rockefeller Center]]'s [[Center Theatre (New York, New York)|Center Theatre]] attracting millions of ticket buyers.\n\nAt the height of her fame, Henie brought as much as $2 million per year from her shows and touring activities. She also had numerous lucrative endorsement contracts, and deals to market skates, clothing, jewelry, dolls, and other merchandise branded with her name. These activities made her one of the wealthiest women in the world in her time.\n[[File:Sonja Henie graumans.jpg|thumb|left|Henie's handprint/signature in front of the [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]]]]\nHenie broke off her arrangement with Wirtz in 1950 and for the next three seasons produced her own tours under the name \"Sonja Henie Ice Revue\". It was an ill-advised decision to set herself up in competition with Wirtz, whose shows now featured the new Olympic champion [[Barbara Ann Scott]]. Since Wirtz controlled the best arenas and dates, Henie was left playing smaller venues and markets already saturated by other touring ice shows such as [[Ice Capades]]. The collapse of a section of bleachers during a show in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], in 1952 compounded the tour's legal and financial woes.\n\nIn 1953, Henie formed a new partnership with [[Morris Chalfen]] to appear in his European ''[[Holiday On Ice]]'' tour, which proved to be a great success. She produced her own show at New York's [[Roxy Theatre (New York City)|Roxy Theatre]] in January 1956.<ref>Bosley Crowther, [https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F20A1FF83459157B93C0A8178AD85F428585F9 \"Screen: 'The Lieutenant Wore Skirts\"]. ''The New York Times'', 12 January 1956.</ref> However, a subsequent South American tour in 1956 was a disaster. Henie was drinking heavily at that time and could no longer keep up with the demands of touring, and this marked her retirement from skating. She did try to make a film series at her own expense; a series that would serve as a travelogue to several cities. Paris and London were mentioned, but only ''[[Hello London]]'' (1958) was made with her own backing, co-starring [[Michael Wilding (actor)|Michael Wilding]] and special guest star [[Stanley Holloway]]. While her ice show numbers were still worth watching, the film received few distributors and poor reviews, ending her film career. \n\nHer autobiography ''Mitt livs eventyr'', was published in 1938 which was translated and released as ''Wings on My Feet'' in 1940, and which was republished in a revised edition in 1954. At the time of her death, Henie was planning a comeback for a television special that would have aired in January 1970. She was to have danced to \"[[Lara's Theme]]\" from ''[[Doctor Zhivago (film)|Doctor Zhivago]]''.\n\n===Nazi controversy===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-09482, Sonja Henie.jpg|thumb|Henie in Berlin, 1930]]\nHenie's connections with [[Adolf Hitler]] and other high-ranking [[Nazi]] officials made her the subject of controversy before, during, and after [[World War II]]. During her amateur skating career, she performed often in [[Germany]] and was a favorite of German audiences and of Hitler personally. As a wealthy celebrity, she moved in the same social circles as royalty and heads of state and made Hitler's acquaintance as a matter of course. During the shooting of ''[[Second Fiddle (1939 film)|Second Fiddle]]'' (1939), she greeted the then Crown-Prince couple of Norway [[Olav V of Norway|Olav]] and [[Princess M\u00e4rtha of Sweden|M\u00e4rtha]] during their US tour. Through the years, her shows and later art exhibitions drew the attention of such people as [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon]] and [[Gustaf VI Adolf of Sweden]] and she met with them.\n[[File:Sonja Henie & Adolf Hitler 1936.jpg|thumb|left|Henie with Hitler in 1936]]\nControversy appeared first when Henie greeted Hitler with a [[Nazi salute]] at the 1936 Winter Olympics in [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]] and after the Games she accepted an invitation to lunch with Hitler at his resort home in nearby [[Berchtesgaden]], where Hitler presented Henie with an autographed photo with a lengthy inscription. She was strongly denounced in the Norwegian press for this. In her revised 1954 biography,<ref group=note>Page 39</ref> she states that no Norwegian judge was in the panel for the 1936 Olympics\u2014as she was entitled to as a Norwegian. She therefore made the most of it and won her third Olympic medal. When she\u2014as a gold medal winner\u2014passed Hitler's tribune with silver medalist [[Cecilia Colledge]] and bronze medalist [[Vivi-Anne Hult\u00e9n]], neither she nor the others honored Hitler with the Nazi salute. The [[1936 European Figure Skating Championships]] also took place in Berlin and neither Henie, Colledge, nor [[Megan Taylor]] paid obeisance to Hitler.{{cn|date=December 2019}} \n\nIn her film ''[[Everything Happens at Night]]'' (1939), [[Ray Milland]] and [[Robert Cummings]] star as rival reporters hot on the trail of Hugo Norden (Maurice Moscovich). Norden, a Nobel Prize winner, was supposedly murdered by the Gestapo, but is rumored to be in hiding and writing anonymous dispatches advocating world peace. When Geoffrey and Ken track Norden to a small village in the Swiss Alps, they soon find themselves competing over the affections of beautiful Louise (Henie), who has a deeper connection to the missing Nobel laureate than the reporters realize. When Geoffrey and Ken get so distracted by romance that they begin to neglect their assignments, it almost leads to disaster as the Gestapo sets out to silence Norden once and for all. Released on 22 December 1939, it was banned in Nazi Germany.\n\nThrough her 1940 marriage to [[Dan Topping]] she had become an American citizen. As such, she was not eligible to speak Norway's cause and with producer [[Alexander Korda]], who was set to produce the propaganda film [[That Hamilton Woman]], could have faced deportation. The Senate Subcommittee (Senate Foreign Relations) dealt with such matters. After the [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|bombing of Pearl Harbor]], when America was no longer neutral, Henie pulled in uniform and visited and gave money to [[Little Norway]]. All Norwegians got free tickets to her shows during the war and she paid and held parties for them.\n\nDuring the [[occupation of Norway by Nazi Germany]], German troops saw Hitler's autographed photo prominently displayed at the piano in the Henie family home in [[Land\u00f8ya]], [[Asker]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sonja Henie|url=http://www.geni.com/people/Sonja-Henie/6000000015540940745|accessdate=27 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702042510/http://www.geni.com/people/Sonja-Henie/6000000015540940745|archive-date=2 July 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As a result, none of Henie's properties in Norway were confiscated or damaged by the Germans. Henie became a [[naturalized citizen]] of the [[United States]] in 1940. Like many Hollywood stars, she supported the U.S. war effort through [[USO]] and similar activities. After the Japanese attack, she invited the boys from [[Little Norway]] to her ice shows, gave the mechanics a plane as well a substantial sum of money to their educational fund. But her first rejection before the US entered the war was never to be forgotten. For this, she was condemned by many Norwegians and Norwegian-Americans. After the war, Henie was mindful that many of her countrymen considered her to be a [[quisling]]. However, she made a triumphant return to Norway with the [[Holiday on Ice]] tour in 1953 and 1955. The [[Norwegian Royal Family]] attended both events and indeed attended her funeral in 1969. The Royal Family were very mindful of whom they supported after the war and Norwegians looked to them as role models in that respect.\n\n===Personal life===\n{{external media\n| image1 = [http://unitproj.library.ucla.edu/dlib/lat/display.cfm?ms=uclalat_1429_b519_222464 '''Sonja Henie'''] with her art collection in Los Angeles, 1964. Her collection is now held by the [[Henie-Onstad Art Centre]]. }}\n\nHenie was married three times, to [[Dan Topping]] (1940\u20131946), Winthrop Gardiner Jr. (1949\u20131956),<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1980/10/18/archives/winthrop-gardiner-jr-dies-at-67-formerly-owned-gardiners-island.html Obituary: \"Winthrop Gardiner, Jr.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115112601/http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F20715F63D5512728DDDA10994D8415B8084F1D3 |date=15 November 2013 }} ''The New York Times''. 18 October 1980.</ref> and the Norwegian shipping magnate and art patron [[Niels Onstad]] (1956\u20131969) (her death). After her retirement in 1956, Henie and Onstad settled in Oslo and accumulated a large collection of modern art that formed the basis for the [[Henie-Onstad Art Centre|Henie Onstad Kunstsenter]] at [[H\u00f8vikodden]] in [[B\u00e6rum]] near [[Oslo]].\n\nShe studied in [[Oslo]] together with [[Martin Stixrud]] and [[Erna Andersen\u200e]] who was her competitor and skate club member.<ref name=life>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=P0oEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA39&lpg=PA39&dq=%22Erna+Andersen%22+speed+skating&source=bl&ots=sTJ47L7P9f&sig=ACfU3U1-NVqXHOe76cKePGR8hdZrHuVfBA&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi3m9bZ3NPoAhXLm6QKHdUXAtcQ6AEwC3oECAoQLw#v=onepage&q=%22Erna%20Andersen%22%20speed%20skating&f=false]</ref>\n\n==Death==\nHenie was diagnosed with [[chronic lymphocytic leukemia]] in the mid-1960s.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=sQklCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA197&lpg=PA197&dq=chronic+lymphocytic+leukemia+sonja+henie#v=onepage |title = Robbins and Cotran Review of Pathology E-Book|isbn = 9780323261982|last1 = Klatt|first1 = Edward C.|last2 = Kumar|first2 = Vinay|date = 3 September 2014}}</ref> She died of the disease at age 57 in 1969 during a flight from [[Paris]] to [[Oslo]].<ref name=sr/><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0408.html Obituary: \"Sonja Henie\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808064102/http://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0408.html |date=8 August 2017 }} ''The New York Times''. 13 October 1969.</ref> She is buried with Onstad in Oslo on the hilltop overlooking the [[Henie Onstad Kunstsenter|Henie Onstad Art Centre]].\n\n==Results==\n\n===Ladies singles===\n[[File:Sonja Henie gold 1928.jpg|thumb|upright|Henie's Olympic gold medal, St. Moritz 1928.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Event\n! 1923\n! 1924\n! 1925\n! 1926\n! 1927\n! 1928\n! 1929\n! 1930\n! 1931\n! 1932\n! 1933\n! 1934\n! 1935\n! 1936\n|-\n| [[Winter Olympic Games|Winter Olympics]] || || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 8th || || || ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st || || || ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st || || || ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st\n|-\n| [[World Figure Skating Championships|World Championships]] || || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5th || ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:silver;\"| 2nd ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st\n|-\n| [[European Figure Skating Championships|European Championships]] || || || || || || || || ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st\n|-\n| [[Norwegian Figure Skating Championships|Norwegian Championships]] ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st || || || || || || ||\n|}\n\n===Pairs===\n(with Arne Lie)\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Event\n! 1926\n! 1927\n! 1928\n|-\n| [[World Figure Skating Championships|World Championships]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5th || || \n|-\n| [[Norwegian Figure Skating Championships|Norwegian Championships]] ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st \n|}\n\n==Awards==\n* Inducted into the [[World Figure Skating Hall of Fame]] (1976).<ref>[http://www.worldskatingmuseum.org/WorldHallOfFame.html World Hall of Fame Members] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207142949/http://www.worldskatingmuseum.org/WorldHallOfFame.html |date=7 December 2017 }}. worldskatingmuseum.org</ref>\n* Inducted into the International Women's Sports Hall of Fame (1982).<ref>[http://www.womenssportsfoundation.org/home/programs/awards/international-womens-sports-hall-of-fame International Women's Sports Hall of Fame] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127174843/http://www.womenssportsfoundation.org/home/programs/awards/international-womens-sports-hall-of-fame |date=27 November 2014 }}. womenssportsfoundation.org</ref>\n* She has a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].\n* In 1938, at age 25, she became the youngest person made a knight first class of [[The Royal Norwegian Order of St. Olav]]\n* Honorary Colonel and Godmother of the 508th Parachute Infantry Regiment, 82d Airborne Division, Fort Bragg, North Carolina.http://508pir.org/digest/digest_1945_Aug_1.htm\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"cellpadding=0;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n|1927\n|''[[Seven Days for Elizabeth]]''\n|Skater\n|-\n|1929\n|''Se Norge''\n|Herself\n|-\n|1936\n|''[[One in a Million (1936 film)|One in a Million]]''\n|Greta \"Gretchen\" Muller\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1937\n|''[[Thin Ice (1937 film)|Thin Ice]]''\n|Lili Heiser\n|-\n|''[[Ali Baba Goes to Town]]''\n|Herself \n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1938\n|''[[Happy Landing (1938 film)|Happy Landing]]''\n|Trudy Ericksen\n|-\n|''[[My Lucky Star (1938 film)|My Lucky Star]]''\n|Krista Nielsen\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1939\n|''[[Second Fiddle (1939 film)|Second Fiddle]]''\n|Trudi Hovland\n|-\n|''[[Everything Happens at Night]]''\n|Louise\n|-\n|1941\n|''[[Sun Valley Serenade]]''\n|Karen Benson\n|-\n|1942\n|''[[Iceland (film)|Iceland]]''\n|Katina Jonsdottir\n|-\n|1943\n|''[[Wintertime (film)|Wintertime]]''\n|Nora\n|-\n|1945\n|''[[It's a Pleasure (film)|It's a Pleasure]]''\n|Chris Linden\n|-\n|1948\n|''[[The Countess of Monte Cristo (1948 film)|The Countess of Monte Cristo]]''\n|Karen Kirsten\n|-\n|1958\n|''[[Hello London]]''\n|Herself\n|}\n\n==Other appearances==\n[[File:EI-LNA Boeing 787-8 Norwegian Tail (9523928105).jpg|thumb|Norwegian Long Haul Boeing 787 painted with an image of Sonja Henie|right]]\n* For a time, Sonja Henie's picture adorned the tail of a [[Boeing 737-300]] of the airline [[Norwegian Air Shuttle]]. As the Boeing 737-300 was being phased out, her picture was placed on the tail of a [[Boeing 737-800]] of the same airline<ref>[http://www.airliners.net/search/photo.search?keywords=Sonja+henie&sort_order=photo_id+desc&page_limit=15&page=1&sid=9169c178ed80f5e71c410e641ebc53d0 Photo Search Results]. airliners.net</ref> and in 2013 to the tail of Norwegian Air Shuttle's first [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner]].<ref>[http://planepictures.net/netshow.php?id=1240755 Photo Norwegian Air Shuttle Boeing 787\u20138 Dreamliner EI-LNA] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904022801/http://planepictures.net/netshow.php?id=1240755 |date=4 September 2015 }}. Planepictures.net. Retrieved on 19 August 2015.</ref> One of the airline's trademarks is having portraits of famous deceased [[Norwegians]] on the tails of its aircraft.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.norwegian.com/en/about-norwegian/our-company/history/our-heroes/|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120911142942/http://www.norwegian.com/en/about-norwegian/our-company/history/our-heroes/|url-status=dead|title=Cheap flights to Oslo, Copenhagen, Stockholm \u2013 Norwegian|access-date=27 April 2012|archive-date=11 September 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2012, the [[Posten Norge]] (Norwegian postal service) issued two stamps featuring Sonja Henie.<ref>[http://www.posten.no/produkter-og-tjenester/frimerker-til-samling/frimerkeprogram-2012/13.april-2012--171861 13 April 2012 \u2013 Personjubileer] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725001847/http://www.posten.no/produkter-og-tjenester/frimerker-til-samling/frimerkeprogram-2012/13.april-2012--171861 |date=25 July 2012 }}. posten.no. Retrieved on 19 August 2015.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* Henie is referenced in two [[Donald Duck]] cartoons in 1939. In ''[[The Hockey Champ]]'', he briefly makes himself look like Sonja Henie while skating on the ice saying \u201cWho is this Sonja Henie?\u201d, while he then meets Henie in ''[[The Autograph Hound]]''.\n* In the 1978 ''[[M*A*S*H]]'' episode \"[[M*A*S*H (season 7)#ep157|Baby, It's Cold Outside]]\", the weekly movie features Sonja. Col. Potter admits to Hawkeye that he loved Sonja from the first time he saw her, and that he \"really fell for her\", then smacks his own butt three times as he adds \"AGAIN and AGAIN and AGAIN!\".\n* In ''[[Caddyshack]]'' (1980), when asked to pick a substitute for [[Rodney Dangerfield]]'s character, [[Chevy Chase]]'s character exclaims, \"Sonja Henie's out.\"\n* In  ''[[I Tonya]]'', Tonya Harding\u2019s mother said \u201cdo you think Sonja Genus\u2019s mother loved her?\u201d\n* Croatian singer-songwriter and poet [[Arsen Dedi\u0107]] ironically compared his juggling music editors and DJs who \"[[wiktionary:on_ice|put him on ice]]\" as \"skating like Sonja Henie\" in his 1979 song, ''Pjesma s ledom'' (''Song on the Rocks'')\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*[https://archive.org/stream/variety153-1944-01#page/n51/mode/2up Variety (January 1944)]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/variety149-1943-01#page/n57/mode/1up Variety (January 1943)]\n*[http://www.aftenposten.no/norge/Little-Norway-Norske-flyktninger-floy-for-frihet-60524b.html Little Norway: Norske flyktninger fl\u00f8y for frihet]\n*[https://no.pinterest.com/pin/87327680251299228/ Sonja Henie, Norwegian figure skater and film star. She was godmother of the 508th PIR, 82nd Airborne Division. She even jumped with them duri\u2026 | WW II | World war two, Military history, Wwii]\n\n* Andersen, Alf G. ''Som i en dr\u00f8m: Sonja Henies liv''. Schibsted (1985) {{ISBN|82-516-1041-9}}\n* Henie, Leif and Raymond Strait. ''Queen of Ice, Queen\n* [http://508pir.org/digest/digest_1945_Aug_1.htm August 1945]\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n{{commons|Sonja Henie|Sonja Henie}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=0377012|name=Sonja Henie}}\n*{{Find a Grave|6005}}\n*[http://www.olympic.org/uk/athletes/heroes/bio_uk.asp?PAR_I_ID=74701 Olympic.org Athlete Profile \u2013 Henie]\n\n{{NavigationOlympicChampionsFigureSkatingLadies}}\n{{NavigationWorldChampionsFigureSkatingLadies}}\n{{NavigationEuropeanChampionsFigureSkatingLadies}}\n{{NavigationNorwegianChampionsFigureSkatingLadies}}\n{{NavigationNorwegianChampionsFigureSkatingPairs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henie, Sonja}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1969 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Deaths from leukemia]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Oslo]]\n[[Category:Norwegian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Norwegian expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:Norwegian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Norwegian female single skaters]]\n[[Category:Norwegian female pair skaters]]\n[[Category:Figure skaters at the 1924 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Figure skaters at the 1928 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Figure skaters at the 1932 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Figure skaters at the 1936 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Norway]]\n[[Category:Olympic figure skaters of Norway]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in figure skating]]\n[[Category:World Figure Skating Championships medalists]]\n[[Category:European Figure Skating Championships medalists]]\n[[Category:World Figure Skating Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox contract players]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1928 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1932 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1936 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the St. Olav's Medal]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Norwegian figure skater}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2017}}<!--many paragraphs have no citations-->\n{{distinguish|text=American basketball player [[Sonja Henning]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox figure skater\n|name                = Sonja Henie\n|image               =Sonja Henie 1936.jpg\n|caption             =Henie at the 1936 Olympics\n|fullname            = Sonja Henie\n|altname             = \n|country             = \n|formercountry       =\n|birth_date          = {{birth date|df=yes|1912|4|8}}\n|birth_place         = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n|hometown            =\n|residence           = \n|death_date          =  {{death date and age|df=yes|1969|10|12|1912|4|8}}\n|death_place         = en route to [[Oslo, Norway]]\n| height = {{convert|1.55|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|formerpartner       = [[Jack Dunn (figure skater)|Jack Dunn]] <br/> [[Stewart Reburn]]\n|coach               = \n|formercoach         = Howard Nicholson \n|choreographer       =\n|formerchoreographer =\n|skating club        = Oslo SK\n|retired             = \n|medaltemplates      = <!-- see [[Template:MedalRelatedTemplates]] -->\n{{MedalCountry | {{NOR}}}}\n{{MedalSport | Ladies' [[Figure skating]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Winter Olympic Games|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1928 Winter Olympics|1928 St. Moritz]]|[[Figure skating at the 1928 Winter Olympics \u2013 Ladies' singles|Singles]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1932 Winter Olympics|1932 Lake Placid]]|[[Figure skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Ladies' singles|Singles]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1936 Winter Olympics|1936 Garmisch-Partenkirchen]]|[[Figure skating at the 1936 Winter Olympics \u2013 Ladies' singles|Singles]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Figure Skating Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1927 World Figure Skating Championships|1927 Oslo]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1928 World Figure Skating Championships|1928 London]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1929 World Figure Skating Championships|1929 Budapest]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1930 World Figure Skating Championships|1930 New York]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1931 World Figure Skating Championships|1931 Berlin]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1932 World Figure Skating Championships|1932 Montreal]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1933 World Figure Skating Championships|1933 Stockholm]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1934 World Figure Skating Championships|1934 Oslo]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1935 World Figure Skating Championships|1935 Vienna]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1936 World Figure Skating Championships|1936 Paris]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1926 World Figure Skating Championships|1926 Stockholm]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Figure Skating Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1931 European Figure Skating Championships|1931 St. Moritz]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1932 European Figure Skating Championships|1932 Paris]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1933 European Figure Skating Championships|1933 London]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1934 European Figure Skating Championships|1934 Prague]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1935 European Figure Skating Championships|1935 St. Moritz]]|Singles}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1936 European Figure Skating Championships|1936 Berlin]]|Singles}}\n}}\n\n'''Sonja Henie''' (8 April 1912 \u2013 12 October 1969) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[figure skating|figure skater]] and film star. She was a three-time [[List of Olympic medalists in figure skating|Olympic Champion]] ([[Figure skating at the 1928 Winter Olympics|1928]], [[Figure skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics|1932]], [[Figure skating at the 1936 Winter Olympics|1936]]) in women's Singles, a ten-time [[World Figure Skating Championships|World Champion]] (1927\u20131936) and a six-time [[European Figure Skating Championships|European Champion]] (1931\u20131936). Henie won more Olympic and World titles than any other ladies' figure skater. At the height of her acting career, she was one of the highest-paid stars in [[Cinema in the United States|Hollywood]] and starred in a series of box-office hits, including ''[[Thin Ice (1937 film)|Thin Ice]]'' (1937), [[Happy Landing (1938 film)]], ''[[My Lucky Star (1938 film)|My Lucky Star]]'' (1938), ''[[Second Fiddle (1939 film)|Second Fiddle]]'' (1939) and ''[[Sun Valley Serenade]]'' (1941).<ref>[http://www.snl.no/Sonja_Henie '&#39;Sonja Henie'&#39; (Store norske leksikon)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008193416/http://snl.no/Sonja_Henie |date=8 October 2012 }}. Snl.no (13 March 2014). Retrieved on 19 August 2015.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nHenie was born in 1912 in Kristiania (now [[Oslo]]) Norway; she was the only daughter of [[Wilhelm Henie]] (1872\u20131937), a prosperous Norwegian [[fur clothing|furrier]], and his wife, Selma Lochmann-Nielsen (1888\u20131961). In addition to the income from the fur business, both of Henie's parents had inherited wealth. Wilhelm Henie had been a one-time [[UCI Track Cycling World Championships|World Cycling Champion]] and the Henie children were encouraged to take up a variety of sports at a young age. Henie initially showed talent at [[skiing]], then followed her older brother, Leif, to take up [[figure skating]]. As a girl Henie also was a nationally ranked [[tennis]] player, and a skilled [[swimming (sport)|swimmer]] and [[equestrianism|equestrienne]]. Once Henie began serious training as a figure skater, her formal schooling ended. She was educated by tutors, and her father hired the best experts in the world, including the famous Russian ballerina, [[Tamara Karsavina]], to transform his daughter into a sporting celebrity.<ref>[http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Sonja_Henie/utdypning '&#39;Sonja Henie/utdypning'&#39; (Store norske leksikon)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008193424/http://snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Sonja_Henie/utdypning |date=8 October 2012 }}. Snl.no. Retrieved on 19 August 2015.</ref>\n\n===Competitive career===\nHenie won her first major competition, the senior Norwegian championships, at the age of 10. She then placed eighth in a field of eight at the [[1924 Winter Olympics]], at the age of eleven.<ref name=sr>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/he/sonja-henie-1.html Sonja Heni] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100309082541/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/he/sonja-henie-1.html |date=9 March 2010 }}. sports-reference.com</ref> During the 1924 program, she skated over to the side of the rink several times to ask her coach for directions, but by the next Olympiad, she needed no such assistance.\n\nHenie won the first of an unprecedented ten consecutive World Figure Skating Championships in 1927 at the age of fourteen. The results of 1927 World Championships, where Henie won in 3\u20132 decision (or 7 vs. 8 ordinal points) over the defending Olympic and World Champion [[Herma Szabo]] of [[Austria]], was controversial, as three of the five judges that gave Henie first-place ordinals were Norwegian (1 + 1 + 1 + 2 + 2 = 7 points) while Szabo received first-place ordinals from an Austrian and a German Judge (1 + 1 + 2 + 2 + 2 = 8 points). Henie went on to win first of her three [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] gold medals the following year, became one of the [[List of Olympic medalists in figure skating by age#Youngest champions|youngest]] figure skating Olympic champions. She defended her Olympic titles in 1932 and in 1936, and her world titles annually until 1936.<ref name=sr/> She also won six consecutive European championships from 1931 to 1936. Henie's unprecedented three Olympic gold medals haven't been matched by any ladies' single skater since; neither are her achievements as ten-time consecutive World Champion. While [[Irina Slutskaya]] of Russia won her seventh European Championship in 2006 to become the most successful ladies' skater in European Championships, Henie retains record of most consecutive titles, sharing it with [[Katarina Witt]] of [[Eastern Germany]]/[[Germany]] (1983\u20131988).\n\nTowards the end of her career, she began to be strongly challenged by younger skaters including [[Cecilia Colledge]], [[Megan Taylor]], and [[Hedy Stenuf]]. However, she held off these competitors and went on to win her third Olympic title at the [[1936 Winter Olympics]], albeit in very controversial circumstances with Cecilia Colledge finishing a very close second. Indeed, after the school figures section at the 1936 Olympic competition, Colledge and Henie were virtually neck and neck with Colledge trailing by just a few points. As Sandra Stevenson recounted in her article in ''[[The Independent]]'' of 21 April 2008, \"the closeness [of the competition] infuriated Henie, who, when the result for that section was posted on a wall in the competitors' lounge, swiped the piece of paper and tore it into little pieces. The draw for the free skating [then] came under suspicion after Henie landed the plum position of skating last, while Colledge had to perform second of the 26 competitors. The early start was seen as a disadvantage, with the audience not yet whipped into a clapping frenzy and the judges known to become freer with their higher marks as the event proceeded. Years later, a fairer, staggered draw was adopted to counteract this situation\".\n\nDuring her competitive career, Henie traveled widely and worked with a variety of foreign coaches. At home in Oslo, she trained at [[Frogner|Frogner Stadium]], where her coaches included Hj\u00f8rdis Olsen and Oscar Holte. During the latter part of her competitive career she was coached primarily by the American Howard Nicholson in [[London]]. In addition to traveling to train and compete, she was much in demand as a performer at figure skating exhibitions in both Europe and North America. Henie became so popular with the public that police had to be called out for crowd control on her appearances in various disparate cities such as [[Prague]] and [[New York City]]. It was an open secret that, in spite of the strict [[amateur sports|amateurism]] requirements of the time, Wilhelm Henie demanded \"expense money\" for his daughter's skating appearances. Both of Henie's parents had given up their own pursuits in Norway\u2014leaving Leif to run the fur business\u2014in order to accompany Sonja on her travels and act as her managers.\n\nHenie is credited with being the first figure skater to adopt the short skirt costume in figure skating, wear white boots,<ref name=\"Jacobs\">{{cite news |last1=Jacobs |first1=Laura |title=Sonja Henie's Ice Age |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/02/sonja-henie-ice-skating-queen |accessdate=3 September 2018 |work=Vanity Fair |date=11 February 2014}}</ref> and make use of dance [[choreography]]. Her innovative skating techniques and glamorous demeanor transformed the sport permanently and confirmed its acceptance as a legitimate sport in the Winter Olympics.<ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/siforwomen/top_100/4/ ''100 Greatest Female Athletes''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060911201834/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/siforwomen/top_100/4/ |date=11 September 2006 }} (''Sports Illustrated'')</ref>\n\n===Professional and film career===\n[[File:Sonja Henie on Time Magazine 1939.jpg|right|thumb|Sonja Henie appeared on the cover of [[Time (magazine)|''Time'' magazine]] on July 17, 1939.]]\n\nAfter the 1936 [[World Figure Skating Championships]], Henie gave up her amateur status and took up a career as a professional performer in acting and live shows.<ref name=sr/> While still a girl, Henie had decided that she wanted to move to [[California]] and become a movie star when her competitive days were over, without considering that her thick accent might hinder her acting ambitions.\n\nIn 1936, following a successful ice show in [[Los Angeles]] orchestrated by her father to launch her film career, Hollywood studio chief [[Darryl Zanuck]] signed her to a long term contract at [[Twentieth Century Fox]], which made her one of the highest-paid actresses of the time. After the success of her first film, ''[[One in a Million (1936 film)|One in a Million]]'' (1936), Henie's position was assured and she became increasingly demanding in her business dealings with Zanuck. Henie also insisted on having total control of the skating numbers in her films such as ''[[Second Fiddle (1939 film)|Second Fiddle]]'' (1939).\n\nHenie tried to break the musical comedy mould with the anti-Nazi film ''[[Everything Happens at Night]]'' (1939) and ''[[It's a Pleasure (film)|It's a Pleasure]]'' (1945), a skating variation of the often-told ''[[A Star Is Born (1937 film)|A Star Is Born]]'' tale about alcoholic-star-in-decline-helps-newcomer-up. It was her only film shot in [[Technicolor]], but it was not as huge at the box office as her other films and also proved her limitations as a dramatic actress in her one only dramatic film.\n\nWhen Zanuck realized her limits in the pseudo-dramatic vein, he cast her in more musical comedies; ''[[Sun Valley Serenade]]'' (1941) with [[Glenn Miller]], [[John Payne (actor)|John Payne]], [[The Nicholas Brothers]], and hit songs such as \"[[In the Mood]]\", \"[[Chattanooga Choo Choo]]\", \"[[It Happened in Sun Valley]]\", and \"[[I Know Why (And So Do You)]]\", followed by ''[[Iceland (film)|Iceland]]'' (1942) with [[Jack Oakie]], Payne, and the hit song \"[[There Will Never Be Another You]]\", and finally ''[[Wintertime (film)|Wintertime]]'' (1943) with [[Cesar Romero]], [[Carole Landis]], [[Cornel Wilde]], and Oakie. Sonja had by now developed a comedy flair and these films were all among the top box-office hits for [[20th Century-Fox]] the respective years.\n\nIn addition to her film career at Fox from 1936 to 1943, Henie formed a business arrangement with [[Arthur Wirtz]], who produced her touring ice shows under the name of \"Hollywood Ice Revue\". Wirtz also acted as Henie's financial advisor. At the time, figure skating and ice shows were not yet an established form of entertainment in the United States. Henie's popularity as a film actress attracted many new fans and instituted skating shows as a popular new entertainment. Throughout the 1940s, Henie and Wirtz produced lavish musical ice skating extravaganzas at [[Rockefeller Center]]'s [[Center Theatre (New York, New York)|Center Theatre]] attracting millions of ticket buyers.\n\nAt the height of her fame, Henie brought as much as $2 million per year from her shows and touring activities. She also had numerous lucrative endorsement contracts, and deals to market skates, clothing, jewelry, dolls, and other merchandise branded with her name. These activities made her one of the wealthiest women in the world in her time.\n[[File:Sonja Henie graumans.jpg|thumb|left|Henie's handprint/signature in front of the [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]]]]\nHenie broke off her arrangement with Wirtz in 1950 and for the next three seasons produced her own tours under the name \"Sonja Henie Ice Revue\". It was an ill-advised decision to set herself up in competition with Wirtz, whose shows now featured the new Olympic champion [[Barbara Ann Scott]]. Since Wirtz controlled the best arenas and dates, Henie was left playing smaller venues and markets already saturated by other touring ice shows such as [[Ice Capades]]. The collapse of a section of bleachers during a show in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], in 1952 compounded the tour's legal and financial woes.\n\nIn 1953, Henie formed a new partnership with [[Morris Chalfen]] to appear in his European ''[[Holiday On Ice]]'' tour, which proved to be a great success. She produced her own show at New York's [[Roxy Theatre (New York City)|Roxy Theatre]] in January 1956.<ref>Bosley Crowther, [https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F20A1FF83459157B93C0A8178AD85F428585F9 \"Screen: 'The Lieutenant Wore Skirts\"]. ''The New York Times'', 12 January 1956.</ref> However, a subsequent South American tour in 1956 was a disaster. Henie was drinking heavily at that time and could no longer keep up with the demands of touring, and this marked her retirement from skating. She did try to make a film series at her own expense; a series that would serve as a travelogue to several cities. Paris and London were mentioned, but only ''[[Hello London]]'' (1958) was made with her own backing, co-starring [[Michael Wilding (actor)|Michael Wilding]] and special guest star [[Stanley Holloway]]. While her ice show numbers were still worth watching, the film received few distributors and poor reviews, ending her film career. \n\nHer autobiography ''Mitt livs eventyr'', was published in 1938 which was translated and released as ''Wings on My Feet'' in 1940, and which was republished in a revised edition in 1954. At the time of her death, Henie was planning a comeback for a television special that would have aired in January 1970. She was to have danced to \"[[Lara's Theme]]\" from ''[[Doctor Zhivago (film)|Doctor Zhivago]]''.\n\n===Nazi controversy===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-09482, Sonja Henie.jpg|thumb|Henie in Berlin, 1930]]\nHenie's connections with [[Adolf Hitler]] and other high-ranking [[Nazi]] officials made her the subject of controversy before, during, and after [[World War II]]. During her amateur skating career, she performed often in [[Germany]] and was a favorite of German audiences and of Hitler personally. As a wealthy celebrity, she moved in the same social circles as royalty and heads of state and made Hitler's acquaintance as a matter of course. During the shooting of ''[[Second Fiddle (1939 film)|Second Fiddle]]'' (1939), she greeted the then Crown-Prince couple of Norway [[Olav V of Norway|Olav]] and [[Princess M\u00e4rtha of Sweden|M\u00e4rtha]] during their US tour. Through the years, her shows and later art exhibitions drew the attention of such people as [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon]] and [[Gustaf VI Adolf of Sweden]] and she met with them.\n[[File:Sonja Henie & Adolf Hitler 1936.jpg|thumb|left|Henie with Hitler in 1936]]\nControversy appeared first when Henie greeted Hitler with a [[Nazi salute]] at the 1936 Winter Olympics in [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]] and after the Games she accepted an invitation to lunch with Hitler at his resort home in nearby [[Berchtesgaden]], where Hitler presented Henie with an autographed photo with a lengthy inscription. She was strongly denounced in the Norwegian press for this. In her revised 1954 biography,<ref group=note>Page 39</ref> she states that no Norwegian judge was in the panel for the 1936 Olympics\u2014as she was entitled to as a Norwegian. She therefore made the most of it and won her third Olympic medal. When she\u2014as a gold medal winner\u2014passed Hitler's tribune with silver medalist [[Cecilia Colledge]] and bronze medalist [[Vivi-Anne Hult\u00e9n]], neither she nor the others honored Hitler with the Nazi salute. The [[1936 European Figure Skating Championships]] also took place in Berlin and neither Henie, Colledge, nor [[Megan Taylor]] paid obeisance to Hitler.{{cn|date=December 2019}} \n\nIn her film ''[[Everything Happens at Night]]'' (1939), [[Ray Milland]] and [[Robert Cummings]] star as rival reporters hot on the trail of Hugo Norden (Maurice Moscovich). Norden, a Nobel Prize winner, was supposedly murdered by the Gestapo, but is rumored to be in hiding and writing anonymous dispatches advocating world peace. When Geoffrey and Ken track Norden to a small village in the Swiss Alps, they soon find themselves competing over the affections of beautiful Louise (Henie), who has a deeper connection to the missing Nobel laureate than the reporters realize. When Geoffrey and Ken get so distracted by romance that they begin to neglect their assignments, it almost leads to disaster as the Gestapo sets out to silence Norden once and for all. Released on 22 December 1939, it was banned in Nazi Germany.\n\nThrough her 1940 marriage to [[Dan Topping]] she had become an American citizen. As such, she was not eligible to speak Norway's cause and with producer [[Alexander Korda]], who was set to produce the propaganda film [[That Hamilton Woman]], could have faced deportation. The Senate Subcommittee (Senate Foreign Relations) dealt with such matters. After the [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|bombing of Pearl Harbor]], when America was no longer neutral, Henie pulled in uniform and visited and gave money to [[Little Norway]]. All Norwegians got free tickets to her shows during the war and she paid and held parties for them.\n\nDuring the [[occupation of Norway by Nazi Germany]], German troops saw Hitler's autographed photo prominently displayed at the piano in the Henie family home in [[Land\u00f8ya]], [[Asker]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sonja Henie|url=http://www.geni.com/people/Sonja-Henie/6000000015540940745|accessdate=27 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702042510/http://www.geni.com/people/Sonja-Henie/6000000015540940745|archive-date=2 July 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As a result, none of Henie's properties in Norway were confiscated or damaged by the Germans. Henie became a [[naturalized citizen]] of the [[United States]] in 1940. Like many Hollywood stars, she supported the U.S. war effort through [[USO]] and similar activities. After the Japanese attack, she invited the boys from [[Little Norway]] to her ice shows, gave the mechanics a plane as well a substantial sum of money to their educational fund. But her first rejection before the US entered the war was never to be forgotten. For this, she was condemned by many Norwegians and Norwegian-Americans. After the war, Henie was mindful that many of her countrymen considered her to be a [[quisling]]. However, she made a triumphant return to Norway with the [[Holiday on Ice]] tour in 1953 and 1955. The [[Norwegian Royal Family]] attended both events and indeed attended her funeral in 1969. The Royal Family were very mindful of whom they supported after the war and Norwegians looked to them as role models in that respect.\n\n===Personal life===\n{{external media\n| image1 = [http://unitproj.library.ucla.edu/dlib/lat/display.cfm?ms=uclalat_1429_b519_222464 '''Sonja Henie'''] with her art collection in Los Angeles, 1964. Her collection is now held by the [[Henie-Onstad Art Centre]]. }}\n\nHenie was married three times, to [[Dan Topping]] (1940\u20131946), Winthrop Gardiner Jr. (1949\u20131956),<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1980/10/18/archives/winthrop-gardiner-jr-dies-at-67-formerly-owned-gardiners-island.html Obituary: \"Winthrop Gardiner, Jr.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115112601/http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F20715F63D5512728DDDA10994D8415B8084F1D3 |date=15 November 2013 }} ''The New York Times''. 18 October 1980.</ref> and the Norwegian shipping magnate and art patron [[Niels Onstad]] (1956\u20131969) (her death). After her retirement in 1956, Henie and Onstad settled in Oslo and accumulated a large collection of modern art that formed the basis for the [[Henie-Onstad Art Centre|Henie Onstad Kunstsenter]] at [[H\u00f8vikodden]] in [[B\u00e6rum]] near [[Oslo]].\n\nShe studied in [[Oslo]] together with [[Martin Stixrud]] and [[Erna Andersen\u200e]] who was her competitor and skate club member.<ref name=life>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=P0oEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA39&lpg=PA39&dq=%22Erna+Andersen%22+speed+skating&source=bl&ots=sTJ47L7P9f&sig=ACfU3U1-NVqXHOe76cKePGR8hdZrHuVfBA&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi3m9bZ3NPoAhXLm6QKHdUXAtcQ6AEwC3oECAoQLw#v=onepage&q=%22Erna%20Andersen%22%20speed%20skating&f=false]</ref>\n\n==Death==\nHenie was diagnosed with [[chronic lymphocytic leukemia]] in the mid-1960s.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=sQklCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA197&lpg=PA197&dq=chronic+lymphocytic+leukemia+sonja+henie#v=onepage |title = Robbins and Cotran Review of Pathology E-Book|isbn = 9780323261982|last1 = Klatt|first1 = Edward C.|last2 = Kumar|first2 = Vinay|date = 3 September 2014}}</ref> She died of the disease at age 57 in 1969 during a flight from [[Paris]] to [[Oslo]].<ref name=sr/><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0408.html Obituary: \"Sonja Henie\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808064102/http://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0408.html |date=8 August 2017 }} ''The New York Times''. 13 October 1969.</ref> She is buried with Onstad in Oslo on the hilltop overlooking the [[Henie Onstad Kunstsenter|Henie Onstad Art Centre]].\n\n==Results==\n\n===Ladies singles===\n[[File:Sonja Henie gold 1928.jpg|thumb|upright|Henie's Olympic gold medal, St. Moritz 1928.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Event\n! 1923\n! 1924\n! 1925\n! 1926\n! 1927\n! 1928\n! 1929\n! 1930\n! 1931\n! 1932\n! 1933\n! 1934\n! 1935\n! 1936\n|-\n| [[Winter Olympic Games|Winter Olympics]] || || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 8th || || || ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st || || || ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st || || || ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st\n|-\n| [[World Figure Skating Championships|World Championships]] || || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5th || ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:silver;\"| 2nd ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st\n|-\n| [[European Figure Skating Championships|European Championships]] || || || || || || || || ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st\n|-\n| [[Norwegian Figure Skating Championships|Norwegian Championships]] ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st || || || || || || ||\n|}\n\n===Pairs===\n(with Arne Lie)\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Event\n! 1926\n! 1927\n! 1928\n|-\n| [[World Figure Skating Championships|World Championships]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5th || || \n|-\n| [[Norwegian Figure Skating Championships|Norwegian Championships]] ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st ||  style=\"text-align:center; background:gold;\"| 1st \n|}\n\n==Awards==\n* Inducted into the [[World Figure Skating Hall of Fame]] (1976).<ref>[http://www.worldskatingmuseum.org/WorldHallOfFame.html World Hall of Fame Members] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207142949/http://www.worldskatingmuseum.org/WorldHallOfFame.html |date=7 December 2017 }}. worldskatingmuseum.org</ref>\n* Inducted into the International Women's Sports Hall of Fame (1982).<ref>[http://www.womenssportsfoundation.org/home/programs/awards/international-womens-sports-hall-of-fame International Women's Sports Hall of Fame] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127174843/http://www.womenssportsfoundation.org/home/programs/awards/international-womens-sports-hall-of-fame |date=27 November 2014 }}. womenssportsfoundation.org</ref>\n* She has a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].\n* In 1938, at age 25, she became the youngest person made a knight first class of [[The Royal Norwegian Order of St. Olav]]\n* Honorary Colonel and Godmother of the 508th Parachute Infantry Regiment, 82d Airborne Division, Fort Bragg, North Carolina.http://508pir.org/digest/digest_1945_Aug_1.htm\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"cellpadding=0;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n|1927\n|''[[Seven Days for Elizabeth]]''\n|Skater\n|-\n|1929\n|''Se Norge''\n|Herself\n|-\n|1936\n|''[[One in a Million (1936 film)|One in a Million]]''\n|Greta \"Gretchen\" Muller\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1937\n|''[[Thin Ice (1937 film)|Thin Ice]]''\n|Lili Heiser\n|-\n|''[[Ali Baba Goes to Town]]''\n|Herself \n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1938\n|''[[Happy Landing (1938 film)|Happy Landing]]''\n|Trudy Ericksen\n|-\n|''[[My Lucky Star (1938 film)|My Lucky Star]]''\n|Krista Nielsen\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1939\n|''[[Second Fiddle (1939 film)|Second Fiddle]]''\n|Trudi Hovland\n|-\n|''[[Everything Happens at Night]]''\n|Louise\n|-\n|1941\n|''[[Sun Valley Serenade]]''\n|Karen Benson\n|-\n|1942\n|''[[Iceland (film)|Iceland]]''\n|Katina Jonsdottir\n|-\n|1943\n|''[[Wintertime (film)|Wintertime]]''\n|Nora\n|-\n|1945\n|''[[It's a Pleasure (film)|It's a Pleasure]]''\n|Chris Linden\n|-\n|1948\n|''[[The Countess of Monte Cristo (1948 film)|The Countess of Monte Cristo]]''\n|Karen Kirsten\n|-\n|1958\n|''[[Hello London]]''\n|Herself\n|}\n\n==Other appearances==\n[[File:EI-LNA Boeing 787-8 Norwegian Tail (9523928105).jpg|thumb|Norwegian Long Haul Boeing 787 painted with an image of Sonja Henie|right]]\n* For a time, Sonja Henie's picture adorned the tail of a [[Boeing 737-300]] of the airline [[Norwegian Air Shuttle]]. As the Boeing 737-300 was being phased out, her picture was placed on the tail of a [[Boeing 737-800]] of the same airline<ref>[http://www.airliners.net/search/photo.search?keywords=Sonja+henie&sort_order=photo_id+desc&page_limit=15&page=1&sid=9169c178ed80f5e71c410e641ebc53d0 Photo Search Results]. airliners.net</ref> and in 2013 to the tail of Norwegian Air Shuttle's first [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner]].<ref>[http://planepictures.net/netshow.php?id=1240755 Photo Norwegian Air Shuttle Boeing 787\u20138 Dreamliner EI-LNA] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904022801/http://planepictures.net/netshow.php?id=1240755 |date=4 September 2015 }}. Planepictures.net. Retrieved on 19 August 2015.</ref> One of the airline's trademarks is having portraits of famous deceased [[Norwegians]] on the tails of its aircraft.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.norwegian.com/en/about-norwegian/our-company/history/our-heroes/|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120911142942/http://www.norwegian.com/en/about-norwegian/our-company/history/our-heroes/|url-status=dead|title=Cheap flights to Oslo, Copenhagen, Stockholm \u2013 Norwegian|access-date=27 April 2012|archive-date=11 September 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2012, the [[Posten Norge]] (Norwegian postal service) issued two stamps featuring Sonja Henie.<ref>[http://www.posten.no/produkter-og-tjenester/frimerker-til-samling/frimerkeprogram-2012/13.april-2012--171861 13 April 2012 \u2013 Personjubileer] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725001847/http://www.posten.no/produkter-og-tjenester/frimerker-til-samling/frimerkeprogram-2012/13.april-2012--171861 |date=25 July 2012 }}. posten.no. Retrieved on 19 August 2015.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* Henie is referenced in two [[Donald Duck]] cartoons in 1939. In ''[[The Hockey Champ]]'', he briefly makes himself look like Sonja Henie while skating on the ice saying \u201cWho is this Sonja Henie?\u201d, while he then meets Henie in ''[[The Autograph Hound]]''.\n* In the 1978 ''[[M*A*S*H]]'' episode \"[[M*A*S*H (season 7)#ep157|Baby, It's Cold Outside]]\", the weekly movie features Sonja. Col. Potter admits to Hawkeye that he loved Sonja from the first time he saw her, and that he \"really fell for her\", then smacks his own butt three times as he adds \"AGAIN and AGAIN and AGAIN!\".\n* In ''[[Caddyshack]]'' (1980), when asked to pick a substitute for [[Rodney Dangerfield]]'s character, [[Chevy Chase]]'s character exclaims, \"Sonja Henie's out.\"\n* In  ''[[I Tonya]]'', Tonya Harding\u2019s mother said \u201cdo you think Sonja Genus\u2019s mother loved her?\u201d\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*[https://archive.org/stream/variety153-1944-01#page/n51/mode/2up Variety (January 1944)]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/variety149-1943-01#page/n57/mode/1up Variety (January 1943)]\n*[http://www.aftenposten.no/norge/Little-Norway-Norske-flyktninger-floy-for-frihet-60524b.html Little Norway: Norske flyktninger fl\u00f8y for frihet]\n*[