{"title_page": "RCGS Resolute", "text_new": "{{short description|Cruise ship}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=''RCGS Resolute''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = RCGS Resolute.jpg\n| Ship caption = ''RCGS Resolute'' in [[Aberdeen]] in June 2019\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship name = *''Society Adventurer'' (1991\u20131993)\n*''Hanseatic'' (1993\u20132018)\n*''RCGS Resolute'' (2018\u2013present)\n| Ship owner = * [[Discoverer Reederei]] (planned)<ref name=\"id\" />\n* Society Adventurer Shipping Company (1991\u20131993)<ref name=\"id\" />\n* Bunnys Adventure & Cruise Shipping Co Ltd (1993\u2013present)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship operator = * [[Hanseatic Tours]] (1993\u20131997)\n* [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] (1997\u20132018)\n* [[One Ocean Expeditions]] (2018\u20132019)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship registry = * [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]], {{BAH}} (1991\u20132018)\n* [[Madeira, Portugal|Madeira]], {{POR}} (2018\u2013present)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship route = \n| Ship ordered = 22 December 1989<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship builder = [[Rauma Yards]] ([[Rauma, Finland|Rauma]], [[Finland]])<ref name=\"id\">{{cite|last1=Id|first1=Kalle|last2=Peter|first2=Bruce|title=Innovation and Specialisation \u2014 A History of Shipbuilding in Finland|publisher=Nautilus|year=2017|ISBN=9788790924683|page=}}</ref>\n| Ship original cost = US$75 million<ref name=\"id\" />\n| Ship yard number =306<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship laid down = 3 September 1990<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship launched = 5 January 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship completed = 7 June 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship sponsor=Ursel Klein<ref name=\"maritimereporter\">{{cite web|url=https://magazines.marinelink.com/Magazines/MaritimeReporter/199102/content/launches-luxury-cruise-200306|title=Rauma Yards Launches Luxury Cruise Ship|work=Maritime Reporter and Engineering News|date=February 1991|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship christened = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship maiden voyage = 27 March 1993<ref name=\"fof\" />\n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n|Ship identification=* [[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: CQAL6\n* {{IMO Number|9000168}}\n* {{MMSI|255806208}}<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n* {{ship register|DNV|G99209}}<ref name=\"dnv\">{{csr|register=DNV|id=G99209|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship status = In service\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = <ref name=\"dnv\" /><ref name=\"Hapag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurolloyd.com/Hapag-Lloyd/HANSEATIC.pdf|title=MS ''Hanseatic'' Ship details|publisher=Hapag-Lloyd|accessdate=28 February 2009|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| Ship type = [[Cruise ship]]\n| Ship tonnage =* {{GT|8,445}}\n* {{NetT|2,573}}\n* {{DWT|1,177}}\n| Ship displacement = 5,892{{nbsp}}tonnes<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship length = {{convert|124.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|18.00|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = \n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = {{convert|4.9|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = {{convert|7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship decks = 6\n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = [[DNV GL]] E4\n| Ship power = 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[MaK]] 8M453C (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}2,940{{nbsp}}kW)<ref name=\"seaweb\">{{csr|register=SEAWEB|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship propulsion = Two shafts; [[controllable pitch propeller]]s\n| Ship speed = {{convert|16|kn}}\n| Ship range= {{convert|8600|nmi}}\n| Ship capacity = 184 passengers in 88 cabins and four suites\n| Ship crew = 125\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n'''''RCGS Resolute''''' is a [[star (classification)|five-star]] [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] expedition [[cruise ship]] built in 1991 by [[Rauma Yards]] in Finland. She was originally named '''''Society Adventurer''''', but after [[Discoverer Reederei]] was unable to take delivery of the vessel due to financial troubles, the completed ship was laid up at the shipyard for almost two years. In 1993, she was acquired by [[Hanseatic Tours]] (which later merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd]]) and renamed '''''Hanseatic'''''. In 2018, she was chartered to [[One Ocean Expeditions]] and given her current name.\n\n== General characteristics ==\n\n''RCGS Resolute'' is {{convert|124.8|m|ftin}} [[length overall|long overall]] and {{convert|104.45|m|ftin}} [[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]], has a beam of {{convert|18|m|ftin}} and draws {{convert|4.9|m|ftin}} of water with a [[Displacement (ship)|displacement]] of {{convert|5892|t|LT}}.<ref name=\"seaweb\" /> Her [[gross tonnage]] is 8,445; [[net tonnage]] 2,573; and [[deadweight tonnage]] 1,177 tonnes. The ship's hull and propulsion system are strengthened for navigation in ice-covered waters according to the [[DNV GL]] [[ice class]] E4,<ref name=\"dnv\" /> which is equivalent to the highest [[Finnish-Swedish ice class]] for merchant ships, 1A Super.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.finlex.fi/data/normit/43683/TRAFI_383804_03_04_01_00_2016_Vastaavuusluettelo_EN.pdf|title=Finnish ice classes equivalent to class notations of recognized classification societies and the determination of the ice classes of ships|publisher=Finnish Transport Safety Agency|date=14 November 2017|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBuilt to cater to the [[star (classification)|five-star]] luxury cruise market, interiors on the ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s six passenger-accessible decks were designed by the German architect [[Wilfried K\u00f6hnemann]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel has 88 outside cabins and, above the bridge deck, four suites for a total of 184 passengers served by a crew of 125. Public spaces include a restaurant, multiple lounges, and a 78-seat theater. The ship carries 14 [[Zodiac inflatable boat]]s to take passengers ashore during expedition cruises.<ref name=\"Hapag\" /> \n\nThe ship's propulsion system consists of two [[straight-8 engine|eight-cylinder]] [[MaK]] 8M453C four-stroke medium-speed [[diesel engine]]s, each rated {{convert|2940|kW|hp}} at 600{{nbsp}}rpm, driving two [[controllable pitch propeller]]s. Onboard electrical power is generated by two {{convert|1160|kW|hp|adj=on}} [[straight-6 engine|six-cylinder]] MaK 6M332 auxiliary diesel generators and two {{convert|1040|kW|hp|adj=on}} main engine driven shaft generators. For maneuvering in ports, the ship has a {{convert|700|kW|hp|adj=on}} transverse [[bow thruster]].<ref name=\"seaweb\" /><ref name=\"dnv\" /> ''RCGS Resolute'' has a service speed of {{convert|16|kn}} and a cruising range of {{convert|8600|nmi}}.<ref name=\"Hapag\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== ''Society Adventurer'' ===\n\nIn December 1989, the German cruise ship company [[Discoverer Reederei]] decided to order a $75 million expedition cruise ship for its US-based subsidiary [[Society Expeditions]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The shipbuilding contract was awarded to [[Rauma Yards]], a new Finnish company established in August of the same year following the disbanding of [[Rauma-Repola]]'s shipyard group.<ref name=\"meriteollisuus\">{{cite web|url=https://meriteollisuus.teknologiateollisuus.fi/sites/meriteollisuus/files/inline-files/Meriteoll_historiikki_web.pdf|title=Kun rauta kelluu \u2014 V\u00e4l\u00e4hdyksi\u00e4 suomalaisen meriteollisuuden vuosisadasta|publisher=Meriteollisuus|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> The ship, launched on 5 January 1991 as ''Society Adventurer'',<ref name=\"dnv\" /> was intended for adventure-style cruises to remote destinations such as [[Antarctica]] and had, among other features, an ice-strengthened hull. However, Discoverer Reederei was unable to take delivery of the vessel in the following summer due to financial troubles and also had to cancel a [[sister ship]] that had already been contracted.<ref name=\"id\" /><ref name=\"maritimereporter\" /> As a result, the ownership of the vessel was transferred to Rauma Yards's newly-established Bahamas-registered subsidiary, Society Adventurer Shipping Company, on 7 June 1991.<ref name=\"dnv\" /> Later that year, Rauma Yards was merged with another local shipbuilder, [[Hollming]], as [[Finnyards]].<ref name=\"meriteollisuus\" /> While on a lay-up at the yard, ''Society Adventurer'' was inspected by a number of parties interested in acquiring the vessel, among them the future [[president of the United States]] [[Donald Trump]] who visited [[Rauma, Finland|Rauma]] in 1992.<ref name=\"id\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ls24.fi/uutiset/donald-trump-kavi-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-nayttelijavaimo-naytti-poseeraamisen-mallia|title=Donald Trump k\u00e4vi Raumalla laivakaupoilla - n\u00e4yttelij\u00e4vaimo n\u00e4ytti poseeraamisen mallia|work=L\u00e4nsi-Suomi|date=21 May 2016|accessdate=4 April 2020|language=fi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.satakunnankansa.fi/satakunta/donald-trump-piipahti-1992-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-ja-tansseissa-13973980|title=Donald Trump piipahti 1992 Raumalla laivakaupoilla ja tansseissa|work=Satakunnan Kansa|date=9 November 2016|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Hanseatic'' ===\n[[File:Hanseatic 5.jpg|thumb|left|''Hanseatic'' sporting the classic [[Hamburg Atlantic Line]] livery in Nuuk, Greenland, in 2008.]]\n\nIn 1993, the ship was chartered and shortly afterwards purchased by the German expedition cruise operator [[Hanseatic Tours]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The company had been established two years earlier by [[Dirk Moldenhauer]], who had been the last captain of [[German Atlantic Line]]'s cruise ship [[TS Maxim Gorkiy|''Hanseatic'']] in 1973 and later acquired rights to the classic Hamburg Atlantic Line logo, livery and the name \"Hanseatic\".<ref name=\"simplonpc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.simplonpc.co.uk/HamburgAtlantik.html|title=Hamburg Atlantik Line/Deutsche Atlantik Line/Hanseatic Tours|accessdate=4 April 2020|author=Ian Boyle|work=Simplon Postcards}}</ref> ''Society Adventurer'' was renamed ''Hanseatic'' on 23 March 1993,<ref name=\"schwerdtner\">{{cite|title=German Luxury Ocean Liners: From Kaiser Wilhelm Der Grosse to Aidastella|last=Schwerdtner|first=Nils|publisher=Amberley Publishing|year=2013|}}</ref> becoming the fourth ship to bear the name, and the original blue-yellow-white Discoverer Reederei livery was replaced with the white hull and red decorative stripes.<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel's maiden cruise from [[Hamburg]] to [[Sevilla]] began on 27 March 1993.<ref name=\"fof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.faktaomfartyg.se/society_adventurer_1991.htm|title=M/S Society Adventurer|work=Fakta om Fartyg|last=Asklander|first=Micke|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> When Hanseatic Tours was merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] in 1997, ''Hanseatic'' retained her original name as well as Hamburg Atlantic Line livery and funnel logo until rebranding in 2011.<ref name=\"schwerdtner\" /><ref name=\"seatrade\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seatrade-cruise.com/news-headlines/former-hanseatic-leaves-germany-after-long-career-hapag-lloyd|title=Former Hanseatic leaves Germany after long career with Hapag-Lloyd|work=Seatrade Cruise News|publisher=Informa Markets|date=8 October 2018|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Hanseatic'' remained in Hapag-Lloyd's fleet until 2018. Over the ship's 25-year career and a total of 667 cruises, she made 128 expeditions to Antarctica, two voyages to the [[Northern Sea Route]] (Northeast Passage), and transited the full length of the [[Northwest Passage]] 11 times.<ref name=\"seatrade\" /> The latter is a record number for passenger ships, exceeded only by the Russian [[icebreaker]] ''[[Kapitan Khlebnikov]]'' which is also used for expedition cruises.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spri.cam.ac.uk/resources/infosheets/northwestpassage.pdf|title=Transits of the Northwest Passage to the end of the 2019 navigation season|publisher=Scott Polar Research Institute|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> ''Hanseatic'' also holds the record for having been further north among passenger-carrying ships that are not icebreakers: on 26 August 2014, the vessel reached {{Coord|85|40.7|N|135|39.6|E|display=inline}}, {{convert|259|nmi}} from the [[North Pole]], due to unusually easy ice conditions in the Russian Arctic at that time.<ref name=\"seatrade\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelpulse.com/news/cruise/expedition-ship-hanseatic-sets-new-record-for-passenger-ships.html|title=Expedition Ship Hanseatic Sets New Record for Passenger Ships|publisher=Travel Pulse|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''RCGS Resolute'' ===\n\nIn June 2017, the Canada-based cruise ship operator [[One Ocean Expeditions]] announced that it would expand its fleet of expedition cruise ships with a long-term charter of the former ''Hanseatic''. The ship would be renamed ''RCGS Resolute'' after the 1850-built [[Royal Navy]] Arctic exploration vessel [[HMS Resolute|HMS ''Resolute'']] as well as the [[Inuit]] hamlet [[Resolute, Nunavut|Resolute]] in [[Nunavut]]. Furthermore, the ship would carry the initials of the [[Royal Canadian Geographic Society]] (RCGS) with whom One Ocean Expeditions had partnered.<ref name=\"oneocean_july2017\">{{cite web|url=https://discover.oneoceanexpeditions.com/rcgs-resolute/|title=One Ocean Expeditions Expands Fleet and Operations with New Vessel: RCGS RESOLUTE|publisher=One Ocean Expeditions|date=June 2017|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> After concluding her career with Hapag-Lloyd, a brief drydocking in Germany and reflagging from the Bahamas to Portugal, the vessel headed to Canada in October 2018 under her new name and with a new livery.<ref name=\"seatrade\" />\n\nIn 2019, the company's financial difficulties began to surface with the sudden withdrawal of the Russian research vessels ''[[Akademik Ioffe]]'' and ''[[Akademik Sergey Vavilov]]'' chartered from the [[Shirshov Institute of Oceanology]]. Although One Ocean Expeditions initially called the Russian owner's action a contract violation, it was later revealed that the company had failed to pay charter and fueling fees to the intermediate charterer Terragelida Ship Management which had then terminated the contract.<ref name=\"guardian_oct2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.pe.ca/business/regional-business/shipping-news-one-ocean-expeditions-sails-into-troubled-waters-370614/|title=SHIPPING NEWS: One Ocean Expeditions sails into troubled waters|date=31 October 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020|work=The Guardian|publisher=Saltwire Network}}</ref> This left One Ocean Expeditions with just one ship, ''RCGS Resolute''. In August, she was briefly arrested in [[Iqaluit]] over a C$100,000 payment dispute. While this issue was reportedly solved quickly,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/cruise-ship-briefly-arrested-in-nunavut|title= Cruise Ship Briefly Arrested in Nunavut|publisher=The Maritime Executive|date=19 August 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> another arrest over non-payment of services and crew wages followed in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] next month. Finally, in October One Ocean Expeditions was forced to cancel an Antarctic cruise midway after the vessel could not be refueled due to the company's non-payment of outstanding debts. Shortly after the ship's 140 passengers disembarked, ''RCGS Resolute'' was detained in [[Buenos Aires]] over \"significant debt\".<ref name=\"guardian_oct2018\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/one-ocean-expeditions-ship-detained-1.5370649|title=Ship belonging to troubled B.C. expedition cruise company detained in Argentina|date=24 November 2019|publisher=CBC|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The company entered administration in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cruisecritic.co.uk/news/4955/|title=One Ocean Expeditions Cruise Line Collapses|work=CruiseCritic|publisher=The Independent Traveler|date=13 January 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2020, ''RCGS Resolute'' left Buenos Aires after the ship's registered owner, Bunnys Adventure & Cruise Shipping Company Limited,<ref name=\"seaweb\" /> paid a total of US$3.6 million of One Ocean Expeditions's outstanding debt to fuel suppliers, ship agents and crew members in order to avoid a court-ordered sale of the vessel.<ref name=\"chronicleherald17march\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thechronicleherald.ca/business/local-business/shipping-news-some-cruise-companies-scrap-schedule-others-continue-on-425502/|title=SHIPPING NEWS: Some cruise companies scrap schedule, others continue on|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Incidents ==\n\n=== 1996 grounding === \n\nOn 29 August 1996, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground in [[Simpson Strait]] in the Canadian Arctic. The vessel was eleven days into an eastbound transit along the Northwest Passage with 149 passengers and 110 crew, and had stopped at [[Gjoa Haven]] to let passengers ashore. Unknowingly to the crew, a green buoy marking a shallow shoal had not been removed after the previous navigating season and, over the winter months, had been moved to the northeast by about {{convert|200|m|yd}} by drifting ice. Shortly after departure, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground on the shoal at {{Coord|68|33.75|N|97|32.2|W|display=inline}}.<ref name=\"1996report\">{{cite web|url=https://bst-tsb.gc.ca/ENG/rapports-reports/marine/1996/m96h0016/M96H0016.pdf|title=Grounding of passenger vessel \"Hanseatic\" at Simpson Strait, Northwest Territories, 29 August 1996 (report number M96H0016)|publisher=Transport Safety Board of Canada|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith no danger of the vessel sinking, ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s passengers were allowed to explore the nearby islands using the ship's boats until the Russian icebreaker ''[[Kapitan Dranitsyn]]'' arrived to pick up the passengers on 5 September and continue the Northwest Passage expedition under charter by Hanseatic Tours. ''Hanseatic'' itself was successfully refloated on 8 September. While the ship's hull was damaged during the grounding, no oil spilled to the sea and there were no injuries among the passengers or the crew.<ref name=\"1996report\" />\n\n=== 1997 grounding ===\n\nOn 14 July 1997, ''Hanseatic'' was grounded on a sand bank in [[Murchisonfjorden]] in [[Svalbard]] with 145 passengers onboard.<ref>{{cite book|title=Navigation Safety and Risk Assessment Challenges in the High North|last1=Marchenko|first1=N.|last2=Borch|first2=O.J.|last3=Andreassen|first3=N.|last4=Kuznetsova|first4=S.Yu.|last5=Ingimundarson|first5=V.|last6=Jakobsen|first6=U.|work=Marine Navigation: Proceedings of the 12th International Conference on Marine Navigation and Safety of Sea Transportation (TransNav 2017), June 21-23, 2017, Gdynia, Poland|publisher=CRC Press|year=2017|page=345|isbn=978-13-5158-218-6}}</ref><ref name=\"penguins\">{{cite book|last=Wright|first=Christopher|title=Of Penguins and Polar Bears: A History of Cold Water Cruising|year=2020|publisher=The History Press|ISBN=978-07-5099-456-9}}</ref> No injuries nor damage to the ship was reported, and the passengers were again taken to explore nearby islands on ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s Zodiac boats while awaiting evacuation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/0e7c429f30ac4d87307fb0eea3de2220|title=Cruise ship stuck in Arctic after running aground|date=14 July 1997|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> By 17 July, the ship had been refloated and was heading towards [[Longyearbyen]] for inspection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelweekly.com/Cruise-Travel/Hanseatic-Grounded-in-the-Arctic|title=Hanseatic Grounded in the Arctic|date=17 July 1997|publisher=Travel Weekly|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2005 grounding ===\n\nIn August 2005, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground near the island of [[Lur\u00f8ya, Nordland|Lur\u00f8ya]] on the Norwegian coast, just south of the [[Arctic Circle]], with 160 passengers onboard. While the vessel was not in danger of sinking despite a {{convert|5|m|ft|adj=on}} hole in one of her [[ballast water]] tank, the passengers and part of the crew was nonetheless evacuated.<ref name=\"penguins\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ranablad.no/nyheter/cruiseskip-evakuert/s/1-93-1706219|title=Cruiseskip evakuert|language=no|work=Rana Blad|date=22 August 2005|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 drydock fire ===\n\nOn 13 June 2013, a fire broke out in ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s engine room due to [[hot work]] in one of the ballast water tanks while the ship was in a [[drydock]] at the Bredo Shipyard in [[Bremerhaven]]. Due to delays in drydocking and additional repairs required by the fire, four cruises between 17 June and 1 August had to be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/travel/news/2013/06/25/hapag-lloyd-hanseatic-fire/2455171/|title=Hapag-Lloyd cancels more cruises due to shipyard fire|work=USA Today|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 collision with Venezuelan patrol boat ''Naiguat\u00e1'' ===\n[[File:Arbv GC23.jpg|thumb|right|Venezuelan Coast Guard patrol boat {{ship|Venezuelan patrol boat|Naiguat\u00e1||2}} (GC-23), which sank in March 2020 following a collision with ''RCGS Resolute'', seen during sea trials in an undated photograph.]]\n\nOn 30 March 2020, ''RCGS Resolute'' was involved in an incident off the [[Venezuela]]n coast which led to the sinking of the [[Bolivarian Navy of Venezuela|Venezuelan Coast Guard]] patrol boat {{ship|Venezuelan patrol boat|Naiguat\u00e1||2}} (GC-23) following a collision with the cruise ship.<ref name=\"bbc3Apr2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52151951|title=Venezuela navy vessel sinks after 'ramming cruise ship'|publisher=BBC News|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Initial reports ====\n\nIn a statement released by Venezuela on 31 March, ''RCGS Resolute'' was accused of committing an act of \"aggression and piracy\" by intentionally ramming and sinking ''Naiguat\u00e1'' while the patrol boat was conducting a maritime traffic control operation, as well as of acting \"cowardly and criminal\" for not participating in the search and rescue of the patrol boat's crew of 44, all of which were rescued by other Venezuelan vessels.<ref name=\"bbc3Apr2020\" /><ref name=\"bnv_statement\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mindefensa.gob.ve/mindefensa/2020/03/31/comunicado-oficial-de-la-fuerza-armada-nacional-bolivariana-5/|title=Comunicado Oficial de la Fuerza Armada Nacional Bolivariana|language=Spanish|publisher=Ministry of Defense|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> An illustration of the incident released by the Venezuelan Navy describes ''RCGS Resolute'' turning hard starboard to ram ''Naiguat\u00e1'' while the patrol boat was sailing alongside the cruise ship. Video footage later released by the Venezuelan Navy first show a ''Naiguat\u00e1'' crewman firing warning shots with an [[AK-47]] assault rifle, followed by the patrol boat taking water following a collision with ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s visibly damaged bow.<ref name=\"thedrive\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/32893/video-emerges-of-venezuelan-navy-ship-firing-on-and-colliding-with-cruise-ship-before-sinking|title=Video Emerges Of Venezuelan Navy Ship Firing On And Colliding With Cruise Ship Before Sinking|date=4 April 2020|publisher=The Drive|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> In addition, Venezuela has also alleged that Portuguese-flagged ''RCGS Resolute'' was carrying mercenaries for attacking the country's military bases and the ship's inflatable Zodiac boats were intended to transport them to shore.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hisutton/2020/04/05/venezuelan-navy-retweets-questionable-evidence-in-resolute-case/#6363ebc77a2d|title=Venezuelan Navy Retweets Questionable \u2018Evidence\u2019 In Cruise Ship Case|publisher=Forbes|first=H.I.|last=Sutton|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a statement released on 1 April by [[Columbia Cruise Services]], the company responsible for technical management of ''RCGS Resolute'', the cruise ship was approached by ''Naiguat\u00e1'' in [[international waters]], about {{convert|13|nmi}} from [[La Tortuga Island]], [[Venezuela]], shortly after midnight. ''RCGS Resolute'', which had left Buenos Aires on 5 March,<ref name=\"chronicleherald17march\" /> had been adrift in the open sea for a day while carrying out routine maintenance on the starboard main engine before reaching her next destination, [[Willemstad]] in [[Cura\u00e7ao]]. After having questioned her intentions over radio, the Venezuelan Coast Guard vessel ordered ''RCGS Resolute'' to follow her to  [[Puerto Moreno]] on the eastern side of [[Margarita Island]]. While the master was in contact with the company's head office and [[designated person ashore]] (DPA), warning shots were fired from ''Naiguat\u00e1'' and, shortly afterwards, the Venezuelan patrol boat purposely rammed the cruise ship's starboard bow. During an apparent attempt to change the heading of ''RCGS Resolute'' towards Venezuelan territorial waters, ''Naiguat\u00e1'' came in contact with the cruise ship's [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] [[bulbous bow]], started to take water, and eventually sank. ''RCGS Resolute'', which had a crew of 32 onboard but was not carrying passengers, survived the encounter with superficial damage and remained on site for over an hour to provide assistance until being allowed to continue towards Willemstad by Joint [[Rescue Coordination Centre]] (JRCC) Cura\u00e7ao.<ref name=\"ccs_statement\">{{cite  web|url=https://www.columbia-cs.com/statement-on-rcgs-resolute-incident/|title=Statement on RCGS RESOLUTE incident|publisher=Columbia Cruise Services|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Portuguese investigation ====\n{{commonscat|IMO 9000168|RCGS Resolute}}\nOn 6 April, the Office for the Investigation of Maritime Accidents and the Aeronautical Meteorology Authority (Gabinete de Investiga\u00e7\u00e3o de Acidentes Mar\u00edtimos e da Autoridade para a Meteorologia Aeron\u00e1utica; GAMA) of Portugal released a technical investigation report on the incident involving the Portuguese-flagged cruise ship.<ref name=\"gamareport\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gama.mm.gov.pt/images/Relatorios_Tecnicos/2020-065_RCGS_RESOLUTE.pdf|title=Relat\u00f3rio de Investiga\u00e7\u00e3o T\u00e9cnica / Investigation report|language=Portuguese|publisher=Gabinete de Investiga\u00e7\u00e3o de Acidentes Mar\u00edtimos e da Autoridade para a Meteorologia Aeron\u00e1utica (GAMA)|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the report, ''RCGS Resolute'' had departed Buenos Aires on 5 March and sailed to the [[Caribbean Sea]] along the South American coastline. On 28 March, the vessel had stopped in the open sea to allow the crew to carry out maintenance work in the engine room. After drifting closer to the Venezuelan coast on the following day, ''RCGS Resolute'' had resumed sailing west for about 90 minutes until the ship had passed La Tortuga Island and then continued adrift to a westerly direction while the starboard main engine [[turbocharger]] was being serviced.<ref name=\"gamareport\" />\n\nOn the night of 30 March, ''RCGS Resolute'' was contacted by the Venezuelan Coast Guard patrol boat ''Naiguat\u00e1'' at around quarter past midnight. After a brief questioning over VHF, the cruise ship was ordered to follow the Venezuelan vessel to Puerto Moreno on the basis that the Portuguese-flagged vessel was violating Venezuelan territorial waters. After consulting with the company designated person ashore (DPA), ''RCGS Resolute'' announced that the vessel would start engines and resume voyage to Cura\u00e7ao.<ref name=\"gamareport\" />\n\nAt around 01:05 [[Time in Venezuela|local time]], ''Naiguat\u00e1'' approached ''RCGS Resolute'' from the starboard quarter and, after suddenly changing course to port, collided with the bow of the cruise ship at a relative angle of about 45 degrees between the vessels. Few minutes after the initial impact, ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s master ordered the port side [[controllable pitch propeller]] first to zero pitch and then to astern thrust in order to separate the two vessels. The company DPA instructed the cruise ship to remain on site and contact the local Maritime Rescue Coordination Centre (MRCC). At 01:38, about half an hour after the collision, ''Naiguat\u00e1''{{'}}s [[AIS-SART]] was activated but ''RCGS Resolute'' was unable to establish contact with the sinking Venezuelan vessel over VHF and instead reached out to JRCC Cura\u00e7ao. About one hour later, the Venezuelan crew was seen preparing [[liferaft]]s for launching. At 02:43, JRCC Cura\u00e7ao relayed a statement from the Venezuelan authority responsible for the region, MRCC La Guairaa, that ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s assistance was no longer needed on site and instructed the cruise ship to proceed to Willemstad in order to avoid problems with the Venezuelan Navy.<ref name=\"gamareport\" />\n\nAlthough the Portuguese authorities have not obtained statements from Venezuela, the report discusses the possibility that the unexpected change in ''Naiguat\u00e1''{{'}}s heading just before the collision, as reported by ''RCGS Resolute'', may have been caused by a suction effect between the vessels as the faster patrol boat passed the bow of the cruise ship. Although the collision may have not been intentional ramming, the conclusion was nonetheless that the incident that led to the sinking of ''Naiguat\u00e1'' was a deliberate act initiated by the Venezuelan Navy rather than an accidental occurrence.<ref name=\"gamareport\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Hapag-Lloyd Cruises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:RCGS Resolute}}\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:1991 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Rauma, Finland]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cruise ship}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=''RCGS Resolute''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = RCGS Resolute.jpg\n| Ship caption = ''RCGS Resolute'' in [[Aberdeen]] in June 2019\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship name = *''Society Adventurer'' (1991\u20131993)\n*''Hanseatic'' (1993\u20132018)\n*''RCGS Resolute'' (2018\u2013present)\n| Ship owner = * [[Discoverer Reederei]] (planned)<ref name=\"id\" />\n* Society Adventurer Shipping Company (1991\u20131993)<ref name=\"id\" />\n* Bunnys Adventure & Cruise Shipping Co Ltd (1993\u2013present)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship operator = * [[Hanseatic Tours]] (1993\u20131997)\n* [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] (1997\u20132018)\n* [[One Ocean Expeditions]] (2018\u20132019)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship registry = * [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]], {{BAH}} (1991\u20132018)\n* [[Madeira, Portugal|Madeira]], {{POR}} (2018\u2013present)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship route = \n| Ship ordered = 22 December 1989<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship builder = [[Rauma Yards]] ([[Rauma, Finland|Rauma]], [[Finland]])<ref name=\"id\">{{cite|last1=Id|first1=Kalle|last2=Peter|first2=Bruce|title=Innovation and Specialisation \u2014 A History of Shipbuilding in Finland|publisher=Nautilus|year=2017|ISBN=9788790924683|page=}}</ref>\n| Ship original cost = US$75 million<ref name=\"id\" />\n| Ship yard number =306<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship laid down = 3 September 1990<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship launched = 5 January 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship completed = 7 June 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship sponsor=Ursel Klein<ref name=\"maritimereporter\">{{cite web|url=https://magazines.marinelink.com/Magazines/MaritimeReporter/199102/content/launches-luxury-cruise-200306|title=Rauma Yards Launches Luxury Cruise Ship|work=Maritime Reporter and Engineering News|date=February 1991|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship christened = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship maiden voyage = 27 March 1993<ref name=\"fof\" />\n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n|Ship identification=* [[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: CQAL6\n* {{IMO Number|9000168}}\n* {{MMSI|255806208}}<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n* {{ship register|DNV|G99209}}<ref name=\"dnv\">{{csr|register=DNV|id=G99209|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship status = In service\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = <ref name=\"dnv\" /><ref name=\"Hapag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurolloyd.com/Hapag-Lloyd/HANSEATIC.pdf|title=MS ''Hanseatic'' Ship details|publisher=Hapag-Lloyd|accessdate=28 February 2009|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| Ship type = [[Cruise ship]]\n| Ship tonnage =* {{GT|8,445}}\n* {{NetT|2,573}}\n* {{DWT|1,177}}\n| Ship displacement = 5,892{{nbsp}}tonnes<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship length = {{convert|124.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|18.00|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = \n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = {{convert|4.9|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = {{convert|7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship decks = 6\n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = [[DNV GL]] E4\n| Ship power = 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[MaK]] 8M453C (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}2,940{{nbsp}}kW)<ref name=\"seaweb\">{{csr|register=SEAWEB|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship propulsion = Two shafts; [[controllable pitch propeller]]s\n| Ship speed = {{convert|16|kn}}\n| Ship range= {{convert|8600|nmi}}\n| Ship capacity = 184 passengers in 88 cabins and four suites\n| Ship crew = 125\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n'''''RCGS Resolute''''' is a [[star (classification)|five-star]] [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] expedition [[cruise ship]] built in 1991 by [[Rauma Yards]] in Finland. She was originally named '''''Society Adventurer''''', but after [[Discoverer Reederei]] was unable to take delivery of the vessel due to financial troubles, the completed ship was laid up at the shipyard for almost two years. In 1993, she was acquired by [[Hanseatic Tours]] (which later merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd]]) and renamed '''''Hanseatic'''''. In 2018, she was chartered to [[One Ocean Expeditions]] and given her current name.\n\n== General characteristics ==\n\n''RCGS Resolute'' is {{convert|124.8|m|ftin}} [[length overall|long overall]] and {{convert|104.45|m|ftin}} [[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]], has a beam of {{convert|18|m|ftin}} and draws {{convert|4.9|m|ftin}} of water with a [[Displacement (ship)|displacement]] of {{convert|5892|t|LT}}.<ref name=\"seaweb\" /> Her [[gross tonnage]] is 8,445; [[net tonnage]] 2,573; and [[deadweight tonnage]] 1,177 tonnes. The ship's hull and propulsion system are strengthened for navigation in ice-covered waters according to the [[DNV GL]] [[ice class]] E4,<ref name=\"dnv\" /> which is equivalent to the highest [[Finnish-Swedish ice class]] for merchant ships, 1A Super.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.finlex.fi/data/normit/43683/TRAFI_383804_03_04_01_00_2016_Vastaavuusluettelo_EN.pdf|title=Finnish ice classes equivalent to class notations of recognized classification societies and the determination of the ice classes of ships|publisher=Finnish Transport Safety Agency|date=14 November 2017|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBuilt to cater to the [[star (classification)|five-star]] luxury cruise market, interiors on the ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s six passenger-accessible decks were designed by the German architect [[Wilfried K\u00f6hnemann]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel has 88 outside cabins and, above the bridge deck, four suites for a total of 184 passengers served by a crew of 125. Public spaces include a restaurant, multiple lounges, and a 78-seat theater. The ship carries 14 [[Zodiac inflatable boat]]s to take passengers ashore during expedition cruises.<ref name=\"Hapag\" /> \n\nThe ship's propulsion system consists of two [[straight-8 engine|eight-cylinder]] [[MaK]] 8M453C four-stroke medium-speed [[diesel engine]]s, each rated {{convert|2940|kW|hp}} at 600{{nbsp}}rpm, driving two [[controllable pitch propeller]]s. Onboard electrical power is generated by two {{convert|1160|kW|hp|adj=on}} [[straight-6 engine|six-cylinder]] MaK 6M332 auxiliary diesel generators and two {{convert|1040|kW|hp|adj=on}} main engine driven shaft generators. For maneuvering in ports, the ship has a {{convert|700|kW|hp|adj=on}} transverse [[bow thruster]].<ref name=\"seaweb\" /><ref name=\"dnv\" /> ''RCGS Resolute'' has a service speed of {{convert|16|kn}} and a cruising range of {{convert|8600|nmi}}.<ref name=\"Hapag\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== ''Society Adventurer'' ===\n\nIn December 1989, the German cruise ship company [[Discoverer Reederei]] decided to order a $75 million expedition cruise ship for its US-based subsidiary [[Society Expeditions]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The shipbuilding contract was awarded to [[Rauma Yards]], a new Finnish company established in August of the same year following the disbanding of [[Rauma-Repola]]'s shipyard group.<ref name=\"meriteollisuus\">{{cite web|url=https://meriteollisuus.teknologiateollisuus.fi/sites/meriteollisuus/files/inline-files/Meriteoll_historiikki_web.pdf|title=Kun rauta kelluu \u2014 V\u00e4l\u00e4hdyksi\u00e4 suomalaisen meriteollisuuden vuosisadasta|publisher=Meriteollisuus|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> The ship, launched on 5 January 1991 as ''Society Adventurer'',<ref name=\"dnv\" /> was intended for adventure-style cruises to remote destinations such as [[Antarctica]] and had, among other features, an ice-strengthened hull. However, Discoverer Reederei was unable to take delivery of the vessel in the following summer due to financial troubles and also had to cancel a [[sister ship]] that had already been contracted.<ref name=\"id\" /><ref name=\"maritimereporter\" /> As a result, the ownership of the vessel was transferred to Rauma Yards's newly-established Bahamas-registered subsidiary, Society Adventurer Shipping Company, on 7 June 1991.<ref name=\"dnv\" /> Later that year, Rauma Yards was merged with another local shipbuilder, [[Hollming]], as [[Finnyards]].<ref name=\"meriteollisuus\" /> While on a lay-up at the yard, ''Society Adventurer'' was inspected by a number of parties interested in acquiring the vessel, among them the future [[president of the United States]] [[Donald Trump]] who visited [[Rauma, Finland|Rauma]] in 1992.<ref name=\"id\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ls24.fi/uutiset/donald-trump-kavi-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-nayttelijavaimo-naytti-poseeraamisen-mallia|title=Donald Trump k\u00e4vi Raumalla laivakaupoilla - n\u00e4yttelij\u00e4vaimo n\u00e4ytti poseeraamisen mallia|work=L\u00e4nsi-Suomi|date=21 May 2016|accessdate=4 April 2020|language=fi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.satakunnankansa.fi/satakunta/donald-trump-piipahti-1992-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-ja-tansseissa-13973980|title=Donald Trump piipahti 1992 Raumalla laivakaupoilla ja tansseissa|work=Satakunnan Kansa|date=9 November 2016|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Hanseatic'' ===\n[[File:Hanseatic 5.jpg|thumb|left|''Hanseatic'' sporting the classic [[Hamburg Atlantic Line]] livery in Nuuk, Greenland, in 2008.]]\n\nIn 1993, the ship was chartered and shortly afterwards purchased by the German expedition cruise operator [[Hanseatic Tours]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The company had been established two years earlier by [[Dirk Moldenhauer]], who had been the last captain of [[German Atlantic Line]]'s cruise ship [[TS Maxim Gorkiy|''Hanseatic'']] in 1973 and later acquired rights to the classic Hamburg Atlantic Line logo, livery and the name \"Hanseatic\".<ref name=\"simplonpc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.simplonpc.co.uk/HamburgAtlantik.html|title=Hamburg Atlantik Line/Deutsche Atlantik Line/Hanseatic Tours|accessdate=4 April 2020|author=Ian Boyle|work=Simplon Postcards}}</ref> ''Society Adventurer'' was renamed ''Hanseatic'' on 23 March 1993,<ref name=\"schwerdtner\">{{cite|title=German Luxury Ocean Liners: From Kaiser Wilhelm Der Grosse to Aidastella|last=Schwerdtner|first=Nils|publisher=Amberley Publishing|year=2013|}}</ref> becoming the fourth ship to bear the name, and the original blue-yellow-white Discoverer Reederei livery was replaced with the white hull and red decorative stripes.<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel's maiden cruise from [[Hamburg]] to [[Sevilla]] began on 27 March 1993.<ref name=\"fof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.faktaomfartyg.se/society_adventurer_1991.htm|title=M/S Society Adventurer|work=Fakta om Fartyg|last=Asklander|first=Micke|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> When Hanseatic Tours was merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] in 1997, ''Hanseatic'' retained her original name as well as Hamburg Atlantic Line livery and funnel logo until rebranding in 2011.<ref name=\"schwerdtner\" /><ref name=\"seatrade\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seatrade-cruise.com/news-headlines/former-hanseatic-leaves-germany-after-long-career-hapag-lloyd|title=Former Hanseatic leaves Germany after long career with Hapag-Lloyd|work=Seatrade Cruise News|publisher=Informa Markets|date=8 October 2018|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Hanseatic'' remained in Hapag-Lloyd's fleet until 2018. Over the ship's 25-year career and a total of 667 cruises, she made 128 expeditions to Antarctica, two voyages to the [[Northern Sea Route]] (Northeast Passage), and transited the full length of the [[Northwest Passage]] 11 times.<ref name=\"seatrade\" /> The latter is a record number for passenger ships, exceeded only by the Russian [[icebreaker]] ''[[Kapitan Khlebnikov]]'' which is also used for expedition cruises.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spri.cam.ac.uk/resources/infosheets/northwestpassage.pdf|title=Transits of the Northwest Passage to the end of the 2019 navigation season|publisher=Scott Polar Research Institute|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> ''Hanseatic'' also holds the record for having been further north among passenger-carrying ships that are not icebreakers: on 26 August 2014, the vessel reached {{Coord|85|40.7|N|135|39.6|E|display=inline}}, {{convert|259|nmi}} from the [[North Pole]], due to unusually easy ice conditions in the Russian Arctic at that time.<ref name=\"seatrade\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelpulse.com/news/cruise/expedition-ship-hanseatic-sets-new-record-for-passenger-ships.html|title=Expedition Ship Hanseatic Sets New Record for Passenger Ships|publisher=Travel Pulse|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''RCGS Resolute'' ===\n\nIn June 2017, the Canada-based cruise ship operator [[One Ocean Expeditions]] announced that it would expand its fleet of expedition cruise ships with a long-term charter of the former ''Hanseatic''. The ship would be renamed ''RCGS Resolute'' after the 1850-built [[Royal Navy]] Arctic exploration vessel [[HMS Resolute|HMS ''Resolute'']] as well as the [[Inuit]] hamlet [[Resolute, Nunavut|Resolute]] in [[Nunavut]]. Furthermore, the ship would carry the initials of the [[Royal Canadian Geographic Society]] (RCGS) with whom One Ocean Expeditions had partnered.<ref name=\"oneocean_july2017\">{{cite web|url=https://discover.oneoceanexpeditions.com/rcgs-resolute/|title=One Ocean Expeditions Expands Fleet and Operations with New Vessel: RCGS RESOLUTE|publisher=One Ocean Expeditions|date=June 2017|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> After concluding her career with Hapag-Lloyd, a brief drydocking in Germany and reflagging from the Bahamas to Portugal, the vessel headed to Canada in October 2018 under her new name and with a new livery.<ref name=\"seatrade\" />\n\nIn 2019, the company's financial difficulties began to surface with the sudden withdrawal of the Russian research vessels ''[[Akademik Ioffe]]'' and ''[[Akademik Sergey Vavilov]]'' chartered from the [[Shirshov Institute of Oceanology]]. Although One Ocean Expeditions initially called the Russian owner's action a contract violation, it was later revealed that the company had failed to pay charter and fueling fees to the intermediate charterer Terragelida Ship Management which had then terminated the contract.<ref name=\"guardian_oct2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.pe.ca/business/regional-business/shipping-news-one-ocean-expeditions-sails-into-troubled-waters-370614/|title=SHIPPING NEWS: One Ocean Expeditions sails into troubled waters|date=31 October 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020|work=The Guardian|publisher=Saltwire Network}}</ref> This left One Ocean Expeditions with just one ship, ''RCGS Resolute''. In August, she was briefly arrested in [[Iqaluit]] over a C$100,000 payment dispute. While this issue was reportedly solved quickly,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/cruise-ship-briefly-arrested-in-nunavut|title= Cruise Ship Briefly Arrested in Nunavut|publisher=The Maritime Executive|date=19 August 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> another arrest over non-payment of services and crew wages followed in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] next month. Finally, in October One Ocean Expeditions was forced to cancel an Antarctic cruise midway after the vessel could not be refueled due to the company's non-payment of outstanding debts. Shortly after the ship's 140 passengers disembarked, ''RCGS Resolute'' was detained in [[Buenos Aires]] over \"significant debt\".<ref name=\"guardian_oct2018\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/one-ocean-expeditions-ship-detained-1.5370649|title=Ship belonging to troubled B.C. expedition cruise company detained in Argentina|date=24 November 2019|publisher=CBC|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The company entered administration in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cruisecritic.co.uk/news/4955/|title=One Ocean Expeditions Cruise Line Collapses|work=CruiseCritic|publisher=The Independent Traveler|date=13 January 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2020, ''RCGS Resolute'' left Buenos Aires after the ship's registered owner, Bunnys Adventure & Cruise Shipping Company Limited,<ref name=\"seaweb\" /> paid a total of US$3.6 million of One Ocean Expeditions's outstanding debt to fuel suppliers, ship agents and crew members in order to avoid a court-ordered sale of the vessel.<ref name=\"chronicleherald17march\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thechronicleherald.ca/business/local-business/shipping-news-some-cruise-companies-scrap-schedule-others-continue-on-425502/|title=SHIPPING NEWS: Some cruise companies scrap schedule, others continue on|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Incidents ==\n\n=== 1996 grounding === \n\nOn 29 August 1996, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground in [[Simpson Strait]] in the Canadian Arctic. The vessel was eleven days into an eastbound transit along the Northwest Passage with 149 passengers and 110 crew, and had stopped at [[Gjoa Haven]] to let passengers ashore. Unknowingly to the crew, a green buoy marking a shallow shoal had not been removed after the previous navigating season and, over the winter months, had been moved to the northeast by about {{convert|200|m|yd}} by drifting ice. Shortly after departure, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground on the shoal at {{Coord|68|33.75|N|97|32.2|W|display=inline}}.<ref name=\"1996report\">{{cite web|url=https://bst-tsb.gc.ca/ENG/rapports-reports/marine/1996/m96h0016/M96H0016.pdf|title=Grounding of passenger vessel \"Hanseatic\" at Simpson Strait, Northwest Territories, 29 August 1996 (report number M96H0016)|publisher=Transport Safety Board of Canada|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith no danger of the vessel sinking, ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s passengers were allowed to explore the nearby islands using the ship's boats until the Russian icebreaker ''[[Kapitan Dranitsyn]]'' arrived to pick up the passengers on 5 September and continue the Northwest Passage expedition under charter by Hanseatic Tours. ''Hanseatic'' itself was successfully refloated on 8 September. While the ship's hull was damaged during the grounding, no oil spilled to the sea and there were no injuries among the passengers or the crew.<ref name=\"1996report\" />\n\n=== 1997 grounding ===\n\nOn 14 July 1997, ''Hanseatic'' was grounded on a sand bank in [[Murchisonfjorden]] in [[Svalbard]] with 145 passengers onboard.<ref>{{cite book|title=Navigation Safety and Risk Assessment Challenges in the High North|last1=Marchenko|first1=N.|last2=Borch|first2=O.J.|last3=Andreassen|first3=N.|last4=Kuznetsova|first4=S.Yu.|last5=Ingimundarson|first5=V.|last6=Jakobsen|first6=U.|work=Marine Navigation: Proceedings of the 12th International Conference on Marine Navigation and Safety of Sea Transportation (TransNav 2017), June 21-23, 2017, Gdynia, Poland|publisher=CRC Press|year=2017|page=345|isbn=978-13-5158-218-6}}</ref><ref name=\"penguins\">{{cite book|last=Wright|first=Christopher|title=Of Penguins and Polar Bears: A History of Cold Water Cruising|year=2020|publisher=The History Press|ISBN=978-07-5099-456-9}}</ref> No injuries nor damage to the ship was reported, and the passengers were again taken to explore nearby islands on ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s Zodiac boats while awaiting evacuation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/0e7c429f30ac4d87307fb0eea3de2220|title=Cruise ship stuck in Arctic after running aground|date=14 July 1997|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> By 17 July, the ship had been refloated and was heading towards [[Longyearbyen]] for inspection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelweekly.com/Cruise-Travel/Hanseatic-Grounded-in-the-Arctic|title=Hanseatic Grounded in the Arctic|date=17 July 1997|publisher=Travel Weekly|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2005 grounding ===\n\nIn August 2005, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground near the island of [[Lur\u00f8ya, Nordland|Lur\u00f8ya]] on the Norwegian coast, just south of the [[Arctic Circle]], with 160 passengers onboard. While the vessel was not in danger of sinking despite a {{convert|5|m|ft|adj=on}} hole in one of her [[ballast water]] tank, the passengers and part of the crew was nonetheless evacuated.<ref name=\"penguins\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ranablad.no/nyheter/cruiseskip-evakuert/s/1-93-1706219|title=Cruiseskip evakuert|language=no|work=Rana Blad|date=22 August 2005|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 drydock fire ===\n\nOn 13 June 2013, a fire broke out in ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s engine room due to [[hot work]] in one of the ballast water tanks while the ship was in a [[drydock]] at the Bredo Shipyard in [[Bremerhaven]]. Due to delays in drydocking and additional repairs required by the fire, four cruises between 17 June and 1 August had to be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/travel/news/2013/06/25/hapag-lloyd-hanseatic-fire/2455171/|title=Hapag-Lloyd cancels more cruises due to shipyard fire|work=USA Today|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 collision with Venezuelan patrol boat ''Naiguat\u00e1'' ===\n[[File:Arbv GC23.jpg|thumb|right|Venezuelan Coast Guard patrol boat {{ship|Venezuelan patrol boat|Naiguat\u00e1||2}} (GC-23), which sank in March 2020 following a collision with ''RCGS Resolute'', seen during sea trials in an undated photograph.]]\n\nOn 30 March 2020, ''RCGS Resolute'' was involved in an incident off the [[Venezuela]]n coast which led to the sinking of the [[Bolivarian Navy of Venezuela|Venezuelan Coast Guard]] patrol boat {{ship|Venezuelan patrol boat|Naiguat\u00e1||2}} (GC-23) following a collision with the cruise ship.<ref name=\"bbc3Apr2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-52151951|title=Venezuela navy vessel sinks after 'ramming cruise ship'|publisher=BBC News|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Initial reports ====\n\nIn a statement released by Venezuela on 31 March, ''RCGS Resolute'' was accused of committing an act of \"aggression and piracy\" by intentionally ramming and sinking ''Naiguat\u00e1'' while the patrol boat was conducting a maritime traffic control operation, as well as of acting \"cowardly and criminal\" for not participating in the search and rescue of the patrol boat's crew of 44, all of which were rescued by other Venezuelan vessels.<ref name=\"bbc3Apr2020\" /><ref name=\"bnv_statement\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mindefensa.gob.ve/mindefensa/2020/03/31/comunicado-oficial-de-la-fuerza-armada-nacional-bolivariana-5/|title=Comunicado Oficial de la Fuerza Armada Nacional Bolivariana|language=Spanish|publisher=Ministry of Defense|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> An illustration of the incident released by the Venezuelan Navy describes ''RCGS Resolute'' turning hard starboard to ram ''Naiguat\u00e1'' while the patrol boat was sailing alongside the cruise ship. Video footage later released by the Venezuelan Navy first show a ''Naiguat\u00e1'' crewman firing warning shots with an [[AK-47]] assault rifle, followed by the patrol boat taking water following a collision with ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s visibly damaged bow.<ref name=\"thedrive\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/32893/video-emerges-of-venezuelan-navy-ship-firing-on-and-colliding-with-cruise-ship-before-sinking|title=Video Emerges Of Venezuelan Navy Ship Firing On And Colliding With Cruise Ship Before Sinking|date=4 April 2020|publisher=The Drive|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> In addition, Venezuela has also alleged that Portuguese-flagged ''RCGS Resolute'' was carrying mercenaries for attacking the country's military bases and the ship's inflatable Zodiac boats were intended to transport them to shore.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hisutton/2020/04/05/venezuelan-navy-retweets-questionable-evidence-in-resolute-case/#6363ebc77a2d|title=Venezuelan Navy Retweets Questionable \u2018Evidence\u2019 In Cruise Ship Case|publisher=Forbes|first=H.I.|last=Sutton|date=5 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a statement released by [[Columbia Cruise Services]], the company responsible for technical management of ''RCGS Resolute'', on 1 April, the cruise ship was approached by ''Naiguat\u00e1'' in [[international waters]], about {{convert|13|nmi}} from [[La Tortuga Island]], [[Venezuela]], shortly after midnight. ''RCGS Resolute'', which had left Buenos Aires on 5 March,<ref name=\"chronicleherald17march\" /> had been adrift in the open sea for a day while carrying out routine maintenance on the starboard main engine before reaching her next destination, [[Willemstad]] in [[Cura\u00e7ao]]. After having questioned her intentions over radio, the Venezuelan Coast Guard vessel ordered ''RCGS Resolute'' to follow her to  [[Puerto Moreno]] on the eastern side of [[Margarita Island]]. While the master was in contact with the company's head office and [[designated person ashore]] (DPA), warning shots were fired from ''Naiguat\u00e1'' and, shortly afterwards, the Venezuelan patrol boat purposely rammed the cruise ship's starboard bow. During an apparent attempt to change the heading of ''RCGS Resolute'' towards Venezuelan territorial waters, ''Naiguat\u00e1'' came in contact with the cruise ship's [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] [[bulbous bow]], started to take water, and eventually sank. ''RCGS Resolute'', which had a crew of 32 onboard but was not carrying passengers, survived the encounter with superficial damage and remained on site for over an hour to provide assistance until being allowed to continue towards Willemstad by Joint [[Rescue Coordination Centre]] (JRCC) Cura\u00e7ao.<ref name=\"ccs_statement\">{{cite  web|url=https://www.columbia-cs.com/statement-on-rcgs-resolute-incident/|title=Statement on RCGS RESOLUTE incident|publisher=Columbia Cruise Services|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Portuguese investigation ====\n{{commonscat|IMO 9000168|RCGS Resolute}}\nOn 6 April, the Office for the Investigation of Maritime Accidents and the Aeronautical Meteorology Authority (Gabinete de Investiga\u00e7\u00e3o de Acidentes Mar\u00edtimos e da Autoridade para a Meteorologia Aeron\u00e1utica; GAMA) of Portugal released a technical investigation report on the incident involving the Portuguese-flagged cruise ship.<ref name=\"gamareport\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gama.mm.gov.pt/images/Relatorios_Tecnicos/2020-065_RCGS_RESOLUTE.pdf|title=Relat\u00f3rio de Investiga\u00e7\u00e3o T\u00e9cnica / Investigation report|language=Portuguese|publisher=Gabinete de Investiga\u00e7\u00e3o de Acidentes Mar\u00edtimos e da Autoridade para a Meteorologia Aeron\u00e1utica (GAMA)|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the report, ''RCGS Resolute'' had departed Buenos Aires on 5 March and sailed to the [[Caribbean Sea]] along the South American coastline. On 28 March, the vessel had stopped in the open sea to allow the crew to carry out maintenance work in the engine room. After drifting closer to the Venezuelan coast on the following day, ''RCGS Resolute'' had resumed sailing west for about 90 minutes until the ship had passed La Tortuga Island and then continued adrift to a westerly direction while the starboard main engine [[turbocharger]] was being serviced.<ref name=\"gamareport\" />\n\nOn the night of 30 March, ''RCGS Resolute'' was contacted by the Venezuelan Coast Guard patrol boat ''Naiguat\u00e1'' at around quarter past midnight. After a brief questioning over VHF, the cruise ship was ordered to follow the Venezuelan vessel to Puerto Moreno on the basis that the Portuguese-flagged vessel was violating Venezuelan territorial waters. After consulting with the company designated person ashore (DPA), ''RCGS Resolute'' announced that the vessel would start engines and resume voyage to Cura\u00e7ao.<ref name=\"gamareport\" />\n\nAt around 01:05 [[Time in Venezuela|local time]], ''Naiguat\u00e1'' approached ''RCGS Resolute'' from the starboard quarter and, after suddenly changing course to port, collided with the bow of the cruise ship at a relative angle of about 45 degrees between the vessels. Few minutes after the initial impact, ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s master ordered the port side [[controllable pitch propeller]] first to zero pitch and then to astern thrust in order to separate the two vessels. The company DPA instructed the cruise ship to remain on site and contact the local Maritime Rescue Coordination Centre (MRCC). At 01:38, about half an hour after the collision, ''Naiguat\u00e1''{{'}}s [[AIS-SART]] was activated but ''RCGS Resolute'' was unable to establish contact with the sinking Venezuelan vessel over VHF and instead reached out to JRCC Cura\u00e7ao. About one hour later, the Venezuelan crew was seen preparing [[liferaft]]s for launching. At 02:43, JRCC Cura\u00e7ao relayed a statement from the Venezuelan authority responsible for the region, MRCC La Guairaa, that ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s assistance was no longer needed on site and instructed the cruise ship to proceed to Willemstad in order to avoid problems with the Venezuelan Navy.<ref name=\"gamareport\" />\n\nAlthough the Portuguese authorities have not obtained statements from Venezuela, the report discusses the possibility that the unexpected change in ''Naiguat\u00e1''{{'}}s heading just before the collision, as reported by ''RCGS Resolute'', may have been caused by a suction effect between the vessels as the faster patrol boat passed the bow of the cruise ship. Although the collision may have not been intentional ramming, the conclusion was nonetheless that the incident that led to the sinking of ''Naiguat\u00e1'' was a deliberate act initiated by the Venezuelan Navy rather than an accidental occurrence.<ref name=\"gamareport\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Hapag-Lloyd Cruises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:RCGS Resolute}}\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:1991 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Rauma, Finland]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n", "name_user": "Tupsumato", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInitial reports", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RCGS_Resolute"}
{"title_page": "Zubair ul Hassan Kandhlawi", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Islam]]\n|image            = \n|caption          = \n|name             = Zubair Ul Hasan Kandhlawi\n|birth_date       = 30 March 1950<ref name=twocircles/>\n|birth_place      = [[Kandhla]], [[Muzaffarnagar district]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India\n|death_date       = {{Death date and age|2014|3|18|1950|3|30|df=yes}}<ref name=twocircles/>\n|death_place      = [[new Dehli]]\n|burial_place     =\n|nationality      = Indian\n|ethnicity        = \n|era              = \n|region           = \n|occupation       = [[Islamic scholar]], Da'i of [[Tablighi Jamaat]]\n|denomination     = [[Sunni]]\n|Madh'hab         = [[Hanafi]] \n|movement         = [[Deobandi]], [[Tablighi Jamaat]]<ref name=\"RN332\">{{cite book |last1=Rasheed, Nighat |title=A critical study of the reformist trends in the Indian Muslim society during the nineteenth century |location=Chapter 7 |page=332 |url=https://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/52379/13/13_chapter%207.pdf#page=70 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ZP\">{{cite book |last1=Z. Pieri |title=Tablighi Jamaat and the Quest for the London Mega Mosque: Continuity and Change |url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=q9G_BwAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&dq=zubayr%20tabligh&pg=PT61#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n|Sufi_order       = \n|disciple_of      = [[Muhammad Zakariya Kandhlawi]]\n|alma_mater       = [[Mazahir Uloom Saharanpur]]\n|main_interests   = dawah\n|notable_ideas    = \n|works            = \n|influences       = [[Muhammad Ilyas Kandhlawi]], [[Muhammad Yusuf Kandhlawi]], [[Muhammad Zakariya Kandhlawi]], [[Inamul Hasan Kandhlawi]], [[Maulana Iftikhar ul Hassan]]\n|term1            = June 1995{{spaced ndash}}18 March 2014\n|predecessor1     = [[Inamul Hasan Kandhlawi]]\n}}\nSucceeder.        = [[Maulana saad kandhlawi\n\n'''Zubair-ul-\u1e24asan kandhlawi''' {{circa}} (30 March 1950{{spaced ndash}}18 March 2014)<ref name=IndianExpress/><ref name=Siasat>[https://archive.siasat.com/news/moulana-zubair-ul-hasan-passed-away-555219/ Maulana Zubair-ul-Hasan passed away] The Siasat Daily (newspaper), Published 19 March 2014, Retrieved 27 February 2020</ref> was an [[India]]n [[Islamic scholar]] and [[Emir|emir]] (top leader) of [[Tablighi Jamaat]] in India.<ref name=twocircles>[http://twocircles.net/2014mar21/demise_tablighi_jamaat_ameer_spread_sadness_among_muslims.html Maulana Zubair ul Hasan's obituary and profile on TwoCircles.net website], Published 21 March 2014, Retrieved 27 February 2020</ref><ref name=\"MZF79\">{{cite book |last1=MOHD.ZAKIRULLAH |first1=FIRDAUSI |title=Political Ideology of Abul Ala Maududi |page=79 |url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=tzF8BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA79#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Deobandi}}\n\n==Early life and career==\nZubair-ul-\u1e24asan was born on 30 March 1950 in the town of [[Kandhla]] in present-day [[Muzaffarnagar district]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]. He studied at [[Mazahir Uloom Saharanpur]], Uttar Pradesh, India.<ref name=IndianExpress/> He was a disciple, and subsequently a ''khaleefa'' (an accredited successor) of his eminent maternal grandfather Shaikh-ul-Hadees Maulana [[Muhammad Zakariyya al-Kandhlawi]] who was also a celebrated Muslim leader and was an early and life-long booster of Tablighi Jamaat. Zubair graduated and completed his education in 1971. Maulana Zubair was the leader of the concluding prayers at the world congregations held annually at [[Bishwa Ijtema]] [[Dhaka]], [[Raiwind]] and [[Bhopal]].<ref name=IndianExpress/><ref name=twocircles/>\n\nDue to his obesity, he was often seen in a wheelchair. He was largely known for his concluding prayers rather than his long addresses and speeches in front of large gatherings as Jamaat leaders before him, including his father used to be known for.<ref name=twocircles/>\n\nHe was initially a member of the council of scholars (''International Tablighi Shura'') which was elected to run the affairs of Tablighi Jamaat after the death of his father Maulana [[Inamul Hasan Kandhlawi]]. After his death, his burial was at [[Nizamuddin Dargah]] grounds in [[New Delhi]].<ref name=twocircles/><ref name=Siasat/>\n\n==Death, survivors and legacy==\nIn 1969, Maulana Zubair ul Hassan married Tahira Khatoon, daughter of Al-hafiz Ilyas of Shahranpur, one of the sons-in-law of [[Muhammad Zakariyya al-Kandhlawi]]. The couple had three sons and three daughters. The eldest son, Hafiz Maulana Juahir-ul-Hasan Kandhlawi, has become a well-known negotiator of the Tabligh movement. Reportedly Zubair was obese, diabetic and not in good health for some time. According to [[New Delhi]] police estimates, nearly 20,0000 people turned up at his funeral.<ref name=twocircles/><ref name=Siasat/><ref name=IndianExpress>[https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/tablighi-jamaat-ameer-dies-thousands-turn-up-for-his-funeral-procession-at-nizamuddin/ Tablighi Jamaat Ameer dies, thousands turn up for his funeral procession at Nizamuddin] The Indian Express (newspaper), Published 19 March 2014, Retrieved 27 February 2020</ref>\n\n[[Shahi Imam]] of [[Jama Masjid, Delhi]], [[Maulana]] [[Syed Ahmed Bukhari]] said in his tribute that the late senior member of Tablighi Jamaat, Maulana Zubair ul Hassan was an important Muslim leader who worked for the benefit of the community. \" He remained non-political throughout his life and only concerned himself with matters of religion.\"<ref name=IndianExpress/><ref name=twocircles/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Muhammad Zakariya Kandhlawi]]\n* [[Muhammad Ilyas Kandhlawi]]\n* [[Inamul Hasan Kandhlawi]]\n*[[Maulana Zubair Ahmed]]\n* [[Tablighi Jamaat]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Hanafi scholars}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:ul Hassan, Maulana Zubair}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:Indian religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Tablighi Jamaat people]]\n[[Category:Indian Sunni Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n{{Islamic-scholar-stub}}\n{{india-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Islam]]\n|image            = \n|caption          = \n|name             = Zubair Ul Hasan Kandhlawi\n|birth_date       = 30 March 1950<ref name=twocircles/>\n|birth_place      = [[Kandhla]], [[Muzaffarnagar district]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India\n|death_date       = {{Death date and age|2014|3|18|1950|3|30|df=yes}}<ref name=twocircles/>\n|death_place      = [[new Dehli]]\n|burial_place     =\n|nationality      = Indian\n|ethnicity        = \n|era              = \n|region           = \n|occupation       = [[Islamic scholar]], Da'i of [[Tablighi Jamaat]]\n|denomination     = [[Sunni]]\n|Madh'hab         = [[Hanafi]] \n|movement         = [[Deobandi]], [[Tablighi Jamaat]]<ref name=\"RN332\">{{cite book |last1=Rasheed, Nighat |title=A critical study of the reformist trends in the Indian Muslim society during the nineteenth century |location=Chapter 7 |page=332 |url=https://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/52379/13/13_chapter%207.pdf#page=70 |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ZP\">{{cite book |last1=Z. Pieri |title=Tablighi Jamaat and the Quest for the London Mega Mosque: Continuity and Change |url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=q9G_BwAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&dq=zubayr%20tabligh&pg=PT61#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n|Sufi_order       = \n|disciple_of      = [[Muhammad Zakariya Kandhlawi]]\n|alma_mater       = [[Mazahir Uloom Saharanpur]]\n|main_interests   = dawah\n|notable_ideas    = \n|works            = \n|influences       = [[Muhammad Ilyas Kandhlawi]], [[Muhammad Yusuf Kandhlawi]], [[Muhammad Zakariya Kandhlawi]], [[Inamul Hasan Kandhlawi]], [[Maulana Iftikhar ul Hassan]]\n|term1            = June 1995{{spaced ndash}}18 March 2014\n|predecessor1     = [[Inamul Hasan Kandhlawi]]\n}}\n\n'''Zubair-ul-\u1e24assan''' {{circa}} (30 March 1950{{spaced ndash}}18 March 2014)<ref name=IndianExpress/><ref name=Siasat>[https://archive.siasat.com/news/moulana-zubair-ul-hasan-passed-away-555219/ Maulana Zubair-ul-Hasan passed away] The Siasat Daily (newspaper), Published 19 March 2014, Retrieved 27 February 2020</ref> was an [[India]]n [[Islamic scholar]] and [[Emir|emir]] (top leader) of [[Tablighi Jamaat]] in India.<ref name=twocircles>[http://twocircles.net/2014mar21/demise_tablighi_jamaat_ameer_spread_sadness_among_muslims.html Maulana Zubair ul Hassan's obituary and profile on TwoCircles.net website], Published 21 March 2014, Retrieved 27 February 2020</ref><ref name=\"MZF79\">{{cite book |last1=MOHD.ZAKIRULLAH |first1=FIRDAUSI |title=Political Ideology of Abul Ala Maududi |page=79 |url=https://books.google.com.sa/books?id=tzF8BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA79#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Deobandi}}\n\n==Early life and career==\nZubair-ul-\u1e24asan was born on 30 March 1950 in the town of [[Kandhla]] in present-day [[Muzaffarnagar district]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]. He studied at [[Mazahir Uloom Saharanpur]], Uttar Pradesh, India.<ref name=IndianExpress/> He was a disciple, and subsequently a ''khaleefa'' (an accredited successor) of his eminent maternal grandfather Shaikh-ul-Hadees Maulana [[Muhammad Zakariyya al-Kandhlawi]] who was also a celebrated Muslim leader and was an early and life-long booster of Tablighi Jamaat. Zubair graduated and completed his education in 1971. Maulana Zubair was the leader of the concluding prayers at the world congregations held annually at [[Bishwa Ijtema]] [[Dhaka]], [[Raiwind]] and [[Bhopal]].<ref name=IndianExpress/><ref name=twocircles/>\n\nDue to his obesity, he was often seen in a wheelchair. He was largely known for his concluding prayers rather than his long addresses and speeches in front of large gatherings as Jamaat leaders before him, including his father used to be known for.<ref name=twocircles/>\n\nHe was initially a member of the council of scholars (''International Tablighi Shura'') which was elected to run the affairs of Tablighi Jamaat after the death of his father Maulana [[Inamul Hasan Kandhlawi]]. After his death, his burial was at [[Nizamuddin Dargah]] grounds in [[New Delhi]].<ref name=twocircles/><ref name=Siasat/>\n\n==Death, survivors and legacy==\nIn 1969, Maulana Zubair ul Hassan married Tahira Khatoon, daughter of Al-hafiz Ilyas of Shahranpur, one of the sons-in-law of [[Muhammad Zakariyya al-Kandhlawi]]. The couple had three sons and three daughters. The eldest son, Hafiz Maulana Juahir-ul-Hasan Kandhlawi, has become a well-known negotiator of the Tabligh movement. Reportedly Zubair was obese, diabetic and not in good health for some time. According to [[New Delhi]] police estimates, nearly 20,0000 people turned up at his funeral.<ref name=twocircles/><ref name=Siasat/><ref name=IndianExpress>[https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/tablighi-jamaat-ameer-dies-thousands-turn-up-for-his-funeral-procession-at-nizamuddin/ Tablighi Jamaat Ameer dies, thousands turn up for his funeral procession at Nizamuddin] The Indian Express (newspaper), Published 19 March 2014, Retrieved 27 February 2020</ref>\n\n[[Shahi Imam]] of [[Jama Masjid, Delhi]], [[Maulana]] [[Syed Ahmed Bukhari]] said in his tribute that the late senior member of Tablighi Jamaat, Maulana Zubair ul Hassan was an important Muslim leader who worked for the benefit of the community. \" He remained non-political throughout his life and only concerned himself with matters of religion.\"<ref name=IndianExpress/><ref name=twocircles/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Muhammad Zakariya Kandhlawi]]\n* [[Muhammad Ilyas Kandhlawi]]\n* [[Inamul Hasan Kandhlawi]]\n*[[Maulana Zubair Ahmed]]\n* [[Tablighi Jamaat]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Hanafi scholars}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:ul Hassan, Maulana Zubair}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:Indian religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Tablighi Jamaat people]]\n[[Category:Indian Sunni Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n{{Islamic-scholar-stub}}\n{{india-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2409:4060:200e:26df::78b:80a5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zubair_ul_Hassan_Kandhlawi"}
{"title_page": "Phoebe Waller-Bridge", "text_new": "{{short description|British actress and writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Phoebe Waller-Bridge\n| image        = Phoebe Waller-Bridge on MTV International.png <!-- If replacing this image, it MUST be properly licensed. See [[WP:IUP]] -->\n| caption      = Waller-Bridge in an interview for ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]'' in 2018\n| birth_name   = Phoebe Mary Waller-Bridge\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1985|7|14}}\n| birth_place  = [[West London]], England<!--No boroughs/neighborhoods, just cities per format.-->\n| education    = [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n| occupation   = {{hlist|Actress|writer|producer}}\n| years_active = 2009\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Conor Woodman]]<br />|2014|2018|end=divorced}}\n| relatives    = [[Isobel Waller-Bridge]] (sister)\n| website      = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Phoebe Mary Waller-Bridge''' (born 14 July 1985) is an English actress, writer, and producer. She created, wrote, and starred in the [[Channel 4]] [[comedy-drama]] series ''[[Crashing (UK TV series)|Crashing]]'' (2016) and the [[BBC]] [[tragicomedy]] series ''[[Fleabag]]'' (2016\u20132019). She was also the [[showrunner]] and [[executive producer]] for the first series of the [[BBC]] thriller series ''[[Killing Eve]]'' (2018\u2013present). Both ''Fleabag'' and ''Killing Eve'' have been highly acclaimed and named among the 100 greatest television series of the 21st century by ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title= The 100 best TV shows of the 21st century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/sep/16/100-best-tv-shows-of-the-21st-century |website=The Guardian |accessdate=27 September 2019}}.</ref>\n\nFor ''Fleabag'', she received the [[British Academy Television Award for Best Female Comedy Performance]], three [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]], and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/phoebe-waller-bridge-wins-2019-lead-comedy-actress-emmy-1203302142/|title=Emmys Surprise: Phoebe Waller-Bridge Wins Lead Actress in a Comedy|last=Turchiano|first=Danielle|last2=Turchiano|first2=Danielle|date=2019-09-23|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref>\nand two [[Golden Globe Awards]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/jan/05/the-full-list-of-golden-globes-2020-winners|title=The full list of Golden Globes 2020 winners|last=Horton|first=Adrian|date=2020-01-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nWaller-Bridge also starred in the comedy series ''[[The Caf\u00e9 (British TV series)|The Caf\u00e9]]'' (2011\u20132013) and the crime drama series ''[[Broadchurch (series 2)|Broadchurch]]'' (2015). She has appeared in films, including ''[[Albert Nobbs]]'' (2011), ''[[The Iron Lady (film)|The Iron Lady]]'' (2011), and ''[[Goodbye Christopher Robin]]'' (2017), and played the [[Droid (Star Wars)|droid]] [[Millennium Falcon#Ownership|L3-37]] in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' anthology prequel ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]'' (2018). She contributed to the screenplay of the [[List of James Bond films|25th ''James Bond'' film]], titled ''[[No Time to Die]]'' (2020).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2020/02/28/no-time-to-die-phoebe-waller-bridge-talks-her-script-revisions/|title=No Time To Die: Phoebe Waller-Bridge Talks Her Script Revisions}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPhoebe Mary Waller-Bridge was born on 14 July 1985,<ref>{{cite news |title=Phoebe Waller-Bridge |url=https://www.empireonline.com/people/phoebe-waller-bridge/ |accessdate=30 November 2019 |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]}}</ref> in [[West London]], the daughter of Theresa Mary (n\u00e9e Clerke) and Michael Cyprian Waller-Bridge.<ref>{{cite book |title=Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage |date=2011 |publisher=Debrett's Peerage Limited |page=234}}</ref> Her father founded the electronic trading platform [[Tradepoint]], while her mother works for the [[Worshipful Company of Ironmongers]].<ref name=transgressive>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/sep/08/phoebe-waller-bridge-fleabag-killing-eve-transgressive-women|title=Phoebe Waller-Bridge: 'I have an appetite for transgressive women' |last=Hattenstone |first=Simon |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=8 September 2018 |access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=Telegraph-Engagement-2014>{{cite news|title=Engagements: Mr C. T. P. Woodman and Ms P. M. Waller-Bridge|url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/engagements/172646/mr-c.t.p.-woodman-and-ms-p.m.-waller-bridge|accessdate=25 September 2016|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=18 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p18173.htm#i181724|title=Person Page: Phoebe M. Waller-Bridge|website=The Peerage}}</ref> The Waller-Bridge family were [[landed gentry]] of [[Cuckfield|Cuckfield, Sussex]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Burke's Family Index|editor1-first=Hugh|editor1-last=Montgomery-Massingberd|publisher=Burke's Peerage Limited|isbn=978-0850110227|year=1976|page=18}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Burke's Landed Gentry|publisher=Burke's Peerage Limited|edition=18th|editor1-first=Peter|editor1-last=Townend|year=1972|volume=3|page=532}}</ref> On her father's side, she is also a descendant of The Rev. Sir [[Egerton Leigh]], 2nd Baronet, [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] for [[Mid Cheshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Cheshire]] from 1873 to his death in 1876.<ref>{{cite book|title=Burke's Peerage, Knightage and Baronetage|publisher=Burke's Peerage Limited|isbn=978-0971196629|edition=107th|date=1 December 2003|volume=2|page=1646}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=[[Burke's Landed Gentry]]|publisher=Burke's Peerage Limited|edition=18th|year=1965|volume=3| page=532}}</ref> Her maternal grandfather was Sir John Edward Longueville Clerke, 12th [[Clerke baronets|baronet]], of [[Hitcham, Buckinghamshire]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Burke's Peerage, Knightage and Baronetage|publisher=Burke's Peerage Limited|isbn=978-0971196629|edition=107th|date=1 December 2003|volume=1|page=819}}</ref> Waller-Bridge grew up in [[Ealing|Ealing, London]],<ref name=Guardian-Fleabag-OnRadar-2016>{{cite news|last1=Bromwich|first1=Kathryn|title=On my radar: Phoebe Waller-Bridge's cultural highlights|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2016/sep/04/on-my-radar-phoebe-waller-bridge-mustang-libertines-louis-ck-guilty-feminist|accessdate=26 September 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=Standard-Crashing-2016>{{cite news|last1=Tate|first1=Gabriel|title=Crashing writer Phoebe Waller-Bridge talks up her new Channel 4 sitcom|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/crashing-channel-4-interview-writer-phoebe-wallerbridge-on-her-new-sitcom-about-property-guardians-a3151166.html|accessdate=19 January 2016|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=7 January 2016}}</ref> and has a younger brother named Jasper, a music manager, and an older sister named [[Isobel Waller-Bridge]], a composer who wrote the music for ''[[Fleabag]]''.<ref name=Peerage-WilliamFrancisTalbotClerke>{{cite web|title=Person Page - 22754: William Francis Talbot Clerke (descendants)|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p22754.htm|website=The Peerage|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=WilliamConqueror-13>{{cite web|last1=Freer|first1=Alan G.|title=Conqueror13|url=http://www.william1.co.uk/w13.html|website=The Descendants of William the Conqueror|accessdate=25 September 2016}}</ref> Her parents are divorced.<ref name=Telegraph-Fleabag-2016>{{cite news|last1=Day|first1=Elizabeth|title=Fleabag star Phoebe Waller-Bridge on female anger, emotional honesty -and fancying Barack Obama|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/fleabag-star-phoebe-waller-bridge-on-female-anger-emotional-hone/|accessdate=25 September 2016|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=7 July 2016}}</ref> She was educated at [[St Augustine's Priory, Ealing|St Augustine's Priory]], a [[Catholic]] independent school for girls,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sapriory.com/priory-post/priory-post-47-playwright-to-watch/|title=Priory Post 47 \u2013 Playwright to Watch|website=[[St Augustine's Priory, Ealing|St Augustine's Priory]], Ealing|date=21 August 2015|accessdate=14 May 2017}}</ref> followed by the independent sixth form college [[Abbey DLD Colleges Group|DLD College London]] in [[Marylebone|Marylebone, London]].<ref name=DLDCollegeLondon-Prospectus-2015>{{cite web|title=Academic Prospectus v. 17|url=http://www.dldcollege.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2015/07/DLD_College_London_Academic_Prospectus_V17.pdf|website=[[Abbey DLD Colleges Group|DLD College London]]|accessdate=25 September 2016|pages=29|date=2015}}</ref> She graduated from the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] in London.<ref name=Guardian-TheOne-2014>{{cite news|last1=Barnett|first1=Laura|title=Phoebe Waller-Bridge: sex, laughs and a packet of Wotsits|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/feb/16/phoebe-waller-bridge-sex-laughs-wotsits|accessdate=25 September 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=19 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2009, Waller-Bridge made her acting debut in the play ''Roaring Trade'' at [[Soho Theatre]].<ref name=Guardian-RoaringTrade-2009>{{cite news|last1=Billington|first1=Michael|title=Roaring Trade|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2009/jan/14/review-roaring-trade-soho-theatre|accessdate=26 September 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 January 2009}}</ref> In 2013, Waller-Bridge appeared in one episode of ''[[Bad Education (TV series)|Bad Education]]'' as \"India\". She appeared in the second series of drama ''[[Broadchurch]]'' in 2015.\n\nIn addition to acting, Waller-Bridge is a playwright. Her work includes the series of plays ''Good. Clean. Fun.''<ref name=\"SohoTheatre-GoodCleanFun-2015\">{{cite web|title=DryWrite presents Good. Clean. Fun|url=http://www.sohotheatre.com/whats-on/good-clean-fun|website=[[Soho Theatre]]|accessdate=19 January 2016|date=September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126041954/http://www.sohotheatre.com/whats-on/good-clean-fun|archive-date=26 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2016, Waller-Bridge wrote and starred in the [[Channel 4]] sitcom ''[[Crashing (UK TV series)|Crashing]]'' and [[BBC Three]]'s adaptation of ''[[Fleabag]]''.<ref name=\"SohoTheatre-Fleabag-2015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sohotheatre.com/whats-on/fleabag/|title=DryWrite and Soho Theatre present Fleabag|date=May 2015|website=[[Soho Theatre]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807023156/http://www.sohotheatre.com/whats-on/fleabag/|archive-date=7 August 2016|accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NickHernBooks-Fleabag-2013\">{{cite book|title=Fleabag|last1=Waller-Bridge|first1=Phoebe|date=2013|publisher=Nick Hern Books|isbn=978-1-84-842364-0|location=London|oclc=894546593}}</ref>\n\nAfter its initial release on [[BBC Three]], ''Fleabag'' was broadcast on [[BBC Two]] from August 2016. It was picked up by the on-demand [[Amazon Video]] service and premiered in the United States in September 2016.<ref name=Variety-Fleabag-Amazon-2016>{{cite web|last1=Barraclough|first1=Leo|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/global/amazon-fleabag-phoebe-waller-bridge-1201778666/|title=Amazon Acquires Comedy Series 'Fleabag' From 'Broadchurch's' Phoebe Waller-Bridge|date=19 May 2016|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=TVLine-Fleabag-Amazon-2016>{{cite web|last1=Schwartz|first1=Ryan|title=Transparent Season 3, High Castle Season 2, Woody Allen Comedy and Others Get Amazon Premiere Dates|url=http://tvline.com/2016/08/07/transparent-season-3-premiere-date-woody-allen-comedy-amazon/|date=7 August 2016|accessdate=17 July 2019|publisher=[[TVLine.com]]}}</ref> For her performance in the series she won the [[British Academy Television Award for Best Female Comedy Performance]] and was nominated for a [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Actress in a Comedy Series]]. ''Fleabag'''s second and final series aired in 2019. For the second series Waller-Bridge received [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]], and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/fleabag-set-return-bbc-amazon-2019-1202538935/|title='Fleabag' Set to Return to BBC, Amazon in 2019|last=Mitchell|first=Robert|date=25 August 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=25 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2017/fleabag-series-two|title=BBC Comedy confirms BAFTA winning Fleabag will return to BBC Three in 2019|date=25 August 2017|website=[[BBC]]|access-date=25 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nWaller-Bridge is the co-artistic director, with [[Vicky Jones]],<ref name=transgressive /> of DryWrite Theatre Company.<ref name=\"SohoTheatre-DryWrite\">{{cite web|title=DryWrite|url=http://www.sohotheatre.com/writers/writers/drywrite/|website=[[Soho Theatre]]|accessdate=25 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012002628/http://sohotheatre.com/writers/writers/drywrite|archive-date=12 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"LondonCalling-DryWrite-2014\">{{cite news|last1=Sutton-Williams|first1=Natasha|title=A Day In The Life Of: DryWrite Theatre Company| url=https://www.culturecalling.com/uk/features/a-day-in-the-life-of-dry-write-theatre-company|accessdate=25 September 2016|work=Culture Calling|date=18 February 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Metro-TheOne-2014\">{{cite news|last1=Dietrich|first1=Paul|title=Fleabag's Vicky Jones and Phoebe Waller-Bridge: The One explores cruelty in love|url=http://metro.co.uk/2014/02/20/fleabags-vicky-jones-and-phoebe-waller-bridge-the-one-explores-cruelty-in-love-4310534/|accessdate=19 January 2016|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|date=20 February 2014}}</ref> The two met and became friends while working on theatre productions.<ref name=\"NewStatesman-Fleabag-2016\">{{cite news|last1=Leszkiewicz| first1=Anna| title=\"I always want to go darker\": Phoebe Waller-Bridge on Fleabag, slutty pizza and guinea pig murder| url=http://www.newstatesman.com/culture/tv-radio/2016/08/i-always-want-go-darker-phoebe-waller-bridge-fleabag-slutty-pizza-and|accessdate=26 September 2016|work=[[New Statesman]]|date=18 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nWaller-Bridge voiced and performed [[droid (Star Wars)|droid]] [[Millennium Falcon#Ownership|L3-37]] in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' film ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]'' (2018).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.starwars.com/news/han-solo-smuggler-scoundrel-hero-new-star-wars-story-begins|title=Han Solo - Smuggler. Scoundrel. Hero. A New Star Wars Story Begins|date=21 February 2017|work=StarWars.com|access-date=21 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170221182257/http://www.starwars.com/news/han-solo-smuggler-scoundrel-hero-new-star-wars-story-begins|archive-date=21 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-39045406|title=Star Wars: First picture of Han Solo film team released|date=22 February 2017|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=22 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nWaller-Bridge wrote and produced the thriller television series ''[[Killing Eve]]'' based on novels by [[Luke Jennings]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/bbc-america-dark-thriller-series-killing-eve-from-fleabag-creator-1201854674/|title=BBC America Greenlights Dark Thriller Series 'Killing Eve' From 'Fleabag' Creator|last=Petski|first=Denise|date=15 November 2016|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=27 January 2018}}</ref> The [[BBC America]] series stars [[Sandra Oh]] and [[Jodie Comer]] and premiered in April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/sandra-oh-ecstatic-female-thriller-killing-eve-greys-anatomy-1202241915/|title=Sandra Oh Is \"Ecstatic\" To Be Part Of Empowering Female-Centric Thriller 'Killing Eve'|last=Blyth|first=Antonia|date=12 January 2018|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=27 January 2018}}</ref> For her work on the script, she received a nomination for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Drama Series]].\n\nIn March 2019, [[HBO]] ordered the series ''[[Run (American TV series)|Run]]'', which is executive-produced by Waller-Bridge and stars [[Domhnall Gleeson]] and [[Merritt Wever]] in lead roles.<ref name=\"Run-HBO\">{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/run-hbo-picks-up-comedic-thriller-to-series-fleabag-duo-eone-1202570738/|first1=Nellie|last1=Andreeva|first2=Mike|last2=Fleming Jr.| title='Run': HBO Gives Series Order To Comedic Thriller Starring Domhnall Gleeson & Merritt Wever From 'Fleabag' Duo & eOne|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=6 March 2019|accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref> Waller-Bridge also features in the series with a recurring role as the character Flick.<ref name=\"Run-HBO-2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/hbo-orders-phoebe-waller-bridges-run-series-1192760|first=Rick|last=Porter| title=Phoebe Waller-Bridge's 'Run' Ordered to Series at HBO|work=[[Hollywood Reporter]]|date=15 September 2019|accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Waller-Bridge co-wrote the screenplay for ''[[No Time to Die]]'' (2020), the 25th [[List of James Bond films|''James Bond'' film]], along with [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade|Neal Purvis]] and [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade|Robert Wade]].<ref name=\"Bond-25\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/apr/14/james-bond-script-phoebe-waller-bridge-fleabag-daniel-craig|title=Phoebe Waller-Bridge brought in to liven up new Bond script|last=Brooks|first=Richard|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=14 April 2019|accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=James Bond film title revealed as No Time To Die |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-49410251 |accessdate=20 August 2019 |agency=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWaller-Bridge lives in [[Kensal Green|Kensal Rise, London]]. She married Irish presenter and documentary filmmaker [[Conor Woodman]] in 2014.<ref name=Standard-Crashing-2016 /> By 2017, the couple had separated and filed for divorce, which was finalised in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/phoebe-waller-bridge-conor-woodman-divorce |title=Phoebe Waller-Bridge and Her Husband Are Divorcing |last=Logan |first=Elizabeth|work=[[W (magazine)|W]] |date=31 December 2017 |access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref> Since early 2018, Waller-Bridge has been in a relationship with English-Irish playwright [[Martin McDonagh]].<ref name=transgressive /> She describes herself as an atheist, although she \"hopped around a bit from religion to religion\" while growing up in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-phoebe-waller-bridge-fleabag-20190524-story.html|title=Phoebe Waller-Bridge finds God and naughty glee in \u2018Fleabag\u2019s\u2019 second season|date=2019-05-24|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 2009 ||''The Reward''||Charlotte||Short film\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2011 || ''Beautiful Enough'' ||Composer (voice)||Short film\n|-\n|''Meconium'' ||Lorna||Short film\n|-\n|''[[Albert Nobbs]]''||Viscountess Yarrell ||\n|-\n|''[[The Iron Lady (film)|The Iron Lady]]''||Susie ||\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Man Up (film)|Man Up]]''||Katie ||\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Goodbye Christopher Robin]]''||Mary Brown ||\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]''||L3-37||\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Fleabag|National Theatre Live: Fleabag]]'' || Fleabag || Theatrical Event\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n|2009||''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]''||Katie Burbridge||Episode: \"Chef's Secret\"\n|-\n|2010||''[[How Not to Live Your Life]]''||Felicity||Episode: \"Don's Posh Weekend\"\n|-\n|2011||''The Night Watch''||Lauren||Television film\n|-\n|2011\u20132013||''[[The Caf\u00e9 (UK TV series)|The Caf\u00e9]]''||Chloe Astill||13 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2013 || ''[[Coming Up (TV series)|Coming Up]]''||Karen||Episode: \"Henry\"\n|-\n|''London Irish''||Steph||Episode: \"Episode 2\"\n|-\n|''[[Bad Education (TV series)|Bad Education]]''||India||Episode: \"Drugs\"\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Glue (TV series)|Glue]]''||Bee Warwick||2 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2015 || ''[[Broadchurch (series 2)|Broadchurch]]''||Abby||8 episodes\n|-\n|''Flack''||Eve||Television film\n|-\n|2016||''[[Crashing (UK TV series)|Crashing]]''||Lulu||Creator, writer; 6 episodes\n|-\n|2016\u20132019||''[[Fleabag]]''||Fleabag ||Creator, executive producer, writer; 12 episodes\n|-\n|2019||''[[Saturday Night Live]]''||Herself (host)||Episode: \"Phoebe Waller-Bridge/[[Taylor Swift]]\"\n|-\n|2020||''[[Run (American TV series)|Run]]''|| Flick || 2 episodes; executive producer\n|}\n\n===Theatre===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!class=\"unsortable\" |Venue\n! Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2005\n|''[[The School for Scandal]]''\n| Performer\n| [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n|\n|-\n|''Imperceptible Mutabilities <br/> of the Third Kingdom''\n| Performer\n| Royal Academy of Dramatic Art\n|\n|-\n|''[[A Dance of the Forests]]''\n| Performer\n| Royal Academy of Dramatic Art\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Timon of Athens|The Life of Timon of Athens]]''\n| Performer\n| Royal Academy of Dramatic Art\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2007\n|''Is Everyone OK?''\n| Performer\n|[[Latitude Festival]], Suffolk\n|\n|-\n|''Crazy Love''\n|Billie\n|[[Paines Plough]]\n|<ref name=The-Guardian-Crazy-Love-2007>{{cite news|last1=Gardner|first1=Lyn|title=Crazy Love, Shunt Vaults, London|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2007/nov/09/theatre|accessdate=3 May 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=10 November 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Twelfth Night]]''\n|Viola\n|Sprite Productions\n|<ref name=The-Press-Twelfth-Night-2008>{{cite news|last1=Hutchinson|first1=Charles|title=Review: Twelfth Night, Sprite Productions, Ripley Castle, Ripley. Until July 13|url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/leisure/theatre/3181923.review-twelfth-night-sprite-productions-ripley-castle-ripley-until-july-13/|accessdate=3 May 2019|work=[[The Press|The Press (York)]]|date=27 June 2008}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2009\n|''Roaring Trade''\n|Jess\n|[[Soho Theatre]], London \n|<ref name=HayFever2012>{{cite news|last1=Marshall|first1=Charlotte|title=Introducing... Phoebe Waller-Bridge|url=http://www.officiallondontheatre.co.uk/news/latest-news/article/item134920|accessdate=25 September 2016|work=Official London Theatre|date=14 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304201438/http://www.officiallondontheatre.co.uk/news/latest-news/article/item134920 |archive-date=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|''2 May 1997''\n| Sarah\n|[[Bush Theatre|The Bush Theatre]], London\n|<ref name=\"HayFever2012\" />\n|-\n|''[[Rope (play)|Rope]]''\n|Leila Arden\n|[[Almeida Theatre]], London\n|<ref name=\"HayFever2012\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2010\