92\u200ePersonal life:updated bare url", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phoebe_Waller-Bridge"}
{"title_page": "Inception", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|2010 science fiction action film directed by Christopher Nolan}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Inception\n| image          = Inception (2010) theatrical poster.jpg\n| alt            = A man in a suit with a gun in his right hand is flanked by five other individuals in the middle of a street which, behind them, is folded upwards. Leonardo DiCaprio's name and those of other cast members are shown above the words \"Your Mind Is the Scene of the Crime\". The title of the film \"INCEPTION\", film credits, and theatrical and IMAX release dates are shown at the bottom.\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Christopher Nolan]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Emma Thomas]]\n* Christopher Nolan\n}}\n| writer         = Christopher Nolan\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Leonardo DiCaprio]]\n* [[Ken Watanabe]]\n* [[Joseph Gordon-Levitt]]\n* [[Marion Cotillard]]\n* [[Ellen Page]]\n* [[Tom Hardy]]\n* [[Cillian Murphy]]\n* [[Tom Berenger]]\n* [[Michael Caine]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Hans Zimmer]]\n| cinematography = [[Wally Pfister]]\n| editing        = [[Lee Smith (editor)|Lee Smith]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Legendary Pictures]]\n* [[Syncopy Inc.|Syncopy]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2010|07|08|[[Odeon Leicester Square]]|2010|07|16|United States and United Kingdom}}\n| runtime        = 148 minutes<ref>{{cite web |title=Inception |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/inception-2010-2 |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=June 29, 2010 |accessdate=August 8, 2010}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States<ref name=\"Lumiere\">{{cite web|url=http://lumiere.obs.coe.int/web/film_info/?id=34895|title=Film: Inception|publisher=[[Lumiere (database)|Lumiere]]|accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n* United Kingdom<ref name=\"Lumiere\"/>\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $160 million<ref name=\"Mojo\">{{cite web |title=Inception (2010) |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt1375666/ |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=January 16, 2011}}</ref>\n| gross          = $829.9 million<ref name=\"Mojo\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Inception''''' is a 2010 <!--- Per [[WP:FILMLEAD]], do not add American-British or British-American: \"If the nationality is not singular, cover the different national interests later in the lead section.\"--->[[science fiction action film]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.warnerbros.com/movies/inception/|title=WarnerBros.com - Inception|website=[[Warner Bros]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/inception/|title=INCEPTION|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]}}</ref> written and directed by [[Christopher Nolan]], who also produced the film with his wife, [[Emma Thomas]]. The film stars [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] as a professional thief who [[corporate espionage|steals information]] by infiltrating the [[subconscious]] of his targets. He is offered a chance to have his criminal history erased as payment for the implantation of another person's idea into a target's subconscious.<ref name=\"synop\">{{cite web|url=http://screenrant.com/inception-plot-synopsis-deatails-mikee-58124/|title=Updated 'Inception' Synopsis Reveals More|website=Screen Rant|date=May 5, 2010|access-date=July 18, 2010|first=Mike|last=Eisenberg}}</ref> The [[ensemble cast]] includes [[Ken Watanabe]], [[Joseph Gordon-Levitt]], [[Marion Cotillard]], [[Ellen Page]], [[Tom Hardy]], [[Dileep Rao]], [[Cillian Murphy]], [[Tom Berenger]], and [[Michael Caine]].\n\nAfter the 2002 completion of ''[[Insomnia (2002 film)|Insomnia]]'', Nolan presented to [[Warner Bros.]] a written 80-page [[film treatment|treatment]] for a [[horror film]] envisioning \"dream stealers,\" based on [[lucid dreaming]].<ref name=\"Hiscock\" /> Deciding he needed more experience before tackling a production of this magnitude and complexity, Nolan retired the project and instead worked on 2005's ''[[Batman Begins]]'', 2006's ''[[The Prestige (film)|The Prestige]]'', and ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' in 2008.<ref name=\"Itzkoff\">{{Cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave|title=A Man and His Dream: Christopher Nolan and ''Inception''|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 30, 2010|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/30/a-man-and-his-dream-christopher-nolan-and-inception/|accessdate=July 1, 2010|quote=This is a film I first pitched to the studio probably nine years ago, and I wasn't really ready to finish it. I needed more experience in making a big movie.}}</ref> The treatment was revised over 6 months and was purchased by Warner in February 2009.<ref name=\"first\">{{Cite news|first=Michael|last=Fleming|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117999988|title=Nolan tackles ''Inception'' for WB|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=February 11, 2009|access-date=February 25, 2009}}</ref> ''Inception'' was filmed in six countries, beginning in Tokyo on June 19 and ending in Canada on November 22.<ref name=\"filming\">{{Cite news|date=December 6, 2009|title=Filming Locations \u2013 NolanFans |url=http://www.nolanfans.com/tag/filming-locations/|accessdate=March 23, 2012}}</ref> Its official budget was US$160&nbsp;million, split between [[Warner Bros]] and [[Legendary Pictures|Legendary]].<ref name=\"budget\">{{Cite news|date=July 15, 2010|last=Fritz|first=Ben|title=Movie projector: 'Inception' headed for No. 1, 'Sorcerer's Apprentice' to open in third|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2010/07/inception-sorcerers-box-office.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|quote=It's also one of the most expensive, at $160&nbsp;million, a cost that was split by Warner and Legendary Pictures. |access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref> Nolan's reputation and success with ''The Dark Knight'' helped secure the film's US$100&nbsp;million in advertising expenditure.\n\n''Inception''{{'}}s premiere was held in [[London]] on July 8, 2010; it was released in both conventional and [[IMAX]] theaters beginning on July 16, 2010.<ref name=\"bomrelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2860&p=.htm|title=Weekend Briefing: 'Inception' Breaks In, 'Apprentice' Lacks Magic|first=Ray|last=Subers|website=Box Office Mojo|date=July 16, 2010|access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=July 14, 2010|first=Jenny|last=Peters|title=Partying for a Cause at the \"Inception\" Premiere|url=http://www.fashionwiredaily.com/first_word/entertainment/article.weml?id=3264|work=Fashion Wire Daily|access-date=October 1, 2010}}</ref> ''Inception'' grossed over US$829&nbsp;million worldwide, becoming the [[2010 in film|fourth highest-grossing film of 2010]]. Considered one of the best films of the 2010s,<ref name=\"Metacritic 2010s\">{{cite web|date=November 18, 2019|first=Jason|last=Dietz|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-movies-of-the-decade-2010s|title=The Best Movies of the Decade (2010-19), According to Film Critics|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 26, 2020}}</ref> ''Inception'' received critical praise for its screenplay, direction, themes, visual effects, musical score, and ensemble cast.<ref name=\"Zeitchik\">{{Cite news|date=July 19, 2010|first=Steven|last=Zeitchik|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-inception-backlash-20100719,0,3544832.story|title='Inception' rides out critical backlash|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> It won four [[Academy Awards]] ([[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]], and [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]]) and was nominated for four more: [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]], [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction]], and [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]].\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- STOP!!! Do not add any unnecessary details to plot. -->\nDominick \"Dom\" Cobb and Arthur are \"extractors\": they perform [[corporate espionage]] using experimental military technology to infiltrate the [[Unconscious mind|subconscious]] of their targets and extract valuable information through a [[shared dreaming|shared]] [[Dream world (plot device)|dream world]]. Their latest target, Japanese businessman Saito, reveals that he arranged their mission himself to test Cobb for a seemingly impossible job: implanting an idea in a person's subconscious, or \"inception\". To break up the [[energy industry|energy]] [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] of ailing competitor Maurice Fischer, Saito wants Cobb to convince Fischer's son and heir, Robert, to dissolve his father's company. In return, Saito promises to use his influence once the job is done to clear Cobb's apparent criminal status, which prevents him from returning home to his children.\n\nThough Arthur believes the task is impossible, Cobb insists that it can be done. Cobb accepts the offer and assembles his team: Eames, a conman and identity forger; Yusuf, a chemist who concocts a powerful [[sedative]] for a stable \"[[false awakening|dream within a dream]]\" strategy; and Ariadne, an architecture student tasked with designing the [[labyrinth]] of the dream landscapes, recruited with the help of Cobb's father-in-law, Professor Stephen Miles. While dream-sharing with Cobb, Ariadne learns his subconscious houses an invasive projection of his late wife Mal.\n\nAfter Maurice dies in [[Sydney]], Robert Fischer accompanies the body on a ten-hour flight back to Los Angeles. The team (including Saito, who wants to verify their success) uses this as an opportunity to sedate and take Fischer into a shared dream. At each dream level, the person generating the dream stays behind to set up a \"[[Hypnic jerk|kick]]\" that will be used to awaken the other sleeping team members from the deeper dream level; to be successful, these kicks must occur simultaneously at each dream level, a fact complicated due to the nature of time, which flows much faster in each successive level. They use \"[[Non, je ne regrette rien]]\" as an auditory cue to help coordinate the kicks. The first level is Yusuf's dream of a rainy Los Angeles. \n\nThe team abducts Fischer, but they are attacked by armed projections from his subconscious, which has been specifically trained to defend against such intruders. The team takes Robert and a wounded Saito to a warehouse, where Cobb reveals that while dying in the dream would normally wake Saito up, the powerful sedatives needed to stabilize the multi-level dream will instead send a dying dreamer into \"[[Limbo#Cultural references|limbo]]\": a world of infinite subconscious from which escape is extremely difficult, if not impossible, and in which a dreamer risks forgetting they are in a dream. Despite these setbacks, the team continues with the mission.\n\nEames impersonates Robert's godfather, Peter Browning, to suggest Robert reconsider his father's will. Yusuf drives them around in a van as the rest are sedated into the second level, a hotel dreamed by Arthur. Cobb persuades Robert that he has been kidnapped by Browning, and that Cobb is his subconscious protector. Cobb persuades Robert to go down another level to explore Browning's subconscious (in reality, it is a ruse to enter Robert's subconscious). The third level is a fortified hospital on a snowy mountain dreamed by Eames. The team has to infiltrate it and hold off the guards as Saito takes Robert into the equivalent of his subconscious. Yusuf, under pursuit by Robert's projections in the first level, deliberately drives off a bridge, thus initiating his kick too soon. This causes an avalanche in Eames' level, and removes the gravity of Arthur's level, thus forcing Arthur to improvise a new kick synchronized with the van hitting the water. Mal's projection emerges in Eames' level and kills Robert; Cobb kills Mal, and Saito succumbs to his wounds. Cobb and Ariadne enter Limbo to rescue Robert and Saito, while Eames sets up a kick by rigging the hospital with explosives.\n\nCobb reveals to Ariadne that he and Mal went to limbo while experimenting with the dream-sharing technology. Sedated for five hours of real time, they spent fifty years in a dream constructing a world from their shared memories. When Mal refused to return to reality, Cobb used a rudimentary form of inception by reactivating her totem (an object that dreamers use to distinguish their dreams from reality), and reminding her subconscious that their world was not real. However, after waking up, the inception had taken root and Mal still believed that she was dreaming. In an attempt to \"wake up\" for real, she committed suicide and framed Cobb for her death to force him to do the same. Facing a murder charge, Cobb fled the U.S., leaving his children in the care of his father-in-law.\n\nThrough his confession, Cobb makes peace with his guilt over Mal's death. Ariadne kills Mal's projection and wakes Robert up with a kick. Revived at the fortified hospital, he enters a safe room to discover and accept the planted idea: a projection of his dying father telling him to be his own man. While Cobb remains in limbo to search for Saito, the other team members ride the synchronized kicks back to reality. Cobb eventually finds an aged Saito in limbo and reminds him of their agreement. The dreamers all awake on the plane and Saito makes a phone call.\n\nUpon arrival at Los Angeles Airport, Cobb passes the U.S. immigration checkpoint and Professor Miles accompanies him to his home. Using Mal's old totem\u2014a [[spinning top]] that spins indefinitely in a dream world but falls over in reality\u2014Cobb conducts a test to prove that he is indeed in the real world, but he does not observe its result and instead joins his children in the garden.\n<!-- DO NOT ADD ANY DETAIL ABOUT THE ENDING HERE. ADD IT TO THE \"ENDING\" SECTION BELOW -->\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:InceptionCastPremiereJuly10.jpg|thumb|The cast at a premiere for the film in July 2010: From left to right: Cillian Murphy, Marion Cotillard, Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Ellen Page, Ken Watanabe, Michael Caine, and Leonardo DiCaprio|alt=A man in a black suit, a woman in a pink dress, a man in a plaid suit, a woman in a black dress, a Japanese man in a black suit, and an old man in a blue suit clap their hands, while a man in a black suit stands. A microphone stand is in the foreground, and blue curtains are in the background.]]\n* [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] as Dom Cobb, a professional thief who specializes in [[con artist|conning]] secrets from his victims by infiltrating their dreams. DiCaprio was the first actor to be cast in the film.<ref name=\"Weintraub\" /> Both [[Brad Pitt]] and [[Will Smith]] were offered the role, according to ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/list-directors-43873 | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Kim | last=Masters | title=The A-List Directors | date=November 10, 2010}}</ref> Cobb's role is compared to \"the haunted widower in a Gothic romance\".<ref>Charles Burnetts, \"'Downwards is the only way forwards': 'Dream Space,' Parallel Time and Selfhood in Inception\", in: Jones, Matthew and Omrod, Joan, eds. ''Time Travel in Popular Media: Essays on Film, Television, Literature and Video Games''. [[Jefferson, North Carolina|Jefferson, N.C.]]: [[McFarland & Company|McFarland]], 2015. p. 234-246, p. 244.</ref>\n* [[Joseph Gordon-Levitt]] as Arthur, Cobb's partner who manages and researches the missions. Gordon-Levitt compared Arthur to the producer of Cobb's art, \"the one saying, 'Okay, you have your vision; now I'm going to figure out how to make all the nuts and bolts work so you can do your thing'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes 2010, p. 7.|publisher=}}</ref> The actor did all of his stunts but one scene and said the preparation \"was a challenge and it would have to be for it to look real\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.about.com/movies/Joseph-Gordon-Levitt-Inception.htm |title=Joseph Gordon-Levitt Inception Interview |date=July 15, 2010 |first=Rebecca |last=Murray |publisher=[[About.com]] |access-date=July 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002051742/http://video.about.com/movies/Joseph-Gordon-Levitt-Inception.htm |archivedate=October 2, 2011}}</ref> [[James Franco]] was in talks with Christopher Nolan to play Arthur, but was ultimately unavailable due to scheduling conflicts.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rappe|first=Elisabeth|title=CHRISTOPHER NOLAN TRADES JAMES FRANCO FOR JOSEPH GORDON-LEVITT IN 'INCEPTION'|date=April 24, 2009|publisher=[[MTV News]]|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2431985/christopher-nolan-trades-james-franco-for-joseph-gordon-levitt-in-inception/|accessdate=June 23, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Ellen Page]] as Ariadne, a [[graduate student]] of architecture who is recruited to construct the various dreamscapes, which are described as mazes. The name [[Ariadne]] alludes to a princess of [[Greek mythology|Greek myth]], daughter of [[Minos|King Minos]], who aided the hero [[Theseus]] by giving him a sword and a ball of string to help him navigate the labyrinth which was the prison of the [[Minotaur]]. Nolan said that Page was chosen for being a \"perfect combination of freshness and savvy and maturity beyond her years\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes 2010, p. 8.|publisher=}}</ref> Page said her character acts as a proxy to the audience, as \"she's just learning about these ideas and, in essence, assists the audience in learning about dream sharing\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/7868889/Inception-Ellen-Page-interview.html|title=Inception: Ellen Page interview|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK|first=Christine|last=Lennon|access-date=July 3, 2011|date=July 12, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Hardy]] as Eames, a sharp-tongued associate of Cobb. He is referred to as a [[fence (criminal)|fence]] but his specialty is forgery, more accurately [[identity theft]]. Eames uses his ability to [[impersonation|impersonate others]] inside the dream world in order to manipulate Fischer. Hardy described his character as \"an old, [[Graham Greene]]-type diplomat; sort of faded, shabby, grandeur \u2013 the old Shakespeare lovey mixed with somebody from [[United Kingdom Special Forces|Her Majesty's Special Forces]]\", who wears \"campy, old money\" costumes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ugo.com/movies/diving-into-your-own-mind |title=Inception's Tom Hardy Is The Forger, Darling |publisher=[[UGO]] |first=Matt |last=Patches |date=July 12, 2010 |access-date=July 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100905040047/http://www.ugo.com/movies/diving-into-your-own-mind |archivedate=September 5, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Ken Watanabe]] as Mr. Saito, a Japanese businessman who employs Cobb for the team's mission. Nolan wrote the role with Watanabe in mind, as he wanted to work with him again after ''[[Batman Begins]]''.<ref name=pn10/> ''Inception'' is Watanabe's first work in a contemporary setting where his primary language is English. Watanabe tried to emphasize a different characteristic of Saito in every dream level: \"First chapter in my castle, I pick up some hidden feelings of the cycle. It's magical, powerful and then the first dream. And back to the second chapter, in the old hotel, I pick up [being] sharp and more calm and smart and it's a little bit [of a] different process to make up the character of any movie\".<ref>{{Cite news|first=Alex |last=Billington |title=Interview: Japanese Actor Ken Watanabe \u2013 Saito in Inception|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=July 20, 2010|url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2010/interview-inceptions-saito-japanese-actor-ken-watanabe/|accessdate=July 3, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Dileep Rao]] as Yusuf. Rao describes Yusuf as \"an avant-garde pharmacologist, who is a resource for people, like Cobb, who want to do this work unsupervised, unregistered and unapproved of by anyone\". Co-producer Jordan Goldberg said the role of the chemist was \"particularly tough because you don't want him to seem like some kind of drug dealer\", and that Rao was cast for being \"funny, interesting and obviously smart\".<ref name=\"Production Notes 2010, p. 11\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes 2010, p. 11.|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Cillian Murphy]] as Robert Michael Fischer, the heir to a business empire and the team's target.<ref name=pn10>{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes 2010, p. 10.|publisher=}}</ref> Murphy said Fischer was portrayed as \"a petulant child who's in need of a lot of attention from his father, he has everything he could ever want materially, but he's deeply lacking emotionally\". The actor also researched the sons of [[Rupert Murdoch]], \"to add to that the idea of living in the shadow of someone so immensely powerful\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishcentral.com/IrishVoice/Hollywood-golden-boy-Cillian-Murphy-talks-about-Inception.html?page=2|title=Hollywood golden boy Cillian Murphy talks about 'Inception'|publisher=Irish Voice Reporter|first=Cahir|last=O'Doherty|date=July 15, 2010|access-date=July 3, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Berenger]] as Peter Browning, Robert Fischer's [[Godparent|godfather]] and fellow executive at the Fischers' company.<ref name=\"CinemaRewind\">{{Cite web|last=George|title=Inception Cast and Crew Updates|publisher=Cinema Rewind|date=July 23, 2009|url=http://www.cinemarewind.com/2009/07/inception-cast-and-crew-updates.html|accessdate=August 31, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801155642/http://www.cinemarewind.com/2009/07/inception-cast-and-crew-updates.html|archivedate=August 1, 2009}}</ref> Berenger said Browning acts as a \"surrogate father\" to Fischer, who calls the character \"Uncle Peter\", and emphasized that \"Browning has been with [Robert] his whole life and has probably spent more quality time with him than his own father\".<ref name=\"Production Notes 2010, p. 11\"/>\n* [[Marion Cotillard]] as Mal Cobb, Dom's deceased wife. She is a manifestation of Dom's guilt about the real cause of Mal's suicide. He is unable to control these projections of her, challenging his abilities as an extractor.<ref name=\"threecircle\" /> Nolan described Mal as \"the essence of the [[femme fatale]],\" and DiCaprio praised Cotillard's performance, saying that \"she can be strong and vulnerable and hopeful and heartbreaking all in the same moment, which was perfect for all the contradictions of her character\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes 2010, p. 9 and 10.|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Pete Postlethwaite]] as Maurice Fischer, Robert Fischer's father and the dying founder of a business empire.\n* [[Michael Caine]] as Professor Stephen Miles, Cobb's mentor and father-in-law,<ref name=\"Production Notes 2010, p. 11\" /> and Ariadne's college professor who recommends her to the team.<ref name=\"InContention\">{{Cite news|last=Tapley|first=Kristopher|title=Caine confirmed in small role in ''Inception'', Gordon-Levitt also joins the cast|publisher=InContention|date=April 24, 2009|url=http://incontention.com/?p=5843|accessdate=April 24, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Lukas Haas]] as Nash, an architect in Cobb's employment who betrays the team and is later replaced by Ariadne.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Boursaw|first=Jane|publisher=EveryJoe|title=Ellen Page on the set of ''Inception'' in Paris|date=August 26, 2009|url=http://everyjoe.com/entertainment/ellen-page-on-the-set-of-inception-in-paris/|accessdate=August 26, 2009|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120712215937/http://everyjoe.com/entertainment/ellen-page-on-the-set-of-inception-in-paris/|archive-date=July 12, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Talulah Riley]] as a woman whom Eames disguises himself as in a dream. Riley liked the role, despite it being minimal: \"I get to wear a nice dress, pick up men in bars, and shove them in elevators. It was good to do something adultish. Usually I play 15-year-old English schoolgirls.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/talulah-riley/|title=Talulah Riley|author=Martin, Michael|work=[[Interview Magazine]]|date=May 10, 2010|access-date=July 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n[[File:Emma Thomas & Christopher Nolan at WonderCon 2010 1.JPG|thumb|left|upright=1|Emma Thomas and Christopher Nolan answer questions about ''Inception''. The husband and wife team produced the film through their company [[Syncopy Films]]. Nolan also wrote and directed it.]]\nInitially, Nolan wrote an 80-page [[film treatment|treatment]] about dream-stealers.<ref name=\"Hiscock\" /> Originally, Nolan had envisioned ''Inception'' as a [[horror film]],<ref name=\"Hiscock\">{{Cite news|last=Hiscock|first=John|title=''Inception'': Christopher Nolan interview|work=Daily Telegraph |location=UK|date=July 1, 2010|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmmakersonfilm/7866677/Inception-Christopher-Nolan-interview.html|accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref> but eventually wrote it as a [[heist film]] even though he found that \"traditionally [they] are very deliberately superficial in emotional terms.\"<ref name=\"Boucher\">{{Cite news|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|title=''Inception'' breaks into dreams|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 4, 2010|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-ca-inception4-2010apr04,0,6869939.story|accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref> Upon revisiting his script, he decided that basing it in that genre did not work because the story \"relies so heavily on the idea of the interior state, the idea of dream and [[memory]]. I realized I needed to raise the emotional stakes.\"<ref name=\"Boucher\" /> \n\nNolan worked on the script for nine to ten years.<ref name=\"Weintraub\" /> When he first started thinking about making the film, Nolan was influenced by \"that era of movies where you had ''[[The Matrix]]'' (1999), you had ''[[Dark City (1998 film)|Dark City]]'' (1998), you had ''[[The Thirteenth Floor]]'' (1999) and, to a certain extent, you had ''[[Memento (film)|Memento]]'' (2000), too. They were based in the principles that the world around you might not be real.\"<ref name=\"Boucher\" /><ref>{{Cite web|date=July 16, 2010|first=Sheila|last=Marikar|title=Inside 'Inception': Could Christopher Nolan's Dream World Exist in Real Life? Dream Experts Say 'Inception's' Conception of the Subconscious Isn't Far From Science|publisher=[[ABC News]]|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/inside-inception-christopher-nolans-dream-world-exist-real/story?id=11174201|accessdate=September 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nNolan first pitched the film to Warner Bros. in 2001, but decided that he needed more experience making large-scale films, and embarked on ''[[Batman Begins]]'' and ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]''.<ref name=\"Itzkoff\"/> He soon realized that a film like ''Inception'' needed a large budget because \"as soon as you're talking about dreams, the potential of the human mind is infinite. And so the scale of the film has to feel infinite. It has to feel like you could go anywhere by the end of the film. And it has to work on a massive scale.\"<ref name=\"Itzkoff\" /> After making ''The Dark Knight'', Nolan decided to make ''Inception'' and spent six months completing the script.<ref name=\"Itzkoff\" /> Nolan said that the key to completing the script was wondering what would happen if several people shared the same dream. \"Once you remove the privacy, you've created an infinite number of alternative universes in which people can meaningfully interact, with validity, with weight, with dramatic consequences.\"<ref name=\"Itzkoff2\">{{Cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave|title=The Man Behind the Dreamscape|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 30, 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/04/movies/04inception.html |access-date=July 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nNolan had been trying to work with Leonardo DiCaprio for years and met him several times, but was unable to recruit him for any of his films until ''Inception''.<ref name=\"threecircle\">{{Cite news|first=Borys |last=Kit |title=Three circle Nolan's 'Inception' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=April 1, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406021957/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i7288557915e143d0665fd7eb397d74e8 |archivedate=April 6, 2009 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i7288557915e143d0665fd7eb397d74e8 |access-date=April 2, 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> DiCaprio finally agreed because he was \"intrigued by this concept\u2014this dream-heist notion and how this character's going to unlock his dreamworld and ultimately affect his real life.\"<ref name=\"Jolin\">{{Cite news|last=Jolin|first=Dan|title=Crime of the Century|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=July 2010|pages=93\u201394}}</ref> He read the script and found it to be \"very well written, comprehensive but you really had to have Chris in person, to try to articulate some of the things that have been swirling around his head for the last eight years.\"<ref name=\"Itzkoff\" /> DiCaprio and Nolan spent months talking about the screenplay. Nolan took a long time re-writing the script in order \"to make sure that the emotional journey of his [Di Caprio's] character was the driving force of the movie.\"<ref name=\"Weintraub\" /> On February 11, 2009, it was announced that [[Warner Bros.]] purchased ''Inception'', a [[spec script]] written by Nolan.<ref name=\"first\" />\n\n===Locations and sets {{anchor|Filming}}===\n[[Principal photography]] began in [[Tokyo]] on June 19, 2009, with the scene in which Saito first hires Cobb during a helicopter flight over the city.<ref name=\"Hiscock\" /><ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes7\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 13.|publisher=}}</ref>\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Inception.JPG|thumb|left|upright=1|The scene]] -->\n\nThe production moved to the United Kingdom and shot in a converted [[airship hangar]] in [[Cardington, Bedfordshire|Cardington]], Bedfordshire, north of London.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes8\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 14.|publisher=}}</ref> There, the hotel bar set which tilted 30 degrees was built.<ref name=\"Heuring\">{{Cite news|last=Heuring|first=David|title=Dream Thieves|work=[[American Cinematographer]]|publisher=American Society of Cinematographers|date=July 2010|page=29|url=http://www.theasc.com/ac_magazine/July2010/Inception/page1.php|accessdate=September 22, 2010}}</ref> A hotel corridor was also constructed by [[Guy Hendrix Dyas]], the production designer, [[Chris Corbould]], the special effects supervisor, and [[Wally Pfister]], the director of photography; it rotated a full 360&nbsp;degrees to create the effect of alternate directions of [[gravity]] for scenes set during the second level of dreaming, where dream-sector physics become chaotic. The idea was inspired by a technique used in [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''[[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]]'' (1968). Nolan said, \"I was interested in taking those ideas, techniques, and philosophies and applying them to an action scenario\".<ref name=\"Heuring2\">Heuring, July 2010, p. 32.</ref> The filmmakers originally planned to make the hallway only 40&nbsp;ft (12&nbsp;m) long, but as the action sequence became more elaborate, the hallway's length was increased to 100&nbsp;ft (30&nbsp;m). The corridor was suspended along eight large concentric rings that were spaced equidistantly outside its walls and powered by two massive electric motors.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes8\" /> \n\nJoseph Gordon-Levitt, who plays Arthur, spent several weeks learning to fight in a corridor that spun like \"a giant [[hamster wheel]]\".<ref name=\"Boucher\" /> Nolan said of the device, \"It was like some incredible torture device; we thrashed Joseph for weeks, but in the end we looked at the footage, and it looks unlike anything any of us has seen before. The rhythm of it is unique, and when you watch it, even if you know how it was done, it confuses your perceptions. It's unsettling in a wonderful way\".<ref name=\"Boucher\" /> Gordon-Levitt remembered, \"it was six-day weeks of just, like, coming home at night battered ... The light fixtures on the ceiling are coming around on the floor, and you have to choose the right time to cross through them, and if you don't, you're going to fall.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gordinier|first=Jeff|title=Joseph Gordon-Levitt Comes of Age|work=[[Details (magazine)|Details]]|date=August 2010|url=http://www.details.com/celebrities-entertainment/cover-stars/201008/inception-actor-joseph-gordon-levitt?currentPage=1|page=4|accessdate=July 27, 2010}}</ref> On July 15, 2009, filming took place at [[University College London]] for the sequences occurring inside a Paris college of architecture in the story,<ref name=\"Hiscock\" /> including the library, Flaxman Gallery and Gustav Tuck Theatre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-film-locations.com/Inception-2010|title=Where was 'Inception' filmed? \u2013 British Film Locations|work=British Film Locations|access-date=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFilming moved to France, where they shot Cobb entering the college of architecture (the place used for the entrance was the [[Mus\u00e9e Galliera]]) and the pivotal scenes between Ariadne and Cobb, in a [[bistro]] (a fictional one set up at the corner of Rue C\u00e9sar Franck and Rue Bouchut), and lastly on the [[Pont de Bir-Hakeim|Bir-Hakeim bridge]].<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes9\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 17.|publisher=}}</ref> For the explosion that takes place during the bistro scene, local authorities would not allow the use of real explosives. High-pressure [[nitrogen]] was used to create the effect of a series of explosions. Pfister used six high-speed cameras to capture the sequence from different angles and make sure that they got the shot. The visual effects department enhanced the sequence, adding more destruction and flying debris. For the \"Paris folding\" sequence and when Ariadne \"creates\" the bridges, [[green screen]] and [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] were used on location.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes9\" />\n\n[[Tangier]], Morocco, doubled as [[Mombasa]], where Cobb hires Eames and Yusuf. A foot chase was shot in the streets and alleyways of the historic [[medina quarter]].<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes10\">The historic medina is south west of the cited \"[[Grand Socco|Grand Souk]]\", which is no longer a market place, but a busy transportation junction. [http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf Production Notes, 2010, p. 18.]</ref> To capture this sequence, Pfister employed a mix of [[hand-held camera]] and [[steadicam]] work.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes11\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 19.|publisher=}}</ref> Tangier was also used as the setting for filming an important riot scene during the initial foray into Saito's mind.\n\nFilming moved to the [[Los Angeles]] area, where some sets were built on a Warner Bros. [[sound stage]], including the interior rooms of Saito's Japanese castle (the exterior was done on a small set built in [[Malibu Beach]]). The dining room was inspired by the historic [[Nijo Castle]], built around 1603. These sets were inspired by a mix of [[Japanese architecture]] and Western influences.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes11\" /> \n\nThe production staged a multi-vehicle [[car chase]] on the streets of [[downtown Los Angeles]], which involved a freight train crashing down the middle of a street.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes12\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 20.|publisher=}}</ref> To do this, the filmmakers configured a train engine on the chassis of a tractor trailer. The replica was made from [[fiberglass]] molds taken from authentic train parts and matched in terms of color and design.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes13\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 21.|publisher=}}</ref> Also, the car chase was supposed to be set in the midst of a downpour, but the L.A. weather stayed typically sunny. The filmmakers set up elaborate effects (e.g., rooftop [[water cannon]]s) to give the audience the impression that the weather was overcast and soggy. L.A. was also the site of the climactic scene where a [[Ford E-Series|Ford Econoline]] van runs off the [[Commodore Schuyler F. Heim Bridge|Schuyler Heim Bridge]] in slow motion.<ref name=\"Ditzian\">{{Cite news|last=Ditzian|first=Eric|title=''Inception'' Stars Reveal Secrets Behind Epic Van Scene|publisher=MTV |date=July 14, 2010|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1643645/20100714/story.jhtml|accessdate=July 22, 2010}}</ref> This sequence was filmed on and off for months, with the van being shot out of a cannon, according to actor Dileep Rao. Capturing the actors suspended within the van in slow motion took a whole day to film. \n\nOnce the van landed in the water, the challenge for the actors was to avoid panic. \"And when they ask you to act, it's a bit of an ask,\" explained Cillian Murphy.<ref name=\"Ditzian\" /> The actors had to be underwater for four to five minutes while drawing air from [[Diving cylinder|scuba tanks]]; underwater [[buddy breathing]] is shown in this sequence.<ref name=\"Ditzian\" /> \n\nCobb's house was in Pasadena. The hotel lobby was filmed at the CAA building in Century City. 'Limbo' was made on location in Los Angeles and [[Morocco]], with the beach scene filmed at [[Palos Verdes]] beach with CGI buildings. N Hope St. in Los Angeles was the primary filming location for 'limbo,' with green screen and CGI being used to create the dream landscape.\n\nThe final phase of principal photography took place in [[Alberta]] in late November 2009. The location manager discovered a temporarily closed ski resort, [[Fortress Mountain Resort|Fortress Mountain]].<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes14\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 22.|publisher=}}</ref> An elaborate set was assembled near the top station of the Canadian [[chairlift]], taking three months to build.<ref name=\"Jolin2\">Jolin, July 2010, pp. 93.</ref> The production had to wait for a huge snowstorm, which eventually arrived.<ref name=\"Hiscock\" /> The ski-chase sequence was inspired by Nolan's favorite [[James Bond]] film, ''[[On Her Majesty's Secret Service (film)|On Her Majesty's Secret Service]]'' (1969): \"What I liked about it that we've tried to emulate in this film is there's a tremendous balance in that movie of action and scale and romanticism and tragedy and emotion.\"<ref name=\"Jolin3\">Jolin, July 2010, pp. 91.</ref>\n\n===Cinematography===\nThe film was shot primarily in the [[anamorphic format]] on [[35mm movie film|35&nbsp;mm film]], with key sequences filmed on [[70 mm film|65&nbsp;mm]], and aerial sequences in [[VistaVision]]. Nolan did not shoot any footage with [[IMAX]] cameras as he had with ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]''. \"We didn't feel that we were going to be able to shoot in IMAX because of the size of the cameras because this film given that it deals with a potentially surreal area, the nature of dreams and so forth, I wanted it to be as realistic as possible. Not be bound by the scale of those IMAX cameras, even though I love the format dearly\".<ref name=\"Weintraub\" /> In addition Nolan and Pfister tested using [[Showscan]] and [[List of film formats|Super Dimension 70]] as potential large format [[high frame rate]] camera systems to use for the film, but ultimately decided against either format.<ref name=\"Heuring\" /> Sequences in slow motion were filmed on a Photo-Sonics 35mm camera at speeds of up to 1000 frames per second. Wally Pfister tested shooting some of these sequences using a high speed [[Digital cinematography|digital camera]], but found the format to be too unreliable due to technical glitches. \"Out of six times that we shot on the digital format, we only had one useable piece and it didn't end up in the film. Out of the six times we shot with the Photo-Sonics camera and 35mm running through it, every single shot was in the movie.\"<ref name=\"Kodak\">{{Cite news|title=From The Dark Knight to Inception, Wally Pfister, ASC refuses to compromise |publisher=Kodak|url=http://motion.kodak.com/motion/Products/Customer_Testimonials/Wally_Pfister/index.htm#ixzz2Ti47T2NZ|accessdate=May 19, 2013}}</ref> Nolan also chose not to shoot any of the film in [[3D film|3D]] as he prefers shooting on film<ref name=\"Weintraub\" /> using [[prime lens]]es, which is not possible with 3D cameras.<ref name=\"Playlist\">{{Cite news|title=Christopher Nolan Tested 3D Conversion For 'Inception,' Might Use Process For 'Batman 3'|work=The Playlist|date=June 14, 2010|url=http://theplaylist.blogspot.com/2010/06/christopher-nolan-tested-3d-conversion.html|accessdate=January 22, 2011}}</ref> Nolan has also criticized the dim image that 3D projection produces, and disputes that traditional film does not allow realistic [[depth perception]], saying \"I think it's a misnomer to call it 3D versus 2D. The whole point of cinematic imagery is it's three dimensional... You know 95% of our [[depth perception|depth cues]] come from [[Ambient occlusion|occlusion]], resolution, color and so forth, so the idea of calling a 2D movie a '2D movie' is a little misleading.\"<ref name=latimes-hcff>{{cite news|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2010/06/13/christopher-nolan-inception-3d-dark-knight-hollywood/|title=Christopher Nolan's dim view of a Hollywood craze: 'I'm not a huge fan of 3-D'|date=June 13, 2010|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=January 22, 2011}}</ref> Nolan did test [[2D to 3D conversion|converting]] ''Inception'' into 3D in post-production but decided that, while it was possible, he lacked the time to complete the conversion to a standard he was happy with.<ref name=\"Hiscock\"/><ref name=\"latimes-hcff\" /> In February 2011 [[Jonathan Liebesman]] suggested that Warner Bros were attempting a 3D conversion for [[Blu-ray]] release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/inception-being-converted-to-3d-blu-ray|title=''Inception'' being converted to 3D Blu-ray?|first=Brian|last=Gallagher|date=February 24, 2011|access-date=February 27, 2011|publisher=movieweb.com}}</ref>\n\nWally Pfister gave each location and dream level a distinctive look to aid the audience's recognition of the narrative's location during the heavily crosscut portion of the film: the mountain fortress appears sterile and cool, the hotel hallways have warm hues, and the scenes in the van are more neutral.<ref name=\"Heuring3\">Heuring, July 2010, pp. 35\u201336.</ref>\n\nNolan has said that the film \"deals with levels of reality, and perceptions of reality which is something I'm very interested in. It's an action film set in a contemporary world, but with a slight science-fiction bent to it,\" while also describing it as \"very much an ensemble film structured somewhat as a heist movie. It's an action adventure that spans the globe\".<ref>{{Cite news|title=''Inception''|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Visual effects===\nFor dream sequences in ''Inception'', Nolan used little [[computer-generated imagery]], preferring [[practical effect]]s whenever possible. Nolan said, \"It's always very important to me to do as much as possible in-camera, and then, if necessary, computer graphics are very useful to build on or enhance what you have achieved physically.\"<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes6\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 12.|publisher=}}</ref> To this end, visual effects supervisor [[Paul Franklin (visual effects supervisor)|Paul Franklin]] built a [[Miniature effect|miniature]] of the mountain fortress set and then blew it up for the film. For the fight scene that takes place in zero gravity, he used CG-based effects to \"subtly bend elements like physics, space and time.\"<ref name=\"trussell\">{{Cite news|last=Russell|first=Terrence|title=How ''Inception''{{'}}s Astonishing Visuals Came to Life|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|date=July 20, 2010|url=https://www.wired.com/underwire/2010/07/inception-visual-effects|accessdate=July 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe most challenging effect was the \"limbo\" city level at the end of the film, because it continually developed during production. Franklin had artists build concepts while Nolan expressed his ideal vision: \"Something glacial, with clear modernist architecture, but with chunks of it breaking off into the sea like icebergs\".<ref name=\"trussell\" /> Franklin and his team ended up with \"something that looked like an iceberg version of [[Gotham City]] with water running through it.\"<ref name=\"trussell\" /> They created a basic model of a glacier and then designers created a program that added elements like roads, intersections and ravines until they had a complex, yet organic-looking, cityscape. For the Paris-folding sequence, Franklin had artists producing concept sketches and then they created rough computer animations to give them an idea of what the sequence looked like while in motion. Later during principal photography, Nolan was able to direct Leonardo DiCaprio and Ellen Page based on this rough computer animation that Franklin had created. ''Inception'' had nearly 500 visual effects shots (in comparison, ''[[Batman Begins]]'' had approximately 620), which is relatively few in comparison to contemporary effects-heavy films, which can have as many as 2,000 visual effects shots.<ref name=\"trussell\" />\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|Inception: Music from the Motion Picture}}\n\nThe score for ''Inception'' was written by [[Hans Zimmer]],<ref name=\"CinemaRewind\" /> who described his work as \"a very electronic,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screenrant.com/inception-score-hans-zimmers-mikee-65200 |title=Hans Zimmer's 'Inception' Score Will Release On July 13th |publisher=ScreenRant.com |access-date=July 1, 2010 |date=June 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625130549/http://screenrant.com/inception-score-hans-zimmers-mikee-65200/ |archivedate=June 25, 2010}}</ref> dense score\",<ref name=\"Cassidy\"/> filled with \"nostalgia and sadness\" to match Cobb's feelings throughout the film.<ref name=\"Martens\"/> The music was written simultaneously to filming,<ref name=\"Cassidy\">{{cite news |last=Cassidy |first=Kevin |title=Q&A: Composer Hans Zimmer |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=July 13, 2010 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/qampa-composer-hans-zimmer-25455|accessdate=July 14, 2010}}</ref> and features a guitar sound reminiscent of [[Ennio Morricone]], played by [[Johnny Marr]], former guitarist of [[The Smiths]].\n[[\u00c9dith Piaf]]'s \"[[Non, je ne regrette rien]]\" (\"No, I Regret Nothing\") appears throughout the film, used to accurately time the dreams, and Zimmer reworked pieces of the song into cues of the score.<ref name=\"Martens\">{{cite news |last=Martens |first=Todd |title=Hans Zimmer and Johnny Marr talk about the sad romance of 'Inception' |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 20, 2010 |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/herocomplex/2010/07/inception-christopher-nolan-the-smiths-johnny-marr-hans-zimmer-and-johnny-marr-on-the-sound-of-inception-its-about-sadness.html |access-date=July 20, 2010}}</ref>\n[[Inception: Music from the Motion Picture|A soundtrack album]] was released on July 11, 2010 by [[Reprise Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inceptionscore.com/|title=Inception: Music from the Motion Picture official website|publisher=Warner Bros.|access-date=July 3, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616131408/http://www.inceptionscore.com/|archive-date=June 16, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The majority of the score was also included in high resolution [[5.1 surround sound]] on the second disc of the 2 disc Blu-ray release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Inception-Blu-ray/14492/#Review|title=Inception Blu-ray review from Blu-ray.com|access-date=August 8, 2012}}</ref> Hans Zimmer's music was nominated for an Academy Award in the [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] category in 2011, losing to [[Trent Reznor]] and [[Atticus Ross]] of ''[[The Social Network]]''.<ref name=oscars/>\n\n==Themes==\n\n===Reality and dreams===\n[[File:Impossible staircase.svg|right|thumb|[[Penrose stairs]] are incorporated into the film as an example of the [[impossible object]]s that can be created in [[lucid dream]] worlds.|alt=A staircase in a square format. The stairs make four 90-degree turns in each corner, so they are in the format of a continuous loop.]]\nIn ''Inception'', Nolan wanted to explore \"the idea of people sharing a dream space...That gives you the ability to access somebody's [[unconscious mind]]. What would that be used and abused for?\"<ref name=\"Weintraub\">{{Cite news|last=Weintraub |first=Steve |title=Christopher Nolan and Emma Thomas Interview |publisher=Collider.com |date=March 25, 2010 |url=http://www.collider.com/2010/03/25/director-christopher-nolan-and-producer-emma-thomas-interview-inception-they-talk-3d-what-kind-of-cameras-they-used-pre-viz-wb-and-a-lot-more/ |accessdate=April 6, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327204348/http://www.collider.com/2010/03/25/director-christopher-nolan-and-producer-emma-thomas-interview-inception-they-talk-3d-what-kind-of-cameras-they-used-pre-viz-wb-and-a-lot-more/ |archivedate=March 27, 2010  }}</ref> The majority of the film's plot takes place in these interconnected dream worlds. This structure creates a framework where actions in the real or dream worlds ripple across others. The dream is always in a state of production, and shifts across the levels as the characters navigate it.<ref name='Paul'>Paul, I. A. [http://sensesofcinema.com/2010/feature-articles/desiring-machines-in-american-cinema-what-inception-tells-us-about-our-experience-of-reality-and-film/ Desiring-Machines in American Cinema: What Inception tells us about our experience of reality and film] ''Senses of Cinema'', Issue 56. Retrieved October 4, 2011</ref> By contrast, the world of ''[[The Matrix]]'' (1999) is an authoritarian, computer-controlled one, alluding to theories of social control developed by thinkers [[Michel Foucault]] and [[Jean Baudrillard]]. However, according to one interpretation Nolan's world has more in common with the works of [[Gilles Deleuze]] and [[F\u00e9lix Guattari]].<ref name='Paul'/>\n\n[[David Denby (film critic)|David Denby]] in ''[[The New Yorker]]'' compared Nolan's cinematic treatment of dreams to [[Luis Bu\u00f1uel]]'s in ''[[Belle de Jour (film)|Belle de Jour]]'' (1967) and ''[[The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie]]'' (1972).<ref name=\"Denby\" /> He criticized Nolan's \"literal-minded\" action level sequencing compared to Bu\u00f1uel, who \"silently pushed us into reveries and left us alone to enjoy our wonderment, but Nolan is working on so many levels of representation at once that he has to lay in pages of dialogue just to explain what's going on.\" The latter captures \"the peculiar malign intensity of actual dreams.\"<ref name=\"Denby\"/>\n\n[[Deirdre Barrett]], a dream researcher at [[Harvard University]], said that Nolan did not get every detail accurate regarding dreams, but their illogical, rambling, disjointed plots would not make for a great thriller anyway. However, \"he did get many aspects right,\" she said, citing the scene in which a sleeping Cobb is shoved into a full bath, and in the dream world water gushes into the windows of the building, waking him up. \"That's very much how real stimuli get incorporated, and you very often wake up right after that intrusion\".<ref name=\"Breznican\">{{Cite news|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|title=With ''Inception'', Chris Nolan's head games continue|work=[[USA Today]]|date=July 15, 2010|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-07-15-inception15_CV_N.htm|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nNolan himself said, \"I tried to work that idea of manipulation and management of a [[Lucid dream|conscious dream]] being a skill that these people have. Really the script is based on those common, very basic experiences and concepts, and where can those take you? And the only outlandish idea that the film presents, really, is the existence of a technology that allows you to enter and share the same dream as someone else.\"<ref name=\"Boucher\" />\n\n=== Dreams and cinema ===\nOthers have argued that the film is itself a [[oneiric (film theory)|metaphor for filmmaking]], and that the filmgoing experience itself, images flashing before one's eyes in a darkened room, is akin to a dream. Writing in ''Wired'', Jonah Lehrer supported this interpretation and presented neurological evidence that brain activity is strikingly similar during film-watching and sleeping. In both, the [[visual cortex]] is highly active and the [[prefrontal cortex]], which deals with logic, deliberate analysis, and self-awareness, is quiet.<ref name='Lehrer'>[[Jonah Lehrer|Lehrer, J.]] [https://www.wired.com/wiredscience/2010/07/the-neuroscience-of-inception/ The Neuroscience of Inception], ''Wired'', July 26, 2010. Retrieved October 8, 2011.</ref> Paul argued that the experience of going to a picturehouse is itself an exercise in shared dreaming, particularly when viewing ''Inception'': the film's sharp cutting between scenes forces the viewer to create larger narrative arcs to stitch the pieces together. This demand of production parallel to consumption of the images, on the part of the audience is analogous to dreaming itself. As in the film's story, in a cinema one enters into the space of another's dream, in this case Nolan's, as with any work of art, one's reading of it is ultimately influenced by one's own subjective desires and subconscious.<ref name='Paul'/> At Bir-Hakeim bridge in Paris, Ariadne creates an illusion of infinity by adding [[Infinity mirror|facing mirrors]] underneath its struts, Stephanie Dreyfus in ''la Croix'' asked \"Is this not a strong, beautiful metaphor for the cinema and its power of illusion?\"<ref>Dreyfus, St\u00e9phanie [http://www.la-croix.com/Culture-Loisirs/Culture/Actualite/Inception-allegorie-onirique-sur-l-illusion-cinematographique-_NG_-2010-07-20-554535 \"Inception\", all\u00e9gorie onirique sur l'illusion cin\u00e9matographique] ''[[La Croix]]'', July 20, 2010. Retrieved January 3, 2012</ref>\n\n==Cinematic technique==\n\n===Genre===\nNolan combined elements from several different film genres into the film, notably science fiction, [[heist film]], and [[film noir]].\n[[Marion Cotillard]] plays \"Mal\" Cobb, Dom Cobb's projection of his guilt over his deceased wife's suicide. As the film's main antagonist, she is a frequent, malevolent presence in his dreams. Dom is unable to control these projections of her, challenging his abilities as an extractor.<ref name=\"threecircle\" /> Nolan described Mal as \"the essence of the femme fatale\",<ref name=\"Production Notes 2010, p. 9\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes 2010, p. 9|publisher=}}</ref> the key ''noir'' reference in the film. As a \"classic femme fatale\" her relationship with Cobb is in his mind, a manifestation of Cobb's own neurosis and fear of how little he knows about the woman he loves.<ref name=\"wired-jan11\"/> DiCaprio praised Cotillard's performance saying that \"she can be strong and vulnerable and hopeful and heartbreaking all in the same moment, which was perfect for all the contradictions of her character\".<ref name=pn10/>\n\nNolan began with the structure of a heist movie, since [[Exposition (literary technique)|exposition]] is an essential element of that genre, though adapted it to have a greater emotional narrative suited to the world of dreams and subconscious.<ref name=\"wired-jan11\"/> Or, as Denby surmised, \"the outer shell of the story is an elaborate caper\".<ref name=\"Denby\"/> [[Kristin Thompson]] argued that exposition was a major formal device in the film. While a traditional heist movie has a heavy dose of exposition at the beginning as the team assembles and the leader explains the plan, in ''Inception'' this becomes nearly continuous as the group progresses through the various levels of dreaming.<ref name='Bordwell2'>[http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2010/08/12/revisiting-inception/ Revisiting INCEPTION] www.davidbordwell.net, August 12, 2010. Retrieved October 6, 2011.</ref> Three quarters of the film, until the van begins to fall from the bridge, are devoted to explaining its plot. In this way, exposition takes precedence over characterization. The characters' relationships are created by their respective skills and roles. Ariadne, like [[Ariadne|her ancient namesake]], creates the maze and guides the others through it, but also helps Cobb navigate his own subconscious, and as the sole student of dream sharing, helps the audience understand the concept of the plot.<ref name='Bordwell1'>[http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2010/08/06/inception-or-dream-a-little-dream-within-a-dream-with-me/ INCEPTION; or, Dream a Little Dream within a Dream with Me] www.davidbordwell.net. August 6, 2010. Retrieved October 6, 2011</ref>\n\nNolan drew inspiration from the works of [[Jorge Luis Borges]]<ref name=\"Hiscock\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/article/836236--howell-relax-and-enjoy-the-ride-inception-director-says|title=Howell: Relax and enjoy the ride, Inception director says|first=Peter|last=Howell|date=July 15, 2010|work=Toronto Star |accessdate=September 4, 2010}}</ref> and ''[[Blade Runner]]'' (1982) by [[Ridley Scott]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Inception par Christopher Nolan: Interview, r\u00e9f\u00e9rences, indices..|publisher=Excessif.com|url=http://www.excessif.com/cinema/actu-cinema/dossiers/inception-par-christopher-nolan-interview-references-indices-5926972-760.html|accessdate=January 4, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717005841/http://www.excessif.com/cinema/actu-cinema/dossiers/inception-par-christopher-nolan-interview-references-indices-5926972-760.html|archivedate=July 17, 2010}} ([https://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.excessif.com%2Fcinema%2Factu-cinema%2Fdossiers%2Finception-par-christopher-nolan-interview-references-indices-5926972-760.html&sl=fr&tl=en&hl= Translation]) {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n===Ending===\nThe film cuts to the [[closing credits]] from a shot of the top apparently starting to show an ever so faint wobble, inviting speculation about whether the final sequence was reality or another dream. Nolan confirmed that the ambiguity was deliberate,<ref name=\"wired-jan11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/11/pl_inception_nolan/all/|title=Inception's director discusses the film's ending and creation|last=Capps|first=Robers|date=December 8, 2010|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=January 24, 2011}}</ref> saying, \"I've been asked the question more times than I've ever been asked any other question about any other film I've made... What's funny to me is that people really do expect me to answer it.\"<ref name=\"insidemovies\">{{cite web|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2010/11/30/christopher-nolan-batman-inception/|title=Christopher Nolan on his 'last' Batman movie, an 'Inception' videogame, and that spinning top|last=Jensen|first=Jeff|date=November 30, 2010|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=January 6, 2011}}</ref> The film's script concludes with \"Behind him, on the table, the spinning top is STILL SPINNING. And we \u2013 FADE OUT\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Inception \u2013 The Shooting Script|author=Christopher Nolan|page=218|isbn=978-1-60887-015-8|publisher=Insight Editions}}</ref> Nolan said, \"I put that cut there at the end, imposing an ambiguity from outside the film. That always felt the right ending to me \u2014 it always felt like the appropriate 'kick' to me... The real point of the scene \u2014 and this is what I tell people \u2014 is that Cobb isn't looking at the top. He's looking at his kids. He's left it behind. That's the emotional significance of the thing.\"<ref name=\"insidemovies\"/> Also, [[Michael Caine]] explained his interpretation of the ending, saying, \"If I'm there it's real, because I'm never in the dream. I'm the guy who invented the dream.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screenrant.com/michael-caine-inception-ending-batman-3-benm-80670 |title=Michael Caine Says 'Inception' Ending Was No Dream |publisher=ScreenRant.com |last=Moore |first=Ben |date=September 10, 2010 |accessdate=June 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617034431/http://screenrant.com/michael-caine-inception-ending-batman-3-benm-80670/ |archivedate=June 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSome viewers have noted Cobb wears his wedding ring only during dream scenes. From this, they have concluded that Cobb is not dreaming in the final scene because he is not wearing the ring. However, this theory has been disputed.<ref>De Benedetti, Luca. \"[http://felixonline.co.uk/articles/2013-1-18-inception-the-theory-of-the-ring/ Inception: The Theory of the Ring.]\" [[Felix (newspaper)|Felix Online]]. N.p., January 12, 2013. Web. July 12, 2014.</ref>\n\n[[Mark Fisher (theorist)|Mark Fisher]] argued that \"a century of cultural theory\" cautions against accepting the [[authorial intent|author's interpretation]] as anything more than a supplementary text, and this all the more so given the theme of the instability of any one master position in Nolan's films. Therein the manipulator is often the one who ends up manipulated, and Cobb's \"not caring\" about whether or not his world is real may be the price of his happiness and release.<ref>Fisher, Mark \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.1525/fq.2011.64.3.37 The Lost Unconscious: Delusions and Dreams in ''Inception'']\", ''[[Film Quarterly]]'', Vol. 64, No. 3 (Spring 2011), pp. 37\u201345 University of California Press.</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n===Marketing===\nWarner Bros. spent US$100&nbsp;million marketing the film. Although ''Inception'' was not part of an existing franchise, Sue Kroll, president of Warner's worldwide marketing, said the company believed it could gain awareness due to the strength of \"Christopher Nolan as a brand\". Kroll declared that \"We don't have the brand equity that usually drives a big summer opening, but we have a great cast and a fresh idea from a filmmaker with a track record of making incredible movies. If you can't make those elements work, it's a sad day.\"<ref name=\"Fritz2\">{{Cite news|last=Fritz|first=Ben|title=Warner gambles on an unproven commodity|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=July 7, 2010|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-ct-inception-20100713,0,3119222.story|accessdate=July 13, 2010}}</ref> The studio also tried to maintain a campaign of secrecy\u2014as reported by the Senior VP of Interactive Marketing, Michael Tritter, \"You have this movie which is going to have a pretty big built in fanbase... but you also have a movie that you are trying to keep very secret. Chris [Nolan] really likes people to see his movies in a theater and not see it all beforehand so everything that you do to market that\u2014at least early on\u2014is with an eye to feeding the interest to fans.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcrw.com/etc/programs/tb/tb100816finding_salt_marketi|title=Finding 'Salt;' Marketing 'Inception'|publisher=[[KCRW]]|date=June 18, 2010|accessdate=July 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nA [[viral marketing]] campaign was employed for the film. After the revelation of the first teaser trailer, in August 2009, the film's official website featured only an animation of Cobb's spinning top. In December, the top toppled over and the website opened the online game ''Mind Crime'', which upon completion revealed ''Inception''{{'}}s poster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/first-poster-from-christopher-nolans-inception-starring-leonardo-dicaprio/12637/|title=First Poster from Christopher Nolan's INCEPTION Starring Leonardo DiCaprio|publisher=Collider.com|date=December 15, 2010|first=Matt|last=Goldberg|accessdate=July 5, 2011}}</ref> The rest of the campaign unrolled after [[WonderCon]] in April 2010, where Warner gave away promotional T-shirts featuring the PASIV briefcase used to create the dream space, and had a [[QR code]] linking to an online manual of the device.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ugo.com/movies/new-inception-site-goes-viral |title=Start Your Dream Weaving |publisher=[[UGO Networks]] |first=Silas |last=Lesnic |date=April 5, 2010 |accessdate=July 5, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510140254/http://www.ugo.com/movies/new-inception-site-goes-viral |archivedate=May 10, 2010}}</ref> ''Mind Crime'' also received a stage&nbsp;2 with more resources, including a hidden trailer for the movie.<ref name=trailer>{{cite news|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/official-full-length-inception-trailer-is-here|date=May 10, 2010|first=Brian|last=Gallagher|work=MovieWeb|title=Official Full-Length Inception Trailer Is Here!|accessdate=July 5, 2011}}</ref> More pieces of viral marketing began to surface before ''Inception''{{'}}s release, such as a manual filled with bizarre images and text sent to ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' magazine,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/underwire/2010/06/dream-share-manual/|title=Mysterious Dream-Share Manual Is a Viral Mind-Wipe|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|last= Thill|first=Scott |accessdate=June 3, 2010|date=June 1, 2010}}</ref> and the online publication of posters, ads, phone applications, and strange websites all related to the film.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Nick |last=Newman |url=http://thefilmstage.com/2010/06/07/new-inception-viral-poster-and-websites/ |title=New Inception Viral Poster |publisher=The Film Stage |accessdate=June 7, 2010 |date=June 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611055801/http://thefilmstage.com/2010/06/07/new-inception-viral-poster-and-websites |archivedate=June 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/07/09/us-inception-idUSTRE6680MM20100709|title='Inception' is no dream for marketers\n|first=Carl|last=DiOrio|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=July 9, 2010|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}</ref> Warner also released an online prequel comic, ''Inception: The Cobol Job''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://econsultancy.com/us/blog/6277-inception-multichannel-marketing-that-works-like-a-dream|title=Inception: multichannel marketing that works like a dream|publisher=eConsultancy|date=July 21, 2010|first=Matt|last=Owen |accessdate=July 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe official trailer released on May 10, 2010 through ''Mind Game'' was extremely well received.<ref name=trailer/> It featured an original piece of music, \"Mind Heist\", by recording artist [[Zack Hemsey]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Mind Heist|url=http://music.zackhemsey.com/album/mind-heist}}</ref> rather than music from the score.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/inception-trailer-composer-zack-hemsey-profiled/|title='Inception' Trailer Composer Zack Hemsey Profiled|publisher=Slash Film|accessdate=April 13, 2011|date=April 7, 2011}}</ref> The trailer quickly went viral with numerous [[mashup (video)|mashups]] copying its style, both by amateurs on sites like YouTube<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collider.com/ghostbusters-trailer-inception/68798/|title=GHOSTBUSTERS Trailer Re-Cut to INCEPTION Score |publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=April 13, 2011|date=January 7, 2011}}</ref> and by professionals on sites such as [[CollegeHumor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.collegehumor.com/video/6305356/50s-inception-trailer |title=50s Inception Trailer Profiled |publisher=CollegeHumor |accessdate=April 13, 2011 |date=October 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301121747/http://www.collegehumor.com/video/6305356/50s-inception-trailer |archivedate=March 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.collegehumor.com/video/6286263/a-capella-inception-trailer |title=A Capella Inception Trailer |publisher=CollegeHumor |accessdate=April 13, 2011 |date=September 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110418045802/http://www.collegehumor.com/video/6286263/a-capella-inception-trailer |archivedate=April 18, 2011}}</ref> On June 7, 2010, a behind-the-scenes featurette on the film was released in HD on Yahoo! Movies.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Jordan |last=Raup |url=http://thefilmstage.com/2010/06/07/behind-the-scenes-inception-featurette-now-available-in-hd/ |title=Behind The Scenes Inception Featurette Now Available In HD |publisher=The Film Stage |accessdate=June 7, 2010 |date=June 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610171853/http://thefilmstage.com/2010/06/07/behind-the-scenes-inception-featurette-now-available-in-hd |archivedate=June 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Inception'' was released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] on December 3, 2010, in France,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premiere.fr/Cinema/Photos/Reportages/PHOTOS-Inception-decouvrez-le-DVD-en-images/%28gid%29/2467699|title=PHOTOS \u2013 Inception : d\u00e9couvrez le DVD en images|work=[[Premiere (magazine)|Premi\u00e8re]]|accessdate=May 4, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209220017/http://www.premiere.fr/Cinema/Photos/Reportages/PHOTOS-Inception-decouvrez-le-DVD-en-images/(gid)/2467699|archivedate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> and the week after in the UK and USA (December 7, 2010).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homevideo.about.com/od/newdvdreleases/tp/New-DVD-Releases-December-7-2010-a.htm|title=New DVD Releases \u2013 December 7, 2010|first=Ivana|last=Redwine|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=May 4, 2011|date=December 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moviefone.co.uk/2010/12/06/new-on-dvd-week-of-6-december/|title=New on DVD: Week of December 6|date=December 6, 2010|first=Joe|last=Barton|publisher=[[Moviefone]] |accessdate=April 5, 2011}}</ref> Warner Bros. also made available in the United States a limited Blu-ray edition packaged in a metal replica of the PASIV briefcase, which included extras such as a metal replica of the spinning top totem. With a production run of less than 2000, it sold out in one weekend.<ref name=Limited>[http://www.wbshop.com/on/demandware.store/Sites-WB-Site/default/Product-Show?pid=INWBDVDBDBC&adid=1110InceptEml&AID=10501819 Inception BD/DVD Briefcase Gift Set] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101118194954/http://www.wbshop.com/on/demandware.store/Sites-WB-Site/default/Product-Show?pid=INWBDVDBDBC&adid=1110InceptEml&AID=10501819 |date=November 18, 2010 }}. Warner Bros. Retrieved November 23, 2010.</ref> ''Inception'' was released on 4K Blu-ray and [[digital copy]] along with other Christopher Nolan films on December 19, 2017.<ref>{{Citation|title=Christopher Nolan Collection 4K Blu-ray|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Christopher-Nolan-Collection-4K-Blu-ray/193522/|accessdate=March 29, 2018}}</ref> {{as of|2018}}, the [[home video]] releases have sold over 9{{nbsp}}million units and grossed over {{US$|160 million|long=no}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=Inception (2010) \u2013 Financial Information |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Inception#tab=video-sales |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Putative video game{{anchor|Proposed video game}}===\nIn a November 2010 interview, Nolan expressed his intention to develop a video game set in the ''Inception'' world, working with a team of collaborators. He described it as \"a longer-term proposition\", referring to the medium of video games as \"something I've wanted to explore\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Jensen|first=Jeff|title=Christopher Nolan on his 'last' Batman movie, an 'Inception' videogame, and that spinning top|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2010/11/30/christopher-nolan-batman-inception/|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=December 3, 2010|date=November 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office{{anchor|Box-office performance}}===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Film\n! colspan=\"1\" | Release date\n! colspan=\"3\" | Box office revenue\n! colspan=\"2\" text=\"wrap\" | Box office ranking\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Budget\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Reference\n|-\n! United States\n! North America\n! International\n! Worldwide\n! All-time United States\n! All-time worldwide\n|-\n| ''Inception ''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| July 2010\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| US$292,576,195\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| US$532,956,569\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| US$825,532,764\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| No. 80\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| No. 67\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| US$160,000,000\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url= http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=inception.htm |title= Inception (2010) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate=August 18, 2011}}</ref>\n|}\n\n''Inception'' was released in both conventional and [[IMAX]] theaters on July 16, 2010.<ref name=\"release\">{{Cite news|first=Jeff |last=Bock |url=http://www.ercboxoffice.com/index.php?page=news&news_id=114 |title=Wb name drops big titles |publisher=ERC Box Office |date=February 24, 2009 |accessdate=February 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226205532/http://www.ercboxoffice.com/index.php?page=news&news_id=114 |archivedate=February 26, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Vlessing|first=Etan|title=Imax books ''Inception''|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=October 1, 2009|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/imax-books-inception-89552|accessdate=October 1, 2009}}</ref> The film had its world premiere at [[Leicester Square]] in London, United Kingdom on July 8, 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Plumb|first=Alastair|title=''Inception'' World Premiere Report|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=July 9, 2010|url=http://www.empireonline.com/news/feed.asp?NID=28324|accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> In the United States and Canada, ''Inception'' was released theatrically in 3,792 conventional theaters and 195 [[IMAX]] theaters.<ref name=\"release\" /> The film grossed US$21.8&nbsp;million during its opening day on July 16, 2010, with midnight screenings in 1,500 locations.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Finke |first=Nikki |url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/07/solid-3m-midnights-for-nolans-inception/ |title='Inception' Dreams Up $21.4M Friday And Possible $52M Weekend; No Magic For 'Sorcerer's Apprentice' With $5.4M/$16.5M |magazine=Deadline.com |date=July 17, 2010 |accessdate=July 18, 2010}}</ref> Overall the film made US$62.7&nbsp;million and debuted at No.1 on its opening weekend.<ref name=\"mojo-weekend\" /> ''Inception''{{'}}s opening weekend gross made it the second-highest-grossing debut for a [[science fiction film|science-fiction film]] that was not a sequel, remake or adaptation, behind ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]''{{'s}} US$77&nbsp;million opening weekend gross in 2009.<ref name=\"mojo-weekend\">{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2862&p=.htm |title=Weekend Report: 'Inception' Incites Intense Interest |last=Gray |first=Brandon |accessdate=July 21, 2010 |date=July 19, 2010|website=Box Office Mojo}}</ref> The film held the top spot of the box office rankings in its second and third weekends, with drops of just 32% (US$42.7&nbsp;million) and 36% (US$27.5&nbsp;million) respectively,<ref>{{cite web|date=July 26, 2010 |first=Brandon |last=Gray |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2865&p=.htm |title='Inception' Maintains Grip, 'Salt' Savors Second Place |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=September 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=August 2, 2010 |first=Brandon |last=Gray |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2874&p=.htm |title='Inception' Keeps Dream Alive |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=September 4, 2010}}</ref> before dropping to second place in its fourth week, behind ''[[The Other Guys]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2882&p=.htm |title=Weekend Report: 'Other Guys' Arrest Audiences, 'Step Up' Gets Served, 'Inception' Lingers|last=Gray|first=Brandon|accessdate=June 19, 2011|date=August 9, 2010|website=Box Office Mojo}}</ref>\n\n''Inception'' grossed US$292&nbsp;million in the United States and Canada, US$56&nbsp;million in the United Kingdom, Ireland and [[Malta]] and US$475&nbsp;million in other countries for a total of US$823&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref name=\"Mojo\"/> Its five highest-grossing markets after the US and Canada (US$292) were China (US$68million), the United Kingdom, Ireland and [[Malta]] (US$56&nbsp;million), France and the [[Maghreb]] region (US$43&nbsp;million), Japan (US$40&nbsp;million) and [[South Korea]] (US$38&nbsp;million).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=inception.htm |title=Inception |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=October 22, 2010}}</ref> It was the sixth-highest-grossing film of 2010 in North America,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=2010&p=.htm |title=2010 DOMESTIC GROSSES |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> and the [[2010 in film#Highest-grossing films|fourth-highest-grossing film of 2010]], behind ''[[Toy Story 3]]'', ''[[Alice in Wonderland (2010 film)|Alice in Wonderland]]'' and ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2010&p=.htm |title=2010 WORLDWIDE GROSSES |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=September 9, 2010}}</ref> ''Inception'' is the third most lucrative production in [[Christopher Nolan]]'s career\u2014behind ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' and ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Director&id=christophernolan.htm|title=Christopher Nolan|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>\u2014 and the second most for [[Leonardo DiCaprio]]\u2014behind ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Actor&id=leonardodicaprio.htm |title=Leonardo DiCaprio |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=November 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{Anchor|Critics}}\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 87% based on 352 reviews, with an average rating of 8.11/10. The website's critical consensus reads: \"Smart, innovative, and thrilling, ''Inception'' is that rare summer blockbuster that succeeds viscerally as well as intellectually.\"<ref name=\"tomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/inception/|title=Inception (2010) |work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=April 23, 2018}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], another review aggregator, assigned the film a weighted average score of 74 out of 100, based on 42 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/inception |title=Inception |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |work = [[Metacritic]]|accessdate=July 27, 2010}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Andrew|last=Stewart|title='Inception' tops weekend box office |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118021880.html|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 18, 2010|accessdate=August 18, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called ''Inception'' a \"wildly ingenious chess game,\" and concluded \"the result is a knockout.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Travers |first=Peter|title=''Inception''|work=Rolling Stone|date=July 12, 2010 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/17388/180225 |accessdate=July 14, 2010}}</ref> Justin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the film as \"a conceptual [[wikt:tour de force|tour de force]]\" and wrote, \"applying a vivid sense of procedural detail to a fiendishly intricate yarn set in the [[labyrinth]] of the [[unconscious mind]], the writer-director has devised a heist thriller for [[surrealist]]s, a [[Jung]]ian's ''[[Rififi]]'', that challenges viewers to sift through multiple layers of (un)reality.\"<ref name=\"variety-review\">{{Cite news |last=Chang |first=Justin|title=''Inception''|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 5, 2010 |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117943114.html |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> Jim Vejvoda of [[IGN]] rated the film as perfect, deeming it \"a singular accomplishment from a filmmaker who has only gotten better with each film.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Vejvoda |first=Jim |title=''\"Inception\" Para la gran mayoria de los criticos Inception es una de las mejores peliculas de la historia del cine.'' Review |work=[[IGN]] |date=July 6, 2010 |url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/110/1103912p1.html |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Relevant (magazine)|Relevant]]''{{'}}s David Roark called it Nolan's \"greatest accomplishment,\" saying, \"Visually, intellectually and emotionally, ''Inception'' is a masterpiece.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Roark |first=David |title=''Inception'' |work=[[Relevant Magazine]] |date=July 12, 2010 |url=http://www.relevantmagazine.com/culture/film/reviews/22278-inception |accessdate=July 14, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100721011123/http://www.relevantmagazine.com/culture/film/reviews/22278-inception |archive-date=July 21, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn its August 2010 issue, ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine gave the film a full five stars and wrote, \"it feels like [[Stanley Kubrick]] adapting the work of the great sci-fi author [[William Gibson]] [...] Nolan delivers another true original: welcome to an undiscovered country.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Pierce |first=Nev |title=''Inception'' |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=June 7, 2010 |url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=136118 |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s Lisa Schwarzbaum gave the film a B+ grade and wrote, \"It's a rolling explosion of images as hypnotizing and sharply angled as any in a drawing by [[M. C. Escher]] or a state-of-the-biz video game; the backwards splicing of Nolan's own ''Memento'' looks rudimentary by comparison.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Schwarzbaum |first=Lisa |title=''Inception'' |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=July 12, 2010 |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20401172,00.html |accessdate=July 13, 2010}}</ref> The ''[[New York Post]]''{{'}}s [[Lou Lumenick]] gave the film a four-star rating and wrote, \"DiCaprio, who has never been better as the tortured hero, draws you in with a love story that will appeal even to non-sci-fi fans.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lumenick|first=Lou|title=Dream team!|work=New York Post|date=July 14, 2010 |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/movies/dream_team_105fXIW5839pHficdGU9vN|accessdate=July 14, 2010}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' awarded the film a full four stars and said that ''Inception'' \"is all about process, about fighting our way through enveloping sheets of reality and dream, reality within dreams, dreams without reality. It's a breathtaking juggling act.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ebert|first=Roger|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/inception-2010|title=''Inception''|date=July 14, 2010|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=July 15, 2010|url-status=live|authorlink=Roger Ebert}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]], also of the ''Sun-Times'', gave ''Inception'' an \"A+\" score and called it \"one of the best movies of the [21st] century.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.richardroeper.com/reviews/inception.aspx|title=''Inception'' Review |last=Roeper |first=Richard |authorlink=Richard Roeper |work=Chicago Sun-Times |accessdate=July 21, 2010}}</ref> [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]'s [[Mark Kermode]] named ''Inception'' as the best film of 2010, stating that \"''Inception'' is proof that people are not stupid, that cinema is not trash, and that it is possible for blockbusters and art to be the same thing.\"<ref name=\"Kermode\">{{cite video |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/markkermode/2010/12/my_top_five_films_of_the_year.html |accessdate=February 9, 2011 |date=December 24, 2010 |first=Mark |last=Kermode |authorlink=Mark Kermode |title=Kermode Uncut: My Top Five Films of the Year |publisher=BBC |time=5:05}}</ref>\n\n[[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film 3 out of 4 stars and wrote, \"I found myself wishing ''Inception'' were weirder, further out [...] the film is Nolan's labyrinth all the way, and it's gratifying to experience a summer movie with large visual ambitions and with nothing more or less on its mind than (as [[Shakespeare]] said) a dream that hath no bottom.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Phillips |first=Michael |title=''Inception'' |work=Chicago Tribune|date=July 15, 2010|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-0713-inception-20100715,0,6233986.column |accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> ''TIME Magazine''{{'}}s [[Richard Corliss]] wrote that the film's \"noble intent is to implant one man's vision in the mind of a vast audience [...] The idea of moviegoing as communal dreaming is a century old. With ''Inception'', viewers have a chance to see that notion get a state-of-the-art update.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Corliss|first=Richard|authorlink=Richard Corliss |title=''Inception'': Whose Mind Is It, Anyway? |work=TIME |date=July 14, 2010|url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,2003808,00.html|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> [[Kenneth Turan]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' felt that Nolan was able to blend \"the best of traditional and modern filmmaking. If you're searching for smart and nervy popular entertainment, this is what it looks like.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Turan|first=Kenneth|authorlink=Kenneth Turan|title=''Inception''|work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 16, 2010|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-inception-20100716,0,5478728.story|accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref>\n''[[USA Today]]''{{'s}} Claudia Puig gave the film three-and-a-half out of four stars and felt that Nolan \"regards his viewers as possibly smarter than they are\u2014or at least as capable of rising to his inventive level. That's a tall order. But it's refreshing to find a director who makes us stretch, even occasionally struggle, to keep up.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Puig|first=Claudia|title=You definitely won't sleep through complex thriller ''Inception''|work=[[USA Today]] |date=July 15, 2010|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2010-07-15-inception15_ST_N.htm|accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\nNot all reviewers gave the film positive reviews. ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]] Magazine''{{'}}s [[David Edelstein]] claimed in his review that he had \"no idea what so many people are raving about. It's as if someone went into their heads while they were sleeping and planted the idea that ''Inception'' is a visionary masterpiece and\u2014hold on ... Whoa! I think I get it. The movie is a metaphor for the power of delusional hype\u2014a metaphor for itself.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Edelstein|first=David|title=Dream a Little Dream|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=July 11, 2010 |url=http://nymag.com/movies/reviews/67155/|accessdate=July 13, 2010}}</ref> ''[[The New York Observer]]''{{'}}s [[Rex Reed]] explained that the film's development was \"pretty much what we've come to expect from summer movies in general and Christopher Nolan movies in particular ... [it] doesn't seem like much of an accomplishment to me.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reed |first=Rex |title=Can Someone Please Explain ''Inception'' to Me? |work=[[The New York Observer]] |date=July 13, 2010 |url=http://www.observer.com/2010/culture/can-someone-please-explain-inception-me |accessdate=July 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715052057/http://www.observer.com/2010/culture/can-someone-please-explain-inception-me |archivedate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> [[A. O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' commented \"there is a lot to see in ''Inception'', there is nothing that counts as genuine vision. Mr. Nolan's idea of the mind is too literal, too logical, and too rule-bound to allow the full measure of madness.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Scott |first=A. O. |authorlink=A. O. Scott|title=This Time the Dream's on Me|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 15, 2010 |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2010/07/16/movies/16inception.html |accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]''{{'}}s [[David Denby]] considered the film to \"not nearly [be] as much fun as Nolan imagined it to be\", concluding that \"''Inception'' is a stunning-looking film that gets lost in fabulous intricacies, a movie devoted to its own workings and to little else.\"<ref name=\"Denby\">{{cite news|last=Denby|first=David|authorlink=David Denby (film critic) |title=Dream Factory|url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/cinema/2010/07/26/100726crci_cinema_denby|accessdate=February 10, 2011|newspaper=[[The New Yorker]] |date=July 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWhile some critics have tended to view the film as perfectly straightforward, and even criticize its overarching themes as \"the stuff of torpid platitudes,\" online discussion has been much more positive.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Nick |last=Schager |title=Inception |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/inception/4898 |work=[[Slant (magazine)|Slant]] |date=July 14, 2010 |accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref> Heated debate has centered on the ambiguity of the ending, with many critics like Devin Faraci making the case that the film is self-referential and tongue-in-cheek, both a film about film-making and a dream about dreams.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Devin|last=Faraci|title=Never Wake Up: The Meaning and Secret of Inception |url=http://www.chud.com/24477/never-wake-up-the-meaning-and-secret-of-inception/|publisher=Chud.com|date=July 19, 2010|accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref> Other critics read ''Inception'' as Christian allegory and focus on the film's use of religious and water symbolism.<ref>{{Cite web |first=David |last=Lancashire |title=Cobb is Dead |url=http://www.quora.com/Inception-2010-movie/Was-Cobb-dreaming-in-the-final-sequence-of-Inception/all_comments/David-Lancashire |date=October 6, 2010 |accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref> Yet other critics, such as [[Kristin Thompson]], see less value in the ambiguous ending of the film and more in its structure and novel method of storytelling, highlighting ''Inception'' as a new form of narrative that revels in \"continuous exposition\".<ref>{{Cite web |first=Kristin |last=Thomas|title=Revisiting Inception|url=http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2010/08/12/revisiting-inception/ |publisher=Observations on Film Art (blog) |date=August 12, 2010|accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSeveral critics and scholars have noted the film has many striking similarities to the 2006 [[anime]] film ''[[Paprika (2006 film)|Paprika]]'' by [[Satoshi Kon]] (and [[Yasutaka Tsutsui]]'s 1993 [[Paprika (novel)|novel of the same name]]), including plot similarities, similar scenes, and similar characters, arguing that ''Inception'' was influenced by ''Paprika''.<ref name=\"Drazen\">{{cite book |last=Drazen |first=Patrick |title=Anime Explosion!: The What? Why? and Wow! of Japanese Animation, Revised and Updated Edition |date=2014 |publisher=[[Stone Bridge Press]] |isbn=9781611725506 |url={{Google books|-s30AgAAQBAJ |page=PA339 |keywords= |text=|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref><ref name=\"Wardlow\">{{cite web |last=Wardlow |first=Ciara |title=The Synergy of 'Inception' and 'Paprika' |url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/the-synergy-of-inception-and-paprika-ffefd0973f12/ |website=[[Film School Rejects]] |date=March 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web |last=Rizzo-Smith |first=Julian |title=An Ode to Anime Auteur Satoshi Kon |url=https://in.ign.com/paprika/127083/feature/an-ode-to-anime-auteur-satoshi-kon |website=[[IGN]] |date=August 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Horner\">{{cite web |last=Horner |first=Joshua |title=20 Suspiciously Similar Movie Scenes You Never Noticed |url=http://whatculture.com/film/20-suspiciously-similar-movie-scenes-never-noticed?page=4 |website=WhatCulture |page=4 |date=January 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Boone |first1=Steven |title='Inception': As eye-catching, and as profound, as an Usher concert |url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2010/07/inception-as-eye-catching-and-as-profound-as-an-usher-concert-067223 |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |work=[[Politico]] |date=July 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Emerson |first1=Jim |title=Inception: Has Christopher Nolan forgotten how to dream? |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/scanners/inception-has-christopher-nolan-forgotten-how-to-dream |website=[[RogerEbert.com]] |date=July 17, 2010 |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> Several sources have also noted plot similarities between the film and the 2002 [[Scrooge McDuck|Uncle Scrooge]] comic ''[[The Dream of a Lifetime]]'' by [[Don Rosa]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Brown|first=Damon|title=Was 'Inception' inspired by Donald Duck?|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/TECH/web/08/10/inception.donald.duck/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=December 29, 2011|date=August 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Gornstein |first=Leslie |title=Did Inception Really Rip Off Scrooge McDuck? |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/ask_the_answer_bitch/did_inception_really_rip_off_scrooge/193794 |work=[[E!#E! Online|E! Online]] |accessdate=December 29, 2011 |date=August 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206031007/http://www.eonline.com/news/ask_the_answer_bitch/did_inception_really_rip_off_scrooge/193794 |archivedate=February 6, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sean|first=O'Neal|title=The \"Inception ripped-off Scrooge McDuck\" theory that will briefly amuse you |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-inception-rippedoff-scrooge-mcduck-theory-that,43814/ |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |accessdate=December 29, 2011 |date=August 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===<span id=\"Top ten lists\"></span><span id=\"Legacy\"></span>Year-end and all-time lists===\n''Inception'' appeared on over 273 critics' lists of the top ten films of 2010, being picked as number-one on at least 55 of those lists.<ref name=\"criticstop10\">{{Cite web |url=http://criticstop10.com/best-of-2010/ |title=Home Page \u2013 Best of 2010 |publisher=CriticsTop10 |accessdate=May 4, 2011}}</ref> It was the second most mentioned film in both the top ten lists and number-one rankings, only behind ''[[The Social Network]]'', joining that film, ''[[Toy Story 3]]'', ''[[The King's Speech]]'', and ''[[Black Swan (film)|Black Swan]]'' as the most critically acclaimed films of 2010.<ref name=\"criticstop10\" />\n\nCritics and publications who ranked the film first for that year included [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', [[Kenneth Turan]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' (tied with ''[[The Social Network]]'' and ''[[Toy Story 3]]''), Tasha Robinson of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine, and Kirk Honeycutt of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''.<ref name=\"metacritictopten\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critic-top-ten-lists |title=2010 Film Critic Top Ten Lists |last=Dietz |first=Jason |website=[[Metacritic]] |date=December 9, 2010 |accessdate=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe film's placement in some notable top ten lists:<ref name=\"metacritictopten\" /><!-- arbitrary list? what's the criteria for inclusion here -->\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 [[Richard Roeper]], ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 [[Kenneth Turan]], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' (tied with ''[[The Social Network]]'' and ''[[Toy Story 3]]'')\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Tasha Robinson, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]''\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Kirk Honeycutt, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 [[Peter Travers]], ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;- [[Christy Lemire]], ''[[Associated Press]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 [[James Berardinelli]], ''Reelviews''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Gregory Ellwood, ''[[HitFix]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Lisa Kennedy, ''[[Denver Post]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Bill Goodykoontz, ''[[Arizona Republic]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 [[Stephen Holden]], ''[[The New York Times]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 [[Philip French]], ''[[The Observer]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 [[FX Feeney]], ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n* 4th&nbsp;\u2013 Keith Phipps, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Nathan Rabin]], ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Lou Lumenick]], ''[[New York Post]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Roger Ebert]], ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 Elizabeth Weitzman, ''[[New York Daily News]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Ann Hornaday]], ''[[Washington Post]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Caryn James]], ''[[Indiewire]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 Claudia Puig, ''[[USA Today]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;- David Germain, [[Associated Press]]\n* 6th&nbsp;- Rene Rodriguez, ''[[Miami Herald]]''\n* 7th&nbsp;\u2013 Noel Murray, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n* 8th&nbsp;\u2013  Mike Scott, ''[[The Times-Picayune]]''\n* 9th&nbsp;\u2013 Drew McWeeny, ''[[HitFix]]''\n* 10th&nbsp;\u2013 [[J. Hoberman]], ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n* 10th&nbsp;\u2013 Peter Hartlaub, ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\nIn March 2011, the film was voted by [[BBC Radio 1]] and [[BBC Radio 1Xtra]] listeners as their ninth favorite film of all time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/radio1movies/ |title=Radio 1 Movies Blog |publisher=BBC |accessdate=July 23, 2013}}</ref> ''Inception'' was voted as the third best sci-fi film of all time in the 2011 list ''[[Best in Film: The Greatest Movies of Our Time]]'', based on a poll conducted by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] and ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''. In 2012, ''Inception'' was ranked the 35th Best Edited Film of All Time by the [[Motion Picture Editors Guild]].<ref name=\"editorsguild\">{{cite web|url=https://www.editorsguild.com/magazine.cfm?ArticleID=1101|title=The 75 Best Editied Films |work=CineMontage |accessdate=June 1, 2013 |date=Summer 2013}}</ref> In the same year, ''[[Total Film]]'' named it the most rewatchable movie of all time.<ref name=Rewatchable>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/50-most-rewatchable-movies/inception-2010 |title=50 Most Rewatchable Movies |magazine=[[Total Film]] |accessdate=July 24, 2013}}</ref> In 2014, ''Empire'' ranked ''Inception'' the tenth greatest film ever made on their list of \"The 301 Greatest Movies Of All Time\" as voted by the magazine's readers,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/301/list.asp?page=29 |title=The 301 Greatest Movies Of All Time |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> while ''Rolling Stone'' magazine named it the second best science fiction film since the turn of the century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/lists/the-top-20-sci-fi-films-of-the-21st-century-20140515 |title=The Top 20 Sci-Fi Films of the 21st Century |work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=August 14, 2014}}</ref> ''Inception'' was ranked 84th on ''Hollywood's 100 Favorite Films'', a list compiled by ''The Hollywood Reporter'' in 2014, surveying \"Studio chiefs, Oscar winners and TV royalty\".<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=June 22, 2015 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/100-greatest-films-all-time-714192/84-inception|title=Hollywood's 100 Favorite Films|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> In 2016, ''Inception'' was voted the 51st [[BBC's 100 Greatest Films of the 21st Century|best film of the 21st Century]] by [[BBC]], as picked by 177 film critics from around the world.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=August 23, 2016|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films?ocid=twcul |title=The 21st Century's 100 Greatest Films|work=BBC}}</ref> The film was included in the [[Visual Effects Society]]'s list of \"The Most Influential Visual Effects Films of All Time\".<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=September 16, 2017|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/09/visual-effects-society-top-70-vfx-films-star-wars-blade-runner-citizen-kane-1201875595/|title=Visual Effects Society: The Top 70 VFX Films of All Time Include 'Star Wars,' 'Blade Runner,' and 'Citizen Kane' |work=Indiewire}}</ref> In 2019, ''Total Film'' named ''Inception'' the best film of the 2010s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/decade-best-movies-2010-2019/4/ |title=The 100 best movies of the decade |work=[[Total Film]] |accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref> Many critics and media outlets included ''Inception'' in their rankings of the best films of the 2010s.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The 100 Greatest Movies Of The 21st Century: 10 - 1|magazine=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=January 11, 2020|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/best-movies-century-page-10/|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=September 5, 2019|url=https://mashable.com/article/best-films-of-2010s-decade/|title=The 15 best films of the 2010s|work=mashable.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=November 5, 2019|url=https://medium.com/luwd-media/the-100-best-films-of-the-2010s-d30b2b54903d|title=The 100 Best Films of the 2010s|work=medium.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/best-movies-decade-2010s-list/|title=Best movies of 2010s decade|last=Leadbeater|first=Alex|date=2 March 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=November 5, 2019|url=https://film.avclub.com/the-100-best-movies-of-the-2010s-1839846306|title=The 100 best movies of the 2010s|work=The A.V. Club}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=May 2, 2019|url=https://www.worldofreel.com/blog/2019/4/critics-poll-top-75-movies-of-the-decade|title=Critics Poll: Top 75 Movies of the Decade|work=World of Reel}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' placed the title on its top ten list of the most overrated films. ''Telegraph''{{'}}s Tim Robey stated, \"It's a criminal failing of the movie that it purports to be about people's dreams being invaded, but demonstrates no instinct at all for what a dream has ever felt like, and no flair for making us feel like we're in one, at any point.\"<ref>{{cite web |first1=Tim |last1=Robey |title=10 most overrated films of all time |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/10767345/10-most-overrated-films-of-all-time.html|website=telegraph.co.uk |date=April 21, 2014 |accessdate=June 1, 2014}}</ref> The film won an informal poll by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' as the most overrated movie of 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2010/12/inception-christopher-nolan-overrated.html |title='Inception' wins informal poll as most overrated movie of 2010 (Part 2) |date=December 30, 2010 |accessdate=June 2, 2014 |first1=Steven |last1=Zeitchik |website=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Inception}}\n\nThe film won many awards in technical categories, such as [[Academy Awards]] for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]], and [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]],<ref name=oscars>{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/83/nominees.html |title=Nominees for the 83rd Academy Awards |publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref> and the [[British Academy Film Awards]] for [[BAFTA Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Special Visual Effects|Best Special Visual Effects]] and [[BAFTA Award for Best Sound|Best Sound]].<ref name=BAFTA>{{cite web |url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/2011-film-awards,1572,BA.html |title=2011 BAFTA Awards Nominees |publisher=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] |accessdate=January 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110110061729/http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/2011-film-awards%2C1572%2CBA.html |archivedate=January 10, 2011  }}</ref> In most of its artistic nominations, such as Film, Director, and Screenplay at the Oscars, BAFTAs and [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globes]], the film was defeated by ''[[The Social Network]]'' or ''[[The King's Speech]]''.<ref name=oscars/><ref name=BAFTA/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/nominations/year/2010 |title=68th Annual Golden Globe Awards Nominations |publisher=[[Hollywood Foreign Press Association]] |accessdate=January 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Ap0fVUMt?url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/nominations/year/2010 |archivedate=September 20, 2012  }}</ref> However, the film did win the two highest honors for a science fiction or fantasy film: the 2011 [[Bradbury Award]] for best dramatic production<ref name= Nebulas>{{cite web |url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2011/05/2011-nebula-award-winners |title=2011 Nebula Award winners |publisher=[[Tor.com]] |accessdate=October 16, 2011}}</ref> and the 2011 [[Hugo Award]] for best dramatic presentation, long form.<ref name=Hugos>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/2011/08/2011-hugo-award-winners/ |title=2011 Hugo Award winners |publisher=[[Hugo Awards]] |accessdate=October 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nNumerous pop and hip hop songs reference the film, including [[Common (rapper)|Common]]'s \"Blue Sky,\" [[N.E.R.D]]'s \"[[Hypnotize U]],\" [[XV (rapper)|XV]]'s \"The Kick,\" [[The Black Eyed Peas]]' \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (The Black Eyed Peas song)|Just Can't Get Enough]],\" [[Lil Wayne]]'s \"[[6 Foot 7 Foot]],\" [[Jennifer Lopez]]'s \"[[On the Floor]],\" and [[B.o.B]]'s \"[[Strange Clouds (song)|Strange Clouds]],\" while [[T.I.]] had ''Inception''-based artwork on two of his mixtapes. An instrumental track by [[Joe Budden]] is titled \"Inception.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Zorgel |title=Why do rappers love the movie Inception so much? |url=http://www.aux.tv/2012/03/why-do-rappers-love-the-movie-inception-so-much/ |work=AUX.TV |date=March 8, 2012 |accessdate=December 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611062544/http://www.aux.tv/2012/03/why-do-rappers-love-the-movie-inception-so-much/ | archive-date=June 11, 2016 | url-status=dead  }}</ref> The animated series ''[[South Park]]'' parodies the film in the show's tenth episode of its [[South Park (season 14)|fourteenth season]], titled \"[[Insheeption]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hill|first1=Scott T.|title=South Park Satirizes Inception's Mind-Wipe |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/10/south-park-inception/|website=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=November 15, 2017|date=October 21, 2010}}</ref> The film was also an influence for [[Ariana Grande]]'s video for \"[[No Tears Left to Cry]].\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Willman |first1=Chris |title=Song Review: Ariana Grande's 'No Tears Left to Cry' |url=https://variety.com/2018/music/news/ariana-grande-no-tears-left-to-cry-review-1202770171/ |website=Variety |accessdate=July 6, 2018 |date=April 19, 2018}}</ref> \"[[Lawnmower Dog]]\", the second episode of the animated comedy show ''[[Rick and Morty]]'', parodied the film.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goldberg |first1=Lesley |title=Adult Swim's 'Rick and Morty' Takes On 'Inception' |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/adult-swims-rick-morty-takes-661896 |website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> In an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', named  \"[[How I Wet Your Mother]]\", the plot spoofs ''Inception'' with various scenes parodying moments from the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2012/03/when-the-simpsons-went-inception-48463/|title=When \u2018The Simpsons\u2019 Went \u2018Inception\u2019|last=Willmore|first=Alison|date=March 27, 2020|website=[[Indiewire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The showrunners of the television series ''[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]'' said its season 4 finale was inspired by ''Inception''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2423571/the-flash-showrunner-explains-how-the-finale-is-inspired-by-inception|title=The Flash Showrunner Explains How The Finale Is Inspired By Inception|last=Venable|first=Nick|date=February 7, 2020|magazine=Cinemablend|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> In February 2020, American singer-songwriter [[Taylor Swift]] released a lyric video for her single \"[[The Man (Taylor Swift song)|The Man]]\", which featured visuals bearing resemblance to the film. The song also name-checks DiCaprio in its lyrics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://popcrush.com/taylor-swift-the-man-lyric-video/|title=Taylor Swift's 'The Man' Lyric Video Features a Subtle Nod to Leonardo DiCaprio|last=Reda|first=Natasha|date=February 7, 2020|magazine=[[PopCrush]]|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film inspired the suffix ''[[wikt:-ception|-ception]]'', which can be appended to a noun to indicate a layering, nesting, or recursion of the thing in question.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://neologisms.rice.edu/index.php?a=term&d=1&t=17573 |title=-ception \u2013 The Rice University Neologisms Database |publisher=Rice University |accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n* [[Suggestion]]\n* [[Simulacrum]]\n* [[Dreamscape_(1984_film)|Dreamscape]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book|last1 =Johnson|first1 =David Kyle (Editor)|last2 =Irwin|first2 =William|year =2011|title =Inception and Philosophy: Because It's Never Just a Dream|publisher =John Wiley & Sons|isbn =1-118-07263-4|url-access =registration|url =https://archive.org/details/inceptionphiloso00john}}\n* {{Cite book |last1= Nolan |first1= Christopher (Author)|last2=Nolan|first2=Jonathan|year =2010 |title =Inception: The Shooting Script|publisher=Insight Editions |isbn=1-60887-015-4}}\n* {{Cite journal |last = Crawford |first = Kevin Ray (Author) |title =The Rhetorics of the Time-Image: Deleuzian Metadiscourse on the Role of Nooshock Temporality (viz. \"Inception\") in Christopher Nolan's Cinema of the Brain|publisher=ProQuest LLC |year =2012}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Inception (film)|Inception}}\n{{Commons category|Inception (film)|Inception}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.inceptionmovie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1375666}}\n* {{AllMovie title|480818}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|inception}}\n\n{{Christopher Nolan}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by Inception|Awards for ''Inception'']]\n|list =\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Action Film}}\n{{Empire Award for Best Film}}\n{{Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation, Long Form}}\n{{Nebula Award for Best Script/Bradbury Award 2001\u20132020}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Science Fiction Film 1991\u20132010}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAward StuntEnsembleMotionPicture}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inception}}\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s action adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:Action films featuring female antagonists]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action adventure films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:Science fiction adventure films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction thriller films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Best Film Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:British psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British action adventure films]]\n[[Category:British action thriller films]]\n[[Category:British science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:British science fiction thriller films]]\n[[Category:D-Box motion-enhanced films]]\n[[Category:Films about dreams]]\n[[Category:Films about telepresence]]\n[[Category:Films about widowhood]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Christopher Nolan]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Christopher Nolan]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Thomas Tull]]\n[[Category:Films set in Japan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films set in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Sound Editing Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Sound Mixing Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Visual Effects Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films whose cinematographer won the Best Cinematography Academy Award]]\n[[Category:American heist films]]\n[[Category:Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation, Long Form winning works]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Legendary Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Christopher Nolan]]\n[[Category:Syncopy Inc. films]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Czech Lion Awards winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Philosophical fiction]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|2010 science fiction action film directed by Christopher Nolan}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Inception\n| image          = Inception (2010) theatrical poster.jpg\n| alt            = A man in a suit with a gun in his right hand is flanked by five other individuals in the middle of a street which, behind them, is folded upwards. Leonardo DiCaprio's name and those of other cast members are shown above the words \"Your Mind Is the Scene of the Crime\". The title of the film \"INCEPTION\", film credits, and theatrical and IMAX release dates are shown at the bottom.\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Christopher Nolan]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Emma Thomas]]\n* Christopher Nolan\n}}\n| writer         = Christopher Nolan\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Leonardo DiCaprio]]\n* [[Ken Watanabe]]\n* [[Joseph Gordon-Levitt]]\n* [[Marion Cotillard]]\n* [[Ellen Page]]\n* [[Tom Hardy]]\n* [[Cillian Murphy]]\n* [[Tom Berenger]]\n* [[Michael Caine]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Hans Zimmer]]\n| cinematography = [[Wally Pfister]]\n| editing        = [[Lee Smith (editor)|Lee Smith]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Legendary Pictures]]\n* [[Syncopy Inc.|Syncopy]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2010|07|08|[[Odeon Leicester Square]]|2010|07|16|United States and United Kingdom}}\n| runtime        = 148 minutes<ref>{{cite web |title=Inception |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/inception-2010-2 |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=June 29, 2010 |accessdate=August 8, 2010}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States<ref name=\"Lumiere\">{{cite web|url=http://lumiere.obs.coe.int/web/film_info/?id=34895|title=Film: Inception|publisher=[[Lumiere (database)|Lumiere]]|accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n* United Kingdom<ref name=\"Lumiere\"/>\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $160 million<ref name=\"Mojo\">{{cite web |title=Inception (2010) |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt1375666/ |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=January 16, 2011}}</ref>\n| gross          = $829.9 million<ref name=\"Mojo\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Inception''''' is a 2010 <!--- Per [[WP:FILMLEAD]], do not add American-British or British-American: \"If the nationality is not singular, cover the different national interests later in the lead section.\"--->[[science fiction action film]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.warnerbros.com/movies/inception/|title=WarnerBros.com - Inception|website=[[Warner Bros]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/inception/|title=INCEPTION|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]}}</ref> written and directed by [[Christopher Nolan]], who also produced the film with his wife, [[Emma Thomas]]. The film stars [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] as a professional thief who [[corporate espionage|steals information]] by infiltrating the [[subconscious]] of his targets. He is offered a chance to have his criminal history erased as payment for the implantation of another person's idea into a target's subconscious.<ref name=\"synop\">{{cite web|url=http://screenrant.com/inception-plot-synopsis-deatails-mikee-58124/|title=Updated 'Inception' Synopsis Reveals More|website=Screen Rant|date=May 5, 2010|access-date=July 18, 2010|first=Mike|last=Eisenberg}}</ref> The [[ensemble cast]] includes [[Ken Watanabe]], [[Joseph Gordon-Levitt]], [[Marion Cotillard]], [[Ellen Page]], [[Tom Hardy]], [[Dileep Rao]], [[Cillian Murphy]], [[Tom Berenger]], and [[Michael Caine]].\n\nAfter the 2002 completion of ''[[Insomnia (2002 film)|Insomnia]]'', Nolan presented to [[Warner Bros.]] a written 80-page [[film treatment|treatment]] for a [[horror film]] envisioning \"dream stealers,\" based on [[lucid dreaming]].<ref name=\"Hiscock\" /> Deciding he needed more experience before tackling a production of this magnitude and complexity, Nolan retired the project and instead worked on 2005's ''[[Batman Begins]]'', 2006's ''[[The Prestige (film)|The Prestige]]'', and ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' in 2008.<ref name=\"Itzkoff\">{{Cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave|title=A Man and His Dream: Christopher Nolan and ''Inception''|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 30, 2010|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/30/a-man-and-his-dream-christopher-nolan-and-inception/|accessdate=July 1, 2010|quote=This is a film I first pitched to the studio probably nine years ago, and I wasn't really ready to finish it. I needed more experience in making a big movie.}}</ref> The treatment was revised over 6 months and was purchased by Warner in February 2009.<ref name=\"first\">{{Cite news|first=Michael|last=Fleming|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117999988|title=Nolan tackles ''Inception'' for WB|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=February 11, 2009|access-date=February 25, 2009}}</ref> ''Inception'' was filmed in six countries, beginning in Tokyo on June 19 and ending in Canada on November 22.<ref name=\"filming\">{{Cite news|date=December 6, 2009|title=Filming Locations \u2013 NolanFans |url=http://www.nolanfans.com/tag/filming-locations/|accessdate=March 23, 2012}}</ref> Its official budget was US$160&nbsp;million, split between [[Warner Bros]] and [[Legendary Pictures|Legendary]].<ref name=\"budget\">{{Cite news|date=July 15, 2010|last=Fritz|first=Ben|title=Movie projector: 'Inception' headed for No. 1, 'Sorcerer's Apprentice' to open in third|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2010/07/inception-sorcerers-box-office.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|quote=It's also one of the most expensive, at $160&nbsp;million, a cost that was split by Warner and Legendary Pictures. |access-date=July 27, 2010}}</ref> Nolan's reputation and success with ''The Dark Knight'' helped secure the film's US$100&nbsp;million in advertising expenditure.\n\n''Inception''{{'}}s premiere was held in [[London]] on July 8, 2010; it was released in both conventional and [[IMAX]] theaters beginning on July 16, 2010.<ref name=\"bomrelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2860&p=.htm|title=Weekend Briefing: 'Inception' Breaks In, 'Apprentice' Lacks Magic|first=Ray|last=Subers|website=Box Office Mojo|date=July 16, 2010|access-date=July 18, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=July 14, 2010|first=Jenny|last=Peters|title=Partying for a Cause at the \"Inception\" Premiere|url=http://www.fashionwiredaily.com/first_word/entertainment/article.weml?id=3264|work=Fashion Wire Daily|access-date=October 1, 2010}}</ref> ''Inception'' grossed over US$829&nbsp;million worldwide, becoming the [[2010 in film|fourth highest-grossing film of 2010]]. Considered one of the best films of the 2010s,<ref name=\"Metacritic 2010s\">{{cite web|date=November 18, 2019|first=Jason|last=Dietz|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-movies-of-the-decade-2010s|title=The Best Movies of the Decade (2010-19), According to Film Critics|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 26, 2020}}</ref> ''Inception'' received critical praise for its screenplay, direction, themes, visual effects, musical score, and ensemble cast.<ref name=\"Zeitchik\">{{Cite news|date=July 19, 2010|first=Steven|last=Zeitchik|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-inception-backlash-20100719,0,3544832.story|title='Inception' rides out critical backlash|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> It won four [[Academy Awards]] ([[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]], and [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]]) and was nominated for four more: [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]], [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction]], and [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]].\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- STOP!!! Do not add any unnecessary details to plot. -->\nDominick \"Dom\" Cobb and Arthur are \"extractors\": they perform [[corporate espionage]] using experimental military technology to infiltrate the [[Unconscious mind|subconscious]] of their targets and extract valuable information through a [[shared dreaming|shared]] [[Dream world (plot device)|dream world]]. Their latest target, Japanese businessman Saito, reveals that he arranged their mission himself to test Cobb for a seemingly impossible job: implanting an idea in a person's subconscious, or \"inception\". To break up the [[energy industry|energy]] [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] of ailing competitor Maurice Fischer, Saito wants Cobb to convince Fischer's son and heir, Robert, to dissolve his father's company. In return, Saito promises to use his influence once the job is done to clear Cobb's apparent criminal status, which prevents him from returning home to his children.\n\nThough Arthur believes the task is impossible, Cobb insists that it can be done. Cobb accepts the offer and assembles his team: Eames, a conman and identity forger; Yusuf, a chemist who concocts a powerful [[sedative]] for a stable \"[[false awakening|dream within a dream]]\" strategy; and Ariadne, an architecture student tasked with designing the [[labyrinth]] of the dream landscapes, recruited with the help of Cobb's father-in-law, Professor Stephen Miles. While dream-sharing with Cobb, Ariadne learns his subconscious houses an invasive projection of his late wife Mal.\n\nAfter Maurice dies in [[Sydney]], Robert Fischer accompanies the body on a ten-hour flight back to Los Angeles. The team (including Saito, who wants to verify their success) uses this as an opportunity to sedate and take Fischer into a shared dream. At each dream level, the person generating the dream stays behind to set up a \"[[Hypnic jerk|kick]]\" that will be used to awaken the other sleeping team members from the deeper dream level; to be successful, these kicks must occur simultaneously at each dream level, a fact complicated due to the nature of time, which flows much faster in each successive level. They use \"[[Non, je ne regrette rien]]\" as an auditory cue to help coordinate the kicks. The first level is Yusuf's dream of a rainy Los Angeles. \n\nThe team abducts Fischer, but they are attacked by armed projections from his subconscious, which has been specifically trained to defend against such intruders. The team takes Robert and a wounded Saito to a warehouse, where Cobb reveals that while dying in the dream would normally wake Saito up, the powerful sedatives needed to stabilize the multi-level dream will instead send a dying dreamer into \"[[Limbo#Cultural references|limbo]]\": a world of infinite subconscious from which escape is extremely difficult, if not impossible, and in which a dreamer risks forgetting they are in a dream. Despite these setbacks, the team continues with the mission.\n\nEames impersonates Robert's godfather, Peter Browning, to suggest Robert reconsider his father's will. Yusuf drives them around in a van as the rest are sedated into the second level, a hotel dreamed by Arthur. Cobb persuades Robert that he has been kidnapped by Browning, and that Cobb is his subconscious protector. Cobb persuades Robert to go down another level to explore Browning's subconscious (in reality, it is a ruse to enter Robert's subconscious). The third level is a fortified hospital on a snowy mountain dreamed by Eames. The team has to infiltrate it and hold off the guards as Saito takes Robert into the equivalent of his subconscious. Yusuf, under pursuit by Robert's projections in the first level, deliberately drives off a bridge, thus initiating his kick too soon. This causes an avalanche in Eames' level, and removes the gravity of Arthur's level, thus forcing Arthur to improvise a new kick synchronized with the van hitting the water. Mal's projection emerges in Eames' level and kills Robert; Cobb kills Mal, and Saito succumbs to his wounds. Cobb and Ariadne enter Limbo to rescue Robert and Saito, while Eames sets up a kick by rigging the hospital with explosives.\n\nCobb reveals to Ariadne that he and Mal went to limbo while experimenting with the dream-sharing technology. Sedated for five hours of real time, they spent fifty years in a dream constructing a world from their shared memories. When Mal refused to return to reality, Cobb used a rudimentary form of inception by reactivating her totem (an object that dreamers use to distinguish their dreams from reality), and reminding her subconscious that their world was not real. However, after waking up, the inception had taken root and Mal still believed that she was dreaming. In an attempt to \"wake up\" for real, she committed suicide and framed Cobb for her death to force him to do the same. Facing a murder charge, Cobb fled the U.S., leaving his children in the care of his father-in-law.\n\nThrough his confession, Cobb makes peace with his guilt over Mal's death. Ariadne kills Mal's projection and wakes Robert up with a kick. Revived at the fortified hospital, he enters a safe room to discover and accept the planted idea: a projection of his dying father telling him to be his own man. While Cobb remains in limbo to search for Saito, the other team members ride the synchronized kicks back to reality. Cobb eventually finds an aged Saito in limbo and reminds him of their agreement. The dreamers all awake on the plane and Saito makes a phone call.\n\nUpon arrival at Los Angeles Airport, Cobb passes the U.S. immigration checkpoint and Professor Miles accompanies him to his home. Using Mal's old totem\u2014a [[spinning top]] that spins indefinitely in a dream world but falls over in reality\u2014Cobb conducts a test to prove that he is indeed in the real world, but he does not observe its result and instead joins his children in the garden.\n<!-- DO NOT ADD ANY DETAIL ABOUT THE ENDING HERE. ADD IT TO THE \"ENDING\" SECTION BELOW -->\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:InceptionCastPremiereJuly10.jpg|thumb|The cast at a premiere for the film in July 2010: From left to right: Cillian Murphy, Marion Cotillard, Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Ellen Page, Ken Watanabe, Michael Caine, and Leonardo DiCaprio|alt=A man in a black suit, a woman in a pink dress, a man in a plaid suit, a woman in a black dress, a Japanese man in a black suit, and an old man in a blue suit clap their hands, while a man in a black suit stands. A microphone stand is in the foreground, and blue curtains are in the background.]]\n* [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] as Dom Cobb, a professional thief who specializes in [[con artist|conning]] secrets from his victims by infiltrating their dreams. DiCaprio was the first actor to be cast in the film.<ref name=\"Weintraub\" /> Both [[Brad Pitt]] and [[Will Smith]] were offered the role, according to ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/list-directors-43873 | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Kim | last=Masters | title=The A-List Directors | date=November 10, 2010}}</ref> Cobb's role is compared to \"the haunted widower in a Gothic romance\".<ref>Charles Burnetts, \"'Downwards is the only way forwards': 'Dream Space,' Parallel Time and Selfhood in Inception\", in: Jones, Matthew and Omrod, Joan, eds. ''Time Travel in Popular Media: Essays on Film, Television, Literature and Video Games''. [[Jefferson, North Carolina|Jefferson, N.C.]]: [[McFarland & Company|McFarland]], 2015. p. 234-246, p. 244.</ref>\n* [[Joseph Gordon-Levitt]] as Arthur, Cobb's partner who manages and researches the missions. Gordon-Levitt compared Arthur to the producer of Cobb's art, \"the one saying, 'Okay, you have your vision; now I'm going to figure out how to make all the nuts and bolts work so you can do your thing'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes 2010, p. 7.|publisher=}}</ref> The actor did all of his stunts but one scene and said the preparation \"was a challenge and it would have to be for it to look real\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.about.com/movies/Joseph-Gordon-Levitt-Inception.htm |title=Joseph Gordon-Levitt Inception Interview |date=July 15, 2010 |first=Rebecca |last=Murray |publisher=[[About.com]] |access-date=July 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002051742/http://video.about.com/movies/Joseph-Gordon-Levitt-Inception.htm |archivedate=October 2, 2011}}</ref> [[James Franco]] was in talks with Christopher Nolan to play Arthur, but was ultimately unavailable due to scheduling conflicts.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rappe|first=Elisabeth|title=CHRISTOPHER NOLAN TRADES JAMES FRANCO FOR JOSEPH GORDON-LEVITT IN 'INCEPTION'|date=April 24, 2009|publisher=[[MTV News]]|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2431985/christopher-nolan-trades-james-franco-for-joseph-gordon-levitt-in-inception/|accessdate=June 23, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Ellen Page]] as Ariadne, a [[graduate student]] of architecture who is recruited to construct the various dreamscapes, which are described as mazes. The name [[Ariadne]] alludes to a princess of [[Greek mythology|Greek myth]], daughter of [[Minos|King Minos]], who aided the hero [[Theseus]] by giving him a sword and a ball of string to help him navigate the labyrinth which was the prison of the [[Minotaur]]. Nolan said that Page was chosen for being a \"perfect combination of freshness and savvy and maturity beyond her years\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes 2010, p. 8.|publisher=}}</ref> Page said her character acts as a proxy to the audience, as \"she's just learning about these ideas and, in essence, assists the audience in learning about dream sharing\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/7868889/Inception-Ellen-Page-interview.html|title=Inception: Ellen Page interview|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK|first=Christine|last=Lennon|access-date=July 3, 2011|date=July 12, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Hardy]] as Eames, a sharp-tongued associate of Cobb. He is referred to as a [[fence (criminal)|fence]] but his specialty is forgery, more accurately [[identity theft]]. Eames uses his ability to [[impersonation|impersonate others]] inside the dream world in order to manipulate Fischer. Hardy described his character as \"an old, [[Graham Greene]]-type diplomat; sort of faded, shabby, grandeur \u2013 the old Shakespeare lovey mixed with somebody from [[United Kingdom Special Forces|Her Majesty's Special Forces]]\", who wears \"campy, old money\" costumes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ugo.com/movies/diving-into-your-own-mind |title=Inception's Tom Hardy Is The Forger, Darling |publisher=[[UGO]] |first=Matt |last=Patches |date=July 12, 2010 |access-date=July 3, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100905040047/http://www.ugo.com/movies/diving-into-your-own-mind |archivedate=September 5, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Ken Watanabe]] as Mr. Saito, a Japanese businessman who employs Cobb for the team's mission. Nolan wrote the role with Watanabe in mind, as he wanted to work with him again after ''[[Batman Begins]]''.<ref name=pn10/> ''Inception'' is Watanabe's first work in a contemporary setting where his primary language is English. Watanabe tried to emphasize a different characteristic of Saito in every dream level: \"First chapter in my castle, I pick up some hidden feelings of the cycle. It's magical, powerful and then the first dream. And back to the second chapter, in the old hotel, I pick up [being] sharp and more calm and smart and it's a little bit [of a] different process to make up the character of any movie\".<ref>{{Cite news|first=Alex |last=Billington |title=Interview: Japanese Actor Ken Watanabe \u2013 Saito in Inception|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=July 20, 2010|url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2010/interview-inceptions-saito-japanese-actor-ken-watanabe/|accessdate=July 3, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Dileep Rao]] as Yusuf. Rao describes Yusuf as \"an avant-garde pharmacologist, who is a resource for people, like Cobb, who want to do this work unsupervised, unregistered and unapproved of by anyone\". Co-producer Jordan Goldberg said the role of the chemist was \"particularly tough because you don't want him to seem like some kind of drug dealer\", and that Rao was cast for being \"funny, interesting and obviously smart\".<ref name=\"Production Notes 2010, p. 11\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes 2010, p. 11.|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Cillian Murphy]] as Robert Michael Fischer, the heir to a business empire and the team's target.<ref name=pn10>{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes 2010, p. 10.|publisher=}}</ref> Murphy said Fischer was portrayed as \"a petulant child who's in need of a lot of attention from his father, he has everything he could ever want materially, but he's deeply lacking emotionally\". The actor also researched the sons of [[Rupert Murdoch]], \"to add to that the idea of living in the shadow of someone so immensely powerful\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishcentral.com/IrishVoice/Hollywood-golden-boy-Cillian-Murphy-talks-about-Inception.html?page=2|title=Hollywood golden boy Cillian Murphy talks about 'Inception'|publisher=Irish Voice Reporter|first=Cahir|last=O'Doherty|date=July 15, 2010|access-date=July 3, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Berenger]] as Peter Browning, Robert Fischer's [[Godparent|godfather]] and fellow executive at the Fischers' company.<ref name=\"CinemaRewind\">{{Cite web|last=George|title=Inception Cast and Crew Updates|publisher=Cinema Rewind|date=July 23, 2009|url=http://www.cinemarewind.com/2009/07/inception-cast-and-crew-updates.html|accessdate=August 31, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801155642/http://www.cinemarewind.com/2009/07/inception-cast-and-crew-updates.html|archivedate=August 1, 2009}}</ref> Berenger said Browning acts as a \"surrogate father\" to Fischer, who calls the character \"Uncle Peter\", and emphasized that \"Browning has been with [Robert] his whole life and has probably spent more quality time with him than his own father\".<ref name=\"Production Notes 2010, p. 11\"/>\n* [[Marion Cotillard]] as Mal Cobb, Dom's deceased wife. She is a manifestation of Dom's guilt about the real cause of Mal's suicide. He is unable to control these projections of her, challenging his abilities as an extractor.<ref name=\"threecircle\" /> Nolan described Mal as \"the essence of the [[femme fatale]],\" and DiCaprio praised Cotillard's performance, saying that \"she can be strong and vulnerable and hopeful and heartbreaking all in the same moment, which was perfect for all the contradictions of her character\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes 2010, p. 9 and 10.|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Pete Postlethwaite]] as Maurice Fischer, Robert Fischer's father and the dying founder of a business empire.\n* [[Michael Caine]] as Professor Stephen Miles, Cobb's mentor and father-in-law,<ref name=\"Production Notes 2010, p. 11\" /> and Ariadne's college professor who recommends her to the team.<ref name=\"InContention\">{{Cite news|last=Tapley|first=Kristopher|title=Caine confirmed in small role in ''Inception'', Gordon-Levitt also joins the cast|publisher=InContention|date=April 24, 2009|url=http://incontention.com/?p=5843|accessdate=April 24, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Lukas Haas]] as Nash, an architect in Cobb's employment who betrays the team and is later replaced by Ariadne.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Boursaw|first=Jane|publisher=EveryJoe|title=Ellen Page on the set of ''Inception'' in Paris|date=August 26, 2009|url=http://everyjoe.com/entertainment/ellen-page-on-the-set-of-inception-in-paris/|accessdate=August 26, 2009|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120712215937/http://everyjoe.com/entertainment/ellen-page-on-the-set-of-inception-in-paris/|archive-date=July 12, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Talulah Riley]] as a woman whom Eames disguises himself as in a dream. Riley liked the role, despite it being minimal: \"I get to wear a nice dress, pick up men in bars, and shove them in elevators. It was good to do something adultish. Usually I play 15-year-old English schoolgirls.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/talulah-riley/|title=Talulah Riley|author=Martin, Michael|work=[[Interview Magazine]]|date=May 10, 2010|access-date=July 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n[[File:Emma Thomas & Christopher Nolan at WonderCon 2010 1.JPG|thumb|left|upright=1|Emma Thomas and Christopher Nolan answer questions about ''Inception''. The husband and wife team produced the film through their company [[Syncopy Films]]. Nolan also wrote and directed it.]]\nInitially, Nolan wrote an 80-page [[film treatment|treatment]] about dream-stealers.<ref name=\"Hiscock\" /> Originally, Nolan had envisioned ''Inception'' as a [[horror film]],<ref name=\"Hiscock\">{{Cite news|last=Hiscock|first=John|title=''Inception'': Christopher Nolan interview|work=Daily Telegraph |location=UK|date=July 1, 2010|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmmakersonfilm/7866677/Inception-Christopher-Nolan-interview.html|accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref> but eventually wrote it as a [[heist film]] even though he found that \"traditionally [they] are very deliberately superficial in emotional terms.\"<ref name=\"Boucher\">{{Cite news|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|title=''Inception'' breaks into dreams|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 4, 2010|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-ca-inception4-2010apr04,0,6869939.story|accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref> Upon revisiting his script, he decided that basing it in that genre did not work because the story \"relies so heavily on the idea of the interior state, the idea of dream and [[memory]]. I realized I needed to raise the emotional stakes.\"<ref name=\"Boucher\" /> \n\nNolan worked on the script for nine to ten years.<ref name=\"Weintraub\" /> When he first started thinking about making the film, Nolan was influenced by \"that era of movies where you had ''[[The Matrix]]'' (1999), you had ''[[Dark City (1998 film)|Dark City]]'' (1998), you had ''[[The Thirteenth Floor]]'' (1999) and, to a certain extent, you had ''[[Memento (film)|Memento]]'' (2000), too. They were based in the principles that the world around you might not be real.\"<ref name=\"Boucher\" /><ref>{{Cite web|date=July 16, 2010|first=Sheila|last=Marikar|title=Inside 'Inception': Could Christopher Nolan's Dream World Exist in Real Life? Dream Experts Say 'Inception's' Conception of the Subconscious Isn't Far From Science|publisher=[[ABC News]]|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/inside-inception-christopher-nolans-dream-world-exist-real/story?id=11174201|accessdate=September 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nNolan first pitched the film to Warner Bros. in 2001, but decided that he needed more experience making large-scale films, and embarked on ''[[Batman Begins]]'' and ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]''.<ref name=\"Itzkoff\"/> He soon realized that a film like ''Inception'' needed a large budget because \"as soon as you're talking about dreams, the potential of the human mind is infinite. And so the scale of the film has to feel infinite. It has to feel like you could go anywhere by the end of the film. And it has to work on a massive scale.\"<ref name=\"Itzkoff\" /> After making ''The Dark Knight'', Nolan decided to make ''Inception'' and spent six months completing the script.<ref name=\"Itzkoff\" /> Nolan said that the key to completing the script was wondering what would happen if several people shared the same dream. \"Once you remove the privacy, you've created an infinite number of alternative universes in which people can meaningfully interact, with validity, with weight, with dramatic consequences.\"<ref name=\"Itzkoff2\">{{Cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave|title=The Man Behind the Dreamscape|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 30, 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/04/movies/04inception.html |access-date=July 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nNolan had been trying to work with Leonardo DiCaprio for years and met him several times, but was unable to recruit him for any of his films until ''Inception''.<ref name=\"threecircle\">{{Cite news|first=Borys |last=Kit |title=Three circle Nolan's 'Inception' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=April 1, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406021957/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i7288557915e143d0665fd7eb397d74e8 |archivedate=April 6, 2009 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i7288557915e143d0665fd7eb397d74e8 |access-date=April 2, 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> DiCaprio finally agreed because he was \"intrigued by this concept\u2014this dream-heist notion and how this character's going to unlock his dreamworld and ultimately affect his real life.\"<ref name=\"Jolin\">{{Cite news|last=Jolin|first=Dan|title=Crime of the Century|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=July 2010|pages=93\u201394}}</ref> He read the script and found it to be \"very well written, comprehensive but you really had to have Chris in person, to try to articulate some of the things that have been swirling around his head for the last eight years.\"<ref name=\"Itzkoff\" /> DiCaprio and Nolan spent months talking about the screenplay. Nolan took a long time re-writing the script in order \"to make sure that the emotional journey of his [Di Caprio's] character was the driving force of the movie.\"<ref name=\"Weintraub\" /> On February 11, 2009, it was announced that [[Warner Bros.]] purchased ''Inception'', a [[spec script]] written by Nolan.<ref name=\"first\" />\n\n===Locations and sets {{anchor|Filming}}===\n[[Principal photography]] began in [[Tokyo]] on June 19, 2009, with the scene in which Saito first hires Cobb during a helicopter flight over the city.<ref name=\"Hiscock\" /><ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes7\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 13.|publisher=}}</ref>\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Inception.JPG|thumb|left|upright=1|The scene]] -->\n\nThe production moved to the United Kingdom and shot in a converted [[airship hangar]] in [[Cardington, Bedfordshire|Cardington]], Bedfordshire, north of London.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes8\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 14.|publisher=}}</ref> There, the hotel bar set which tilted 30 degrees was built.<ref name=\"Heuring\">{{Cite news|last=Heuring|first=David|title=Dream Thieves|work=[[American Cinematographer]]|publisher=American Society of Cinematographers|date=July 2010|page=29|url=http://www.theasc.com/ac_magazine/July2010/Inception/page1.php|accessdate=September 22, 2010}}</ref> A hotel corridor was also constructed by [[Guy Hendrix Dyas]], the production designer, [[Chris Corbould]], the special effects supervisor, and [[Wally Pfister]], the director of photography; it rotated a full 360&nbsp;degrees to create the effect of alternate directions of [[gravity]] for scenes set during the second level of dreaming, where dream-sector physics become chaotic. The idea was inspired by a technique used in [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''[[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]]'' (1968). Nolan said, \"I was interested in taking those ideas, techniques, and philosophies and applying them to an action scenario\".<ref name=\"Heuring2\">Heuring, July 2010, p. 32.</ref> The filmmakers originally planned to make the hallway only 40&nbsp;ft (12&nbsp;m) long, but as the action sequence became more elaborate, the hallway's length was increased to 100&nbsp;ft (30&nbsp;m). The corridor was suspended along eight large concentric rings that were spaced equidistantly outside its walls and powered by two massive electric motors.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes8\" /> \n\nJoseph Gordon-Levitt, who plays Arthur, spent several weeks learning to fight in a corridor that spun like \"a giant [[hamster wheel]]\".<ref name=\"Boucher\" /> Nolan said of the device, \"It was like some incredible torture device; we thrashed Joseph for weeks, but in the end we looked at the footage, and it looks unlike anything any of us has seen before. The rhythm of it is unique, and when you watch it, even if you know how it was done, it confuses your perceptions. It's unsettling in a wonderful way\".<ref name=\"Boucher\" /> Gordon-Levitt remembered, \"it was six-day weeks of just, like, coming home at night battered ... The light fixtures on the ceiling are coming around on the floor, and you have to choose the right time to cross through them, and if you don't, you're going to fall.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gordinier|first=Jeff|title=Joseph Gordon-Levitt Comes of Age|work=[[Details (magazine)|Details]]|date=August 2010|url=http://www.details.com/celebrities-entertainment/cover-stars/201008/inception-actor-joseph-gordon-levitt?currentPage=1|page=4|accessdate=July 27, 2010}}</ref> On July 15, 2009, filming took place at [[University College London]] for the sequences occurring inside a Paris college of architecture in the story,<ref name=\"Hiscock\" /> including the library, Flaxman Gallery and Gustav Tuck Theatre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-film-locations.com/Inception-2010|title=Where was 'Inception' filmed? \u2013 British Film Locations|work=British Film Locations|access-date=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFilming moved to France, where they shot Cobb entering the college of architecture (the place used for the entrance was the [[Mus\u00e9e Galliera]]) and the pivotal scenes between Ariadne and Cobb, in a [[bistro]] (a fictional one set up at the corner of Rue C\u00e9sar Franck and Rue Bouchut), and lastly on the [[Pont de Bir-Hakeim|Bir-Hakeim bridge]].<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes9\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 17.|publisher=}}</ref> For the explosion that takes place during the bistro scene, local authorities would not allow the use of real explosives. High-pressure [[nitrogen]] was used to create the effect of a series of explosions. Pfister used six high-speed cameras to capture the sequence from different angles and make sure that they got the shot. The visual effects department enhanced the sequence, adding more destruction and flying debris. For the \"Paris folding\" sequence and when Ariadne \"creates\" the bridges, [[green screen]] and [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] were used on location.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes9\" />\n\n[[Tangier]], Morocco, doubled as [[Mombasa]], where Cobb hires Eames and Yusuf. A foot chase was shot in the streets and alleyways of the historic [[medina quarter]].<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes10\">The historic medina is south west of the cited \"[[Grand Socco|Grand Souk]]\", which is no longer a market place, but a busy transportation junction. [http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf Production Notes, 2010, p. 18.]</ref> To capture this sequence, Pfister employed a mix of [[hand-held camera]] and [[steadicam]] work.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes11\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 19.|publisher=}}</ref> Tangier was also used as the setting for filming an important riot scene during the initial foray into Saito's mind.\n\nFilming moved to the [[Los Angeles]] area, where some sets were built on a Warner Bros. [[sound stage]], including the interior rooms of Saito's Japanese castle (the exterior was done on a small set built in [[Malibu Beach]]). The dining room was inspired by the historic [[Nijo Castle]], built around 1603. These sets were inspired by a mix of [[Japanese architecture]] and Western influences.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes11\" /> \n\nThe production staged a multi-vehicle [[car chase]] on the streets of [[downtown Los Angeles]], which involved a freight train crashing down the middle of a street.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes12\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 20.|publisher=}}</ref> To do this, the filmmakers configured a train engine on the chassis of a tractor trailer. The replica was made from [[fiberglass]] molds taken from authentic train parts and matched in terms of color and design.<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes13\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 21.|publisher=}}</ref> Also, the car chase was supposed to be set in the midst of a downpour, but the L.A. weather stayed typically sunny. The filmmakers set up elaborate effects (e.g., rooftop [[water cannon]]s) to give the audience the impression that the weather was overcast and soggy. L.A. was also the site of the climactic scene where a [[Ford E-Series|Ford Econoline]] van runs off the [[Commodore Schuyler F. Heim Bridge|Schuyler Heim Bridge]] in slow motion.<ref name=\"Ditzian\">{{Cite news|last=Ditzian|first=Eric|title=''Inception'' Stars Reveal Secrets Behind Epic Van Scene|publisher=MTV |date=July 14, 2010|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1643645/20100714/story.jhtml|accessdate=July 22, 2010}}</ref> This sequence was filmed on and off for months, with the van being shot out of a cannon, according to actor Dileep Rao. Capturing the actors suspended within the van in slow motion took a whole day to film. \n\nOnce the van landed in the water, the challenge for the actors was to avoid panic. \"And when they ask you to act, it's a bit of an ask,\" explained Cillian Murphy.<ref name=\"Ditzian\" /> The actors had to be underwater for four to five minutes while drawing air from [[Diving cylinder|scuba tanks]]; underwater [[buddy breathing]] is shown in this sequence.<ref name=\"Ditzian\" /> \n\nCobb's house was in Pasadena. The hotel lobby was filmed at the CAA building in Century City. 'Limbo' was made on location in Los Angeles and [[Morocco]], with the beach scene filmed at [[Palos Verdes]] beach with CGI buildings. N Hope St. in Los Angeles was the primary filming location for 'limbo,' with green screen and CGI being used to create the dream landscape.\n\nThe final phase of principal photography took place in [[Alberta]] in late November 2009. The location manager discovered a temporarily closed ski resort, [[Fortress Mountain Resort|Fortress Mountain]].<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes14\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 22.|publisher=}}</ref> An elaborate set was assembled near the top station of the Canadian [[chairlift]], taking three months to build.<ref name=\"Jolin2\">Jolin, July 2010, pp. 93.</ref> The production had to wait for a huge snowstorm, which eventually arrived.<ref name=\"Hiscock\" /> The ski-chase sequence was inspired by Nolan's favorite [[James Bond]] film, ''[[On Her Majesty's Secret Service (film)|On Her Majesty's Secret Service]]'' (1969): \"What I liked about it that we've tried to emulate in this film is there's a tremendous balance in that movie of action and scale and romanticism and tragedy and emotion.\"<ref name=\"Jolin3\">Jolin, July 2010, pp. 91.</ref>\n\n===Cinematography===\nThe film was shot primarily in the [[anamorphic format]] on [[35mm movie film|35&nbsp;mm film]], with key sequences filmed on [[70 mm film|65&nbsp;mm]], and aerial sequences in [[VistaVision]]. Nolan did not shoot any footage with [[IMAX]] cameras as he had with ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]''. \"We didn't feel that we were going to be able to shoot in IMAX because of the size of the cameras because this film given that it deals with a potentially surreal area, the nature of dreams and so forth, I wanted it to be as realistic as possible. Not be bound by the scale of those IMAX cameras, even though I love the format dearly\".<ref name=\"Weintraub\" /> In addition Nolan and Pfister tested using [[Showscan]] and [[List of film formats|Super Dimension 70]] as potential large format [[high frame rate]] camera systems to use for the film, but ultimately decided against either format.<ref name=\"Heuring\" /> Sequences in slow motion were filmed on a Photo-Sonics 35mm camera at speeds of up to 1000 frames per second. Wally Pfister tested shooting some of these sequences using a high speed [[Digital cinematography|digital camera]], but found the format to be too unreliable due to technical glitches. \"Out of six times that we shot on the digital format, we only had one useable piece and it didn't end up in the film. Out of the six times we shot with the Photo-Sonics camera and 35mm running through it, every single shot was in the movie.\"<ref name=\"Kodak\">{{Cite news|title=From The Dark Knight to Inception, Wally Pfister, ASC refuses to compromise |publisher=Kodak|url=http://motion.kodak.com/motion/Products/Customer_Testimonials/Wally_Pfister/index.htm#ixzz2Ti47T2NZ|accessdate=May 19, 2013}}</ref> Nolan also chose not to shoot any of the film in [[3D film|3D]] as he prefers shooting on film<ref name=\"Weintraub\" /> using [[prime lens]]es, which is not possible with 3D cameras.<ref name=\"Playlist\">{{Cite news|title=Christopher Nolan Tested 3D Conversion For 'Inception,' Might Use Process For 'Batman 3'|work=The Playlist|date=June 14, 2010|url=http://theplaylist.blogspot.com/2010/06/christopher-nolan-tested-3d-conversion.html|accessdate=January 22, 2011}}</ref> Nolan has also criticized the dim image that 3D projection produces, and disputes that traditional film does not allow realistic [[depth perception]], saying \"I think it's a misnomer to call it 3D versus 2D. The whole point of cinematic imagery is it's three dimensional... You know 95% of our [[depth perception|depth cues]] come from [[Ambient occlusion|occlusion]], resolution, color and so forth, so the idea of calling a 2D movie a '2D movie' is a little misleading.\"<ref name=latimes-hcff>{{cite news|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2010/06/13/christopher-nolan-inception-3d-dark-knight-hollywood/|title=Christopher Nolan's dim view of a Hollywood craze: 'I'm not a huge fan of 3-D'|date=June 13, 2010|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=January 22, 2011}}</ref> Nolan did test [[2D to 3D conversion|converting]] ''Inception'' into 3D in post-production but decided that, while it was possible, he lacked the time to complete the conversion to a standard he was happy with.<ref name=\"Hiscock\"/><ref name=\"latimes-hcff\" /> In February 2011 [[Jonathan Liebesman]] suggested that Warner Bros were attempting a 3D conversion for [[Blu-ray]] release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/inception-being-converted-to-3d-blu-ray|title=''Inception'' being converted to 3D Blu-ray?|first=Brian|last=Gallagher|date=February 24, 2011|access-date=February 27, 2011|publisher=movieweb.com}}</ref>\n\nWally Pfister gave each location and dream level a distinctive look to aid the audience's recognition of the narrative's location during the heavily crosscut portion of the film: the mountain fortress appears sterile and cool, the hotel hallways have warm hues, and the scenes in the van are more neutral.<ref name=\"Heuring3\">Heuring, July 2010, pp. 35\u201336.</ref>\n\nNolan has said that the film \"deals with levels of reality, and perceptions of reality which is something I'm very interested in. It's an action film set in a contemporary world, but with a slight science-fiction bent to it,\" while also describing it as \"very much an ensemble film structured somewhat as a heist movie. It's an action adventure that spans the globe\".<ref>{{Cite news|title=''Inception''|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Visual effects===\nFor dream sequences in ''Inception'', Nolan used little [[computer-generated imagery]], preferring [[practical effect]]s whenever possible. Nolan said, \"It's always very important to me to do as much as possible in-camera, and then, if necessary, computer graphics are very useful to build on or enhance what you have achieved physically.\"<ref name=\"InceptionProdNotes6\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes, 2010, p. 12.|publisher=}}</ref> To this end, visual effects supervisor [[Paul Franklin (visual effects supervisor)|Paul Franklin]] built a [[Miniature effect|miniature]] of the mountain fortress set and then blew it up for the film. For the fight scene that takes place in zero gravity, he used CG-based effects to \"subtly bend elements like physics, space and time.\"<ref name=\"trussell\">{{Cite news|last=Russell|first=Terrence|title=How ''Inception''{{'}}s Astonishing Visuals Came to Life|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|date=July 20, 2010|url=https://www.wired.com/underwire/2010/07/inception-visual-effects|accessdate=July 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe most challenging effect was the \"limbo\" city level at the end of the film, because it continually developed during production. Franklin had artists build concepts while Nolan expressed his ideal vision: \"Something glacial, with clear modernist architecture, but with chunks of it breaking off into the sea like icebergs\".<ref name=\"trussell\" /> Franklin and his team ended up with \"something that looked like an iceberg version of [[Gotham City]] with water running through it.\"<ref name=\"trussell\" /> They created a basic model of a glacier and then designers created a program that added elements like roads, intersections and ravines until they had a complex, yet organic-looking, cityscape. For the Paris-folding sequence, Franklin had artists producing concept sketches and then they created rough computer animations to give them an idea of what the sequence looked like while in motion. Later during principal photography, Nolan was able to direct Leonardo DiCaprio and Ellen Page based on this rough computer animation that Franklin had created. ''Inception'' had nearly 500 visual effects shots (in comparison, ''[[Batman Begins]]'' had approximately 620), which is relatively few in comparison to contemporary effects-heavy films, which can have as many as 2,000 visual effects shots.<ref name=\"trussell\" />\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|Inception: Music from the Motion Picture}}\n\nThe score for ''Inception'' was written by [[Hans Zimmer]],<ref name=\"CinemaRewind\" /> who described his work as \"a very electronic,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screenrant.com/inception-score-hans-zimmers-mikee-65200 |title=Hans Zimmer's 'Inception' Score Will Release On July 13th |publisher=ScreenRant.com |access-date=July 1, 2010 |date=June 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625130549/http://screenrant.com/inception-score-hans-zimmers-mikee-65200/ |archivedate=June 25, 2010}}</ref> dense score\",<ref name=\"Cassidy\"/> filled with \"nostalgia and sadness\" to match Cobb's feelings throughout the film.<ref name=\"Martens\"/> The music was written simultaneously to filming,<ref name=\"Cassidy\">{{cite news |last=Cassidy |first=Kevin |title=Q&A: Composer Hans Zimmer |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=July 13, 2010 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/qampa-composer-hans-zimmer-25455|accessdate=July 14, 2010}}</ref> and features a guitar sound reminiscent of [[Ennio Morricone]], played by [[Johnny Marr]], former guitarist of [[The Smiths]].\n[[\u00c9dith Piaf]]'s \"[[Non, je ne regrette rien]]\" (\"No, I Regret Nothing\") appears throughout the film, used to accurately time the dreams, and Zimmer reworked pieces of the song into cues of the score.<ref name=\"Martens\">{{cite news |last=Martens |first=Todd |title=Hans Zimmer and Johnny Marr talk about the sad romance of 'Inception' |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 20, 2010 |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/herocomplex/2010/07/inception-christopher-nolan-the-smiths-johnny-marr-hans-zimmer-and-johnny-marr-on-the-sound-of-inception-its-about-sadness.html |access-date=July 20, 2010}}</ref>\n[[Inception: Music from the Motion Picture|A soundtrack album]] was released on July 11, 2010 by [[Reprise Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inceptionscore.com/|title=Inception: Music from the Motion Picture official website|publisher=Warner Bros.|access-date=July 3, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616131408/http://www.inceptionscore.com/|archive-date=June 16, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The majority of the score was also included in high resolution [[5.1 surround sound]] on the second disc of the 2 disc Blu-ray release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Inception-Blu-ray/14492/#Review|title=Inception Blu-ray review from Blu-ray.com|access-date=August 8, 2012}}</ref> Hans Zimmer's music was nominated for an Academy Award in the [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] category in 2011, losing to [[Trent Reznor]] and [[Atticus Ross]] of ''[[The Social Network]]''.<ref name=oscars/>\n\n==Themes==\n\n===Reality and dreams===\n[[File:Impossible staircase.svg|right|thumb|[[Penrose stairs]] are incorporated into the film as an example of the [[impossible object]]s that can be created in [[lucid dream]] worlds.|alt=A staircase in a square format. The stairs make four 90-degree turns in each corner, so they are in the format of a continuous loop.]]\nIn ''Inception'', Nolan wanted to explore \"the idea of people sharing a dream space...That gives you the ability to access somebody's [[unconscious mind]]. What would that be used and abused for?\"<ref name=\"Weintraub\">{{Cite news|last=Weintraub |first=Steve |title=Christopher Nolan and Emma Thomas Interview |publisher=Collider.com |date=March 25, 2010 |url=http://www.collider.com/2010/03/25/director-christopher-nolan-and-producer-emma-thomas-interview-inception-they-talk-3d-what-kind-of-cameras-they-used-pre-viz-wb-and-a-lot-more/ |accessdate=April 6, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327204348/http://www.collider.com/2010/03/25/director-christopher-nolan-and-producer-emma-thomas-interview-inception-they-talk-3d-what-kind-of-cameras-they-used-pre-viz-wb-and-a-lot-more/ |archivedate=March 27, 2010  }}</ref> The majority of the film's plot takes place in these interconnected dream worlds. This structure creates a framework where actions in the real or dream worlds ripple across others. The dream is always in a state of production, and shifts across the levels as the characters navigate it.<ref name='Paul'>Paul, I. A. [http://sensesofcinema.com/2010/feature-articles/desiring-machines-in-american-cinema-what-inception-tells-us-about-our-experience-of-reality-and-film/ Desiring-Machines in American Cinema: What Inception tells us about our experience of reality and film] ''Senses of Cinema'', Issue 56. Retrieved October 4, 2011</ref> By contrast, the world of ''[[The Matrix]]'' (1999) is an authoritarian, computer-controlled one, alluding to theories of social control developed by thinkers [[Michel Foucault]] and [[Jean Baudrillard]]. However, according to one interpretation Nolan's world has more in common with the works of [[Gilles Deleuze]] and [[F\u00e9lix Guattari]].<ref name='Paul'/>\n\n[[David Denby (film critic)|David Denby]] in ''[[The New Yorker]]'' compared Nolan's cinematic treatment of dreams to [[Luis Bu\u00f1uel]]'s in ''[[Belle de Jour (film)|Belle de Jour]]'' (1967) and ''[[The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie]]'' (1972).<ref name=\"Denby\" /> He criticized Nolan's \"literal-minded\" action level sequencing compared to Bu\u00f1uel, who \"silently pushed us into reveries and left us alone to enjoy our wonderment, but Nolan is working on so many levels of representation at once that he has to lay in pages of dialogue just to explain what's going on.\" The latter captures \"the peculiar malign intensity of actual dreams.\"<ref name=\"Denby\"/>\n\n[[Deirdre Barrett]], a dream researcher at [[Harvard University]], said that Nolan did not get every detail accurate regarding dreams, but their illogical, rambling, disjointed plots would not make for a great thriller anyway. However, \"he did get many aspects right,\" she said, citing the scene in which a sleeping Cobb is shoved into a full bath, and in the dream world water gushes into the windows of the building, waking him up. \"That's very much how real stimuli get incorporated, and you very often wake up right after that intrusion\".<ref name=\"Breznican\">{{Cite news|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|title=With ''Inception'', Chris Nolan's head games continue|work=[[USA Today]]|date=July 15, 2010|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-07-15-inception15_CV_N.htm|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nNolan himself said, \"I tried to work that idea of manipulation and management of a [[Lucid dream|conscious dream]] being a skill that these people have. Really the script is based on those common, very basic experiences and concepts, and where can those take you? And the only outlandish idea that the film presents, really, is the existence of a technology that allows you to enter and share the same dream as someone else.\"<ref name=\"Boucher\" />\n\n=== Dreams and cinema ===\nOthers have argued that the film is itself a [[oneiric (film theory)|metaphor for filmmaking]], and that the filmgoing experience itself, images flashing before one's eyes in a darkened room, is akin to a dream. Writing in ''Wired'', Jonah Lehrer supported this interpretation and presented neurological evidence that brain activity is strikingly similar during film-watching and sleeping. In both, the [[visual cortex]] is highly active and the [[prefrontal cortex]], which deals with logic, deliberate analysis, and self-awareness, is quiet.<ref name='Lehrer'>[[Jonah Lehrer|Lehrer, J.]] [https://www.wired.com/wiredscience/2010/07/the-neuroscience-of-inception/ The Neuroscience of Inception], ''Wired'', July 26, 2010. Retrieved October 8, 2011.</ref> Paul argued that the experience of going to a picturehouse is itself an exercise in shared dreaming, particularly when viewing ''Inception'': the film's sharp cutting between scenes forces the viewer to create larger narrative arcs to stitch the pieces together. This demand of production parallel to consumption of the images, on the part of the audience is analogous to dreaming itself. As in the film's story, in a cinema one enters into the space of another's dream, in this case Nolan's, as with any work of art, one's reading of it is ultimately influenced by one's own subjective desires and subconscious.<ref name='Paul'/> At Bir-Hakeim bridge in Paris, Ariadne creates an illusion of infinity by adding [[Infinity mirror|facing mirrors]] underneath its struts, Stephanie Dreyfus in ''la Croix'' asked \"Is this not a strong, beautiful metaphor for the cinema and its power of illusion?\"<ref>Dreyfus, St\u00e9phanie [http://www.la-croix.com/Culture-Loisirs/Culture/Actualite/Inception-allegorie-onirique-sur-l-illusion-cinematographique-_NG_-2010-07-20-554535 \"Inception\", all\u00e9gorie onirique sur l'illusion cin\u00e9matographique] ''[[La Croix]]'', July 20, 2010. Retrieved January 3, 2012</ref>\n\n==Cinematic technique==\n\n===Genre===\nNolan combined elements from several different film genres into the film, notably science fiction, [[heist film]], and [[film noir]].\n[[Marion Cotillard]] plays \"Mal\" Cobb, Dom Cobb's projection of his guilt over his deceased wife's suicide. As the film's main antagonist, she is a frequent, malevolent presence in his dreams. Dom is unable to control these projections of her, challenging his abilities as an extractor.<ref name=\"threecircle\" /> Nolan described Mal as \"the essence of the femme fatale\",<ref name=\"Production Notes 2010, p. 9\">{{cite web|url=http://wwws.warnerbros.co.uk/inception/mainsite/pdf/INCEPTION_PK_Notes__Bios_6-18.pdf|title=Production Notes 2010, p. 9|publisher=}}</ref> the key ''noir'' reference in the film. As a \"classic femme fatale\" her relationship with Cobb is in his mind, a manifestation of Cobb's own neurosis and fear of how little he knows about the woman he loves.<ref name=\"wired-jan11\"/> DiCaprio praised Cotillard's performance saying that \"she can be strong and vulnerable and hopeful and heartbreaking all in the same moment, which was perfect for all the contradictions of her character\".<ref name=pn10/>\n\nNolan began with the structure of a heist movie, since [[Exposition (literary technique)|exposition]] is an essential element of that genre, though adapted it to have a greater emotional narrative suited to the world of dreams and subconscious.<ref name=\"wired-jan11\"/> Or, as Denby surmised, \"the outer shell of the story is an elaborate caper\".<ref name=\"Denby\"/> [[Kristin Thompson]] argued that exposition was a major formal device in the film. While a traditional heist movie has a heavy dose of exposition at the beginning as the team assembles and the leader explains the plan, in ''Inception'' this becomes nearly continuous as the group progresses through the various levels of dreaming.<ref name='Bordwell2'>[http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2010/08/12/revisiting-inception/ Revisiting INCEPTION] www.davidbordwell.net, August 12, 2010. Retrieved October 6, 2011.</ref> Three quarters of the film, until the van begins to fall from the bridge, are devoted to explaining its plot. In this way, exposition takes precedence over characterization. The characters' relationships are created by their respective skills and roles. Ariadne, like [[Ariadne|her ancient namesake]], creates the maze and guides the others through it, but also helps Cobb navigate his own subconscious, and as the sole student of dream sharing, helps the audience understand the concept of the plot.<ref name='Bordwell1'>[http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2010/08/06/inception-or-dream-a-little-dream-within-a-dream-with-me/ INCEPTION; or, Dream a Little Dream within a Dream with Me] www.davidbordwell.net. August 6, 2010. Retrieved October 6, 2011</ref>\n\nNolan drew inspiration from the works of [[Jorge Luis Borges]]<ref name=\"Hiscock\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/article/836236--howell-relax-and-enjoy-the-ride-inception-director-says|title=Howell: Relax and enjoy the ride, Inception director says|first=Peter|last=Howell|date=July 15, 2010|work=Toronto Star |accessdate=September 4, 2010}}</ref> and ''[[Blade Runner]]'' (1982) by [[Ridley Scott]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Inception par Christopher Nolan: Interview, r\u00e9f\u00e9rences, indices..|publisher=Excessif.com|url=http://www.excessif.com/cinema/actu-cinema/dossiers/inception-par-christopher-nolan-interview-references-indices-5926972-760.html|accessdate=January 4, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717005841/http://www.excessif.com/cinema/actu-cinema/dossiers/inception-par-christopher-nolan-interview-references-indices-5926972-760.html|archivedate=July 17, 2010}} ([https://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.excessif.com%2Fcinema%2Factu-cinema%2Fdossiers%2Finception-par-christopher-nolan-interview-references-indices-5926972-760.html&sl=fr&tl=en&hl= Translation]) {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n===Ending===\nThe film cuts to the [[closing credits]] from a shot of the top apparently starting to show an ever so faint wobble, inviting speculation about whether the final sequence was reality or another dream. Nolan confirmed that the ambiguity was deliberate,<ref name=\"wired-jan11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/11/pl_inception_nolan/all/|title=Inception's director discusses the film's ending and creation|last=Capps|first=Robers|date=December 8, 2010|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=January 24, 2011}}</ref> saying, \"I've been asked the question more times than I've ever been asked any other question about any other film I've made... What's funny to me is that people really do expect me to answer it.\"<ref name=\"insidemovies\">{{cite web|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2010/11/30/christopher-nolan-batman-inception/|title=Christopher Nolan on his 'last' Batman movie, an 'Inception' videogame, and that spinning top|last=Jensen|first=Jeff|date=November 30, 2010|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=January 6, 2011}}</ref> The film's script concludes with \"Behind him, on the table, the spinning top is STILL SPINNING. And we \u2013 FADE OUT\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Inception \u2013 The Shooting Script|author=Christopher Nolan|page=218|isbn=978-1-60887-015-8|publisher=Insight Editions}}</ref> Nolan said, \"I put that cut there at the end, imposing an ambiguity from outside the film. That always felt the right ending to me \u2014 it always felt like the appropriate 'kick' to me... The real point of the scene \u2014 and this is what I tell people \u2014 is that Cobb isn't looking at the top. He's looking at his kids. He's left it behind. That's the emotional significance of the thing.\"<ref name=\"insidemovies\"/> Also, [[Michael Caine]] explained his interpretation of the ending, saying, \"If I'm there it's real, because I'm never in the dream. I'm the guy who invented the dream.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screenrant.com/michael-caine-inception-ending-batman-3-benm-80670 |title=Michael Caine Says 'Inception' Ending Was No Dream |publisher=ScreenRant.com |last=Moore |first=Ben |date=September 10, 2010 |accessdate=June 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617034431/http://screenrant.com/michael-caine-inception-ending-batman-3-benm-80670/ |archivedate=June 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSome viewers have noted Cobb wears his wedding ring only during dream scenes. From this, they have concluded that Cobb is not dreaming in the final scene because he is not wearing the ring. However, this theory has been disputed.<ref>De Benedetti, Luca. \"[http://felixonline.co.uk/articles/2013-1-18-inception-the-theory-of-the-ring/ Inception: The Theory of the Ring.]\" [[Felix (newspaper)|Felix Online]]. N.p., January 12, 2013. Web. July 12, 2014.</ref>\n\n[[Mark Fisher (theorist)|Mark Fisher]] argued that \"a century of cultural theory\" cautions against accepting the [[authorial intent|author's interpretation]] as anything more than a supplementary text, and this all the more so given the theme of the instability of any one master position in Nolan's films. Therein the manipulator is often the one who ends up manipulated, and Cobb's \"not caring\" about whether or not his world is real may be the price of his happiness and release.<ref>Fisher, Mark \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.1525/fq.2011.64.3.37 The Lost Unconscious: Delusions and Dreams in ''Inception'']\", ''[[Film Quarterly]]'', Vol. 64, No. 3 (Spring 2011), pp. 37\u201345 University of California Press.</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n===Marketing===\nWarner Bros. spent US$100&nbsp;million marketing the film. Although ''Inception'' was not part of an existing franchise, Sue Kroll, president of Warner's worldwide marketing, said the company believed it could gain awareness due to the strength of \"Christopher Nolan as a brand\". Kroll declared that \"We don't have the brand equity that usually drives a big summer opening, but we have a great cast and a fresh idea from a filmmaker with a track record of making incredible movies. If you can't make those elements work, it's a sad day.\"<ref name=\"Fritz2\">{{Cite news|last=Fritz|first=Ben|title=Warner gambles on an unproven commodity|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=July 7, 2010|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-ct-inception-20100713,0,3119222.story|accessdate=July 13, 2010}}</ref> The studio also tried to maintain a campaign of secrecy\u2014as reported by the Senior VP of Interactive Marketing, Michael Tritter, \"You have this movie which is going to have a pretty big built in fanbase... but you also have a movie that you are trying to keep very secret. Chris [Nolan] really likes people to see his movies in a theater and not see it all beforehand so everything that you do to market that\u2014at least early on\u2014is with an eye to feeding the interest to fans.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcrw.com/etc/programs/tb/tb100816finding_salt_marketi|title=Finding 'Salt;' Marketing 'Inception'|publisher=[[KCRW]]|date=June 18, 2010|accessdate=July 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nA [[viral marketing]] campaign was employed for the film. After the revelation of the first teaser trailer, in August 2009, the film's official website featured only an animation of Cobb's spinning top. In December, the top toppled over and the website opened the online game ''Mind Crime'', which upon completion revealed ''Inception''{{'}}s poster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/first-poster-from-christopher-nolans-inception-starring-leonardo-dicaprio/12637/|title=First Poster from Christopher Nolan's INCEPTION Starring Leonardo DiCaprio|publisher=Collider.com|date=December 15, 2010|first=Matt|last=Goldberg|accessdate=July 5, 2011}}</ref> The rest of the campaign unrolled after [[WonderCon]] in April 2010, where Warner gave away promotional T-shirts featuring the PASIV briefcase used to create the dream space, and had a [[QR code]] linking to an online manual of the device.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ugo.com/movies/new-inception-site-goes-viral |title=Start Your Dream Weaving |publisher=[[UGO Networks]] |first=Silas |last=Lesnic |date=April 5, 2010 |accessdate=July 5, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510140254/http://www.ugo.com/movies/new-inception-site-goes-viral |archivedate=May 10, 2010}}</ref> ''Mind Crime'' also received a stage&nbsp;2 with more resources, including a hidden trailer for the movie.<ref name=trailer>{{cite news|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/official-full-length-inception-trailer-is-here|date=May 10, 2010|first=Brian|last=Gallagher|work=MovieWeb|title=Official Full-Length Inception Trailer Is Here!|accessdate=July 5, 2011}}</ref> More pieces of viral marketing began to surface before ''Inception''{{'}}s release, such as a manual filled with bizarre images and text sent to ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' magazine,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/underwire/2010/06/dream-share-manual/|title=Mysterious Dream-Share Manual Is a Viral Mind-Wipe|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|last= Thill|first=Scott |accessdate=June 3, 2010|date=June 1, 2010}}</ref> and the online publication of posters, ads, phone applications, and strange websites all related to the film.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Nick |last=Newman |url=http://thefilmstage.com/2010/06/07/new-inception-viral-poster-and-websites/ |title=New Inception Viral Poster |publisher=The Film Stage |accessdate=June 7, 2010 |date=June 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611055801/http://thefilmstage.com/2010/06/07/new-inception-viral-poster-and-websites |archivedate=June 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/07/09/us-inception-idUSTRE6680MM20100709|title='Inception' is no dream for marketers\n|first=Carl|last=DiOrio|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=July 9, 2010|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}</ref> Warner also released an online prequel comic, ''Inception: The Cobol Job''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://econsultancy.com/us/blog/6277-inception-multichannel-marketing-that-works-like-a-dream|title=Inception: multichannel marketing that works like a dream|publisher=eConsultancy|date=July 21, 2010|first=Matt|last=Owen |accessdate=July 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe official trailer released on May 10, 2010 through ''Mind Game'' was extremely well received.<ref name=trailer/> It featured an original piece of music, \"Mind Heist\", by recording artist [[Zack Hemsey]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Mind Heist|url=http://music.zackhemsey.com/album/mind-heist}}</ref> rather than music from the score.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/inception-trailer-composer-zack-hemsey-profiled/|title='Inception' Trailer Composer Zack Hemsey Profiled|publisher=Slash Film|accessdate=April 13, 2011|date=April 7, 2011}}</ref> The trailer quickly went viral with numerous [[mashup (video)|mashups]] copying its style, both by amateurs on sites like YouTube<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collider.com/ghostbusters-trailer-inception/68798/|title=GHOSTBUSTERS Trailer Re-Cut to INCEPTION Score |publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=April 13, 2011|date=January 7, 2011}}</ref> and by professionals on sites such as [[CollegeHumor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.collegehumor.com/video/6305356/50s-inception-trailer |title=50s Inception Trailer Profiled |publisher=CollegeHumor |accessdate=April 13, 2011 |date=October 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301121747/http://www.collegehumor.com/video/6305356/50s-inception-trailer |archivedate=March 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.collegehumor.com/video/6286263/a-capella-inception-trailer |title=A Capella Inception Trailer |publisher=CollegeHumor |accessdate=April 13, 2011 |date=September 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110418045802/http://www.collegehumor.com/video/6286263/a-capella-inception-trailer |archivedate=April 18, 2011}}</ref> On June 7, 2010, a behind-the-scenes featurette on the film was released in HD on Yahoo! Movies.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Jordan |last=Raup |url=http://thefilmstage.com/2010/06/07/behind-the-scenes-inception-featurette-now-available-in-hd/ |title=Behind The Scenes Inception Featurette Now Available In HD |publisher=The Film Stage |accessdate=June 7, 2010 |date=June 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610171853/http://thefilmstage.com/2010/06/07/behind-the-scenes-inception-featurette-now-available-in-hd |archivedate=June 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Inception'' was released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] on December 3, 2010, in France,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premiere.fr/Cinema/Photos/Reportages/PHOTOS-Inception-decouvrez-le-DVD-en-images/%28gid%29/2467699|title=PHOTOS \u2013 Inception : d\u00e9couvrez le DVD en images|work=[[Premiere (magazine)|Premi\u00e8re]]|accessdate=May 4, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209220017/http://www.premiere.fr/Cinema/Photos/Reportages/PHOTOS-Inception-decouvrez-le-DVD-en-images/(gid)/2467699|archivedate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> and the week after in the UK and USA (December 7, 2010).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homevideo.about.com/od/newdvdreleases/tp/New-DVD-Releases-December-7-2010-a.htm|title=New DVD Releases \u2013 December 7, 2010|first=Ivana|last=Redwine|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=May 4, 2011|date=December 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moviefone.co.uk/2010/12/06/new-on-dvd-week-of-6-december/|title=New on DVD: Week of December 6|date=December 6, 2010|first=Joe|last=Barton|publisher=[[Moviefone]] |accessdate=April 5, 2011}}</ref> Warner Bros. also made available in the United States a limited Blu-ray edition packaged in a metal replica of the PASIV briefcase, which included extras such as a metal replica of the spinning top totem. With a production run of less than 2000, it sold out in one weekend.<ref name=Limited>[http://www.wbshop.com/on/demandware.store/Sites-WB-Site/default/Product-Show?pid=INWBDVDBDBC&adid=1110InceptEml&AID=10501819 Inception BD/DVD Briefcase Gift Set] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101118194954/http://www.wbshop.com/on/demandware.store/Sites-WB-Site/default/Product-Show?pid=INWBDVDBDBC&adid=1110InceptEml&AID=10501819 |date=November 18, 2010 }}. Warner Bros. Retrieved November 23, 2010.</ref> ''Inception'' was released on 4K Blu-ray and [[digital copy]] along with other Christopher Nolan films on December 19, 2017.<ref>{{Citation|title=Christopher Nolan Collection 4K Blu-ray|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Christopher-Nolan-Collection-4K-Blu-ray/193522/|accessdate=March 29, 2018}}</ref> {{as of|2018}}, the [[home video]] releases have sold over 9{{nbsp}}million units and grossed over {{US$|160 million|long=no}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=Inception (2010) \u2013 Financial Information |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Inception#tab=video-sales |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=November 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Putative video game{{anchor|Proposed video game}}===\nIn a November 2010 interview, Nolan expressed his intention to develop a video game set in the ''Inception'' world, working with a team of collaborators. He described it as \"a longer-term proposition\", referring to the medium of video games as \"something I've wanted to explore\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Jensen|first=Jeff|title=Christopher Nolan on his 'last' Batman movie, an 'Inception' videogame, and that spinning top|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2010/11/30/christopher-nolan-batman-inception/|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=December 3, 2010|date=November 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office{{anchor|Box-office performance}}===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Film\n! colspan=\"1\" | Release date\n! colspan=\"3\" | Box office revenue\n! colspan=\"2\" text=\"wrap\" | Box office ranking\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Budget\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Reference\n|-\n! United States\n! North America\n! International\n! Worldwide\n! All-time United States\n! All-time worldwide\n|-\n| ''Inception ''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| July 2010\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| US$292,576,195\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| US$532,956,569\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| US$825,532,764\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| No. 80\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| No. 67\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| US$160,000,000\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url= http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=inception.htm |title= Inception (2010) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate=August 18, 2011}}</ref>\n|}\n\n''Inception'' was released in both conventional and [[IMAX]] theaters on July 16, 2010.<ref name=\"release\">{{Cite news|first=Jeff |last=Bock |url=http://www.ercboxoffice.com/index.php?page=news&news_id=114 |title=Wb name drops big titles |publisher=ERC Box Office |date=February 24, 2009 |accessdate=February 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226205532/http://www.ercboxoffice.com/index.php?page=news&news_id=114 |archivedate=February 26, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Vlessing|first=Etan|title=Imax books ''Inception''|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=October 1, 2009|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/imax-books-inception-89552|accessdate=October 1, 2009}}</ref> The film had its world premiere at [[Leicester Square]] in London, United Kingdom on July 8, 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Plumb|first=Alastair|title=''Inception'' World Premiere Report|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=July 9, 2010|url=http://www.empireonline.com/news/feed.asp?NID=28324|accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> In the United States and Canada, ''Inception'' was released theatrically in 3,792 conventional theaters and 195 [[IMAX]] theaters.<ref name=\"release\" /> The film grossed US$21.8&nbsp;million during its opening day on July 16, 2010, with midnight screenings in 1,500 locations.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Finke |first=Nikki |url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/07/solid-3m-midnights-for-nolans-inception/ |title='Inception' Dreams Up $21.4M Friday And Possible $52M Weekend; No Magic For 'Sorcerer's Apprentice' With $5.4M/$16.5M |magazine=Deadline.com |date=July 17, 2010 |accessdate=July 18, 2010}}</ref> Overall the film made US$62.7&nbsp;million and debuted at No.1 on its opening weekend.<ref name=\"mojo-weekend\" /> ''Inception''{{'}}s opening weekend gross made it the second-highest-grossing debut for a [[science fiction film|science-fiction film]] that was not a sequel, remake or adaptation, behind ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]''{{'s}} US$77&nbsp;million opening weekend gross in 2009.<ref name=\"mojo-weekend\">{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2862&p=.htm |title=Weekend Report: 'Inception' Incites Intense Interest |last=Gray |first=Brandon |accessdate=July 21, 2010 |date=July 19, 2010|website=Box Office Mojo}}</ref> The film held the top spot of the box office rankings in its second and third weekends, with drops of just 32% (US$42.7&nbsp;million) and 36% (US$27.5&nbsp;million) respectively,<ref>{{cite web|date=July 26, 2010 |first=Brandon |last=Gray |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2865&p=.htm |title='Inception' Maintains Grip, 'Salt' Savors Second Place |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=September 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=August 2, 2010 |first=Brandon |last=Gray |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2874&p=.htm |title='Inception' Keeps Dream Alive |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=September 4, 2010}}</ref> before dropping to second place in its fourth week, behind ''[[The Other Guys]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2882&p=.htm |title=Weekend Report: 'Other Guys' Arrest Audiences, 'Step Up' Gets Served, 'Inception' Lingers|last=Gray|first=Brandon|accessdate=June 19, 2011|date=August 9, 2010|website=Box Office Mojo}}</ref>\n\n''Inception'' grossed US$292&nbsp;million in the United States and Canada, US$56&nbsp;million in the United Kingdom, Ireland and [[Malta]] and US$475&nbsp;million in other countries for a total of US$823&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref name=\"Mojo\"/> Its five highest-grossing markets after the US and Canada (US$292) were China (US$68million), the United Kingdom, Ireland and [[Malta]] (US$56&nbsp;million), France and the [[Maghreb]] region (US$43&nbsp;million), Japan (US$40&nbsp;million) and [[South Korea]] (US$38&nbsp;million).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=inception.htm |title=Inception |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=October 22, 2010}}</ref> It was the sixth-highest-grossing film of 2010 in North America,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=2010&p=.htm |title=2010 DOMESTIC GROSSES |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> and the [[2010 in film#Highest-grossing films|fourth-highest-grossing film of 2010]], behind ''[[Toy Story 3]]'', ''[[Alice in Wonderland (2010 film)|Alice in Wonderland]]'' and ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows \u2013 Part 1]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2010&p=.htm |title=2010 WORLDWIDE GROSSES |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=September 9, 2010}}</ref> ''Inception'' is the third most lucrative production in [[Christopher Nolan]]'s career\u2014behind ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' and ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Director&id=christophernolan.htm|title=Christopher Nolan|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref>\u2014 and the second most for [[Leonardo DiCaprio]]\u2014behind ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Actor&id=leonardodicaprio.htm |title=Leonardo DiCaprio |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=November 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{Anchor|Critics}}\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 87% based on 352 reviews, with an average rating of 8.11/10. The website's critical consensus reads: \"Smart, innovative, and thrilling, ''Inception'' is that rare summer blockbuster that succeeds viscerally as well as intellectually.\"<ref name=\"tomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/inception/|title=Inception (2010) |work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=April 23, 2018}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], another review aggregator, assigned the film a weighted average score of 74 out of 100, based on 42 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/inception |title=Inception |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |work = [[Metacritic]]|accessdate=July 27, 2010}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Andrew|last=Stewart|title='Inception' tops weekend box office |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118021880.html|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 18, 2010|accessdate=August 18, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called ''Inception'' a \"wildly ingenious chess game,\" and concluded \"the result is a knockout.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Travers |first=Peter|title=''Inception''|work=Rolling Stone|date=July 12, 2010 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/17388/180225 |accessdate=July 14, 2010}}</ref> Justin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the film as \"a conceptual [[wikt:tour de force|tour de force]]\" and wrote, \"applying a vivid sense of procedural detail to a fiendishly intricate yarn set in the [[labyrinth]] of the [[unconscious mind]], the writer-director has devised a heist thriller for [[surrealist]]s, a [[Jung]]ian's ''[[Rififi]]'', that challenges viewers to sift through multiple layers of (un)reality.\"<ref name=\"variety-review\">{{Cite news |last=Chang |first=Justin|title=''Inception''|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 5, 2010 |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117943114.html |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> Jim Vejvoda of [[IGN]] rated the film as perfect, deeming it \"a singular accomplishment from a filmmaker who has only gotten better with each film.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Vejvoda |first=Jim |title=''\"Inception\" Para la gran mayoria de los criticos Inception es una de las mejores peliculas de la historia del cine.'' Review |work=[[IGN]] |date=July 6, 2010 |url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/110/1103912p1.html |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Relevant (magazine)|Relevant]]''{{'}}s David Roark called it Nolan's \"greatest accomplishment,\" saying, \"Visually, intellectually and emotionally, ''Inception'' is a masterpiece.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Roark |first=David |title=''Inception'' |work=[[Relevant Magazine]] |date=July 12, 2010 |url=http://www.relevantmagazine.com/culture/film/reviews/22278-inception |accessdate=July 14, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100721011123/http://www.relevantmagazine.com/culture/film/reviews/22278-inception |archive-date=July 21, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn its August 2010 issue, ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine gave the film a full five stars and wrote, \"it feels like [[Stanley Kubrick]] adapting the work of the great sci-fi author [[William Gibson]] [...] Nolan delivers another true original: welcome to an undiscovered country.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Pierce |first=Nev |title=''Inception'' |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=June 7, 2010 |url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=136118 |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s Lisa Schwarzbaum gave the film a B+ grade and wrote, \"It's a rolling explosion of images as hypnotizing and sharply angled as any in a drawing by [[M. C. Escher]] or a state-of-the-biz video game; the backwards splicing of Nolan's own ''Memento'' looks rudimentary by comparison.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Schwarzbaum |first=Lisa |title=''Inception'' |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=July 12, 2010 |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20401172,00.html |accessdate=July 13, 2010}}</ref> The ''[[New York Post]]''{{'}}s [[Lou Lumenick]] gave the film a four-star rating and wrote, \"DiCaprio, who has never been better as the tortured hero, draws you in with a love story that will appeal even to non-sci-fi fans.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lumenick|first=Lou|title=Dream team!|work=New York Post|date=July 14, 2010 |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/movies/dream_team_105fXIW5839pHficdGU9vN|accessdate=July 14, 2010}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' awarded the film a full four stars and said that ''Inception'' \"is all about process, about fighting our way through enveloping sheets of reality and dream, reality within dreams, dreams without reality. It's a breathtaking juggling act.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ebert |first=Roger |authorlink=Roger Ebert |title=''Inception''|work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=July 14, 2010 |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100714/REVIEWS/100719997 |accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]], also of the ''Sun-Times'', gave ''Inception'' an \"A+\" score and called it \"one of the best movies of the [21st] century.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.richardroeper.com/reviews/inception.aspx|title=''Inception'' Review |last=Roeper |first=Richard |authorlink=Richard Roeper |work=Chicago Sun-Times |accessdate=July 21, 2010}}</ref> [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]'s [[Mark Kermode]] named ''Inception'' as the best film of 2010, stating that \"''Inception'' is proof that people are not stupid, that cinema is not trash, and that it is possible for blockbusters and art to be the same thing.\"<ref name=\"Kermode\">{{cite video |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/markkermode/2010/12/my_top_five_films_of_the_year.html |accessdate=February 9, 2011 |date=December 24, 2010 |first=Mark |last=Kermode |authorlink=Mark Kermode |title=Kermode Uncut: My Top Five Films of the Year |publisher=BBC |time=5:05}}</ref>\n\n[[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film 3 out of 4 stars and wrote, \"I found myself wishing ''Inception'' were weirder, further out [...] the film is Nolan's labyrinth all the way, and it's gratifying to experience a summer movie with large visual ambitions and with nothing more or less on its mind than (as [[Shakespeare]] said) a dream that hath no bottom.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Phillips |first=Michael |title=''Inception'' |work=Chicago Tribune|date=July 15, 2010|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-0713-inception-20100715,0,6233986.column |accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> ''TIME Magazine''{{'}}s [[Richard Corliss]] wrote that the film's \"noble intent is to implant one man's vision in the mind of a vast audience [...] The idea of moviegoing as communal dreaming is a century old. With ''Inception'', viewers have a chance to see that notion get a state-of-the-art update.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Corliss|first=Richard|authorlink=Richard Corliss |title=''Inception'': Whose Mind Is It, Anyway? |work=TIME |date=July 14, 2010|url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,2003808,00.html|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> [[Kenneth Turan]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' felt that Nolan was able to blend \"the best of traditional and modern filmmaking. If you're searching for smart and nervy popular entertainment, this is what it looks like.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Turan|first=Kenneth|authorlink=Kenneth Turan|title=''Inception''|work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 16, 2010|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-inception-20100716,0,5478728.story|accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref>\n''[[USA Today]]''{{'s}} Claudia Puig gave the film three-and-a-half out of four stars and felt that Nolan \"regards his viewers as possibly smarter than they are\u2014or at least as capable of rising to his inventive level. That's a tall order. But it's refreshing to find a director who makes us stretch, even occasionally struggle, to keep up.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Puig|first=Claudia|title=You definitely won't sleep through complex thriller ''Inception''|work=[[USA Today]] |date=July 15, 2010|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2010-07-15-inception15_ST_N.htm|accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\nNot all reviewers gave the film positive reviews. ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]] Magazine''{{'}}s [[David Edelstein]] claimed in his review that he had \"no idea what so many people are raving about. It's as if someone went into their heads while they were sleeping and planted the idea that ''Inception'' is a visionary masterpiece and\u2014hold on ... Whoa! I think I get it. The movie is a metaphor for the power of delusional hype\u2014a metaphor for itself.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Edelstein|first=David|title=Dream a Little Dream|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=July 11, 2010 |url=http://nymag.com/movies/reviews/67155/|accessdate=July 13, 2010}}</ref> ''[[The New York Observer]]''{{'}}s [[Rex Reed]] explained that the film's development was \"pretty much what we've come to expect from summer movies in general and Christopher Nolan movies in particular ... [it] doesn't seem like much of an accomplishment to me.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reed |first=Rex |title=Can Someone Please Explain ''Inception'' to Me? |work=[[The New York Observer]] |date=July 13, 2010 |url=http://www.observer.com/2010/culture/can-someone-please-explain-inception-me |accessdate=July 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715052057/http://www.observer.com/2010/culture/can-someone-please-explain-inception-me |archivedate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> [[A. O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' commented \"there is a lot to see in ''Inception'', there is nothing that counts as genuine vision. Mr. Nolan's idea of the mind is too literal, too logical, and too rule-bound to allow the full measure of madness.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Scott |first=A. O. |authorlink=A. O. Scott|title=This Time the Dream's on Me|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 15, 2010 |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2010/07/16/movies/16inception.html |accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]''{{'}}s [[David Denby]] considered the film to \"not nearly [be] as much fun as Nolan imagined it to be\", concluding that \"''Inception'' is a stunning-looking film that gets lost in fabulous intricacies, a movie devoted to its own workings and to little else.\"<ref name=\"Denby\">{{cite news|last=Denby|first=David|authorlink=David Denby (film critic) |title=Dream Factory|url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/cinema/2010/07/26/100726crci_cinema_denby|accessdate=February 10, 2011|newspaper=[[The New Yorker]] |date=July 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWhile some critics have tended to view the film as perfectly straightforward, and even criticize its overarching themes as \"the stuff of torpid platitudes,\" online discussion has been much more positive.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Nick |last=Schager |title=Inception |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/inception/4898 |work=[[Slant (magazine)|Slant]] |date=July 14, 2010 |accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref> Heated debate has centered on the ambiguity of the ending, with many critics like Devin Faraci making the case that the film is self-referential and tongue-in-cheek, both a film about film-making and a dream about dreams.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Devin|last=Faraci|title=Never Wake Up: The Meaning and Secret of Inception |url=http://www.chud.com/24477/never-wake-up-the-meaning-and-secret-of-inception/|publisher=Chud.com|date=July 19, 2010|accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref> Other critics read ''Inception'' as Christian allegory and focus on the film's use of religious and water symbolism.<ref>{{Cite web |first=David |last=Lancashire |title=Cobb is Dead |url=http://www.quora.com/Inception-2010-movie/Was-Cobb-dreaming-in-the-final-sequence-of-Inception/all_comments/David-Lancashire |date=October 6, 2010 |accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref> Yet other critics, such as [[Kristin Thompson]], see less value in the ambiguous ending of the film and more in its structure and novel method of storytelling, highlighting ''Inception'' as a new form of narrative that revels in \"continuous exposition\".<ref>{{Cite web |first=Kristin |last=Thomas|title=Revisiting Inception|url=http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2010/08/12/revisiting-inception/ |publisher=Observations on Film Art (blog) |date=August 12, 2010|accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSeveral critics and scholars have noted the film has many striking similarities to the 2006 [[anime]] film ''[[Paprika (2006 film)|Paprika]]'' by [[Satoshi Kon]] (and [[Yasutaka Tsutsui]]'s 1993 [[Paprika (novel)|novel of the same name]]), including plot similarities, similar scenes, and similar characters, arguing that ''Inception'' was influenced by ''Paprika''.<ref name=\"Drazen\">{{cite book |last=Drazen |first=Patrick |title=Anime Explosion!: The What? Why? and Wow! of Japanese Animation, Revised and Updated Edition |date=2014 |publisher=[[Stone Bridge Press]] |isbn=9781611725506 |url={{Google books|-s30AgAAQBAJ |page=PA339 |keywords= |text=|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref><ref name=\"Wardlow\">{{cite web |last=Wardlow |first=Ciara |title=The Synergy of 'Inception' and 'Paprika' |url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/the-synergy-of-inception-and-paprika-ffefd0973f12/ |website=[[Film School Rejects]] |date=March 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web |last=Rizzo-Smith |first=Julian |title=An Ode to Anime Auteur Satoshi Kon |url=https://in.ign.com/paprika/127083/feature/an-ode-to-anime-auteur-satoshi-kon |website=[[IGN]] |date=August 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Horner\">{{cite web |last=Horner |first=Joshua |title=20 Suspiciously Similar Movie Scenes You Never Noticed |url=http://whatculture.com/film/20-suspiciously-similar-movie-scenes-never-noticed?page=4 |website=WhatCulture |page=4 |date=January 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Boone |first1=Steven |title='Inception': As eye-catching, and as profound, as an Usher concert |url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2010/07/inception-as-eye-catching-and-as-profound-as-an-usher-concert-067223 |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |work=[[Politico]] |date=July 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Emerson |first1=Jim |title=Inception: Has Christopher Nolan forgotten how to dream? |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/scanners/inception-has-christopher-nolan-forgotten-how-to-dream |website=[[RogerEbert.com]] |date=July 17, 2010 |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> Several sources have also noted plot similarities between the film and the 2002 [[Scrooge McDuck|Uncle Scrooge]] comic ''[[The Dream of a Lifetime]]'' by [[Don Rosa]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Brown|first=Damon|title=Was 'Inception' inspired by Donald Duck?|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/TECH/web/08/10/inception.donald.duck/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=December 29, 2011|date=August 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Gornstein |first=Leslie |title=Did Inception Really Rip Off Scrooge McDuck? |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/ask_the_answer_bitch/did_inception_really_rip_off_scrooge/193794 |work=[[E!#E! Online|E! Online]] |accessdate=December 29, 2011 |date=August 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206031007/http://www.eonline.com/news/ask_the_answer_bitch/did_inception_really_rip_off_scrooge/193794 |archivedate=February 6, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sean|first=O'Neal|title=The \"Inception ripped-off Scrooge McDuck\" theory that will briefly amuse you |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-inception-rippedoff-scrooge-mcduck-theory-that,43814/ |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |accessdate=December 29, 2011 |date=August 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===<span id=\"Top ten lists\"></span><span id=\"Legacy\"></span>Year-end and all-time lists===\n''Inception'' appeared on over 273 critics' lists of the top ten films of 2010, being picked as number-one on at least 55 of those lists.<ref name=\"criticstop10\">{{Cite web |url=http://criticstop10.com/best-of-2010/ |title=Home Page \u2013 Best of 2010 |publisher=CriticsTop10 |accessdate=May 4, 2011}}</ref> It was the second most mentioned film in both the top ten lists and number-one rankings, only behind ''[[The Social Network]]'', joining that film, ''[[Toy Story 3]]'', ''[[The King's Speech]]'', and ''[[Black Swan (film)|Black Swan]]'' as the most critically acclaimed films of 2010.<ref name=\"criticstop10\" />\n\nCritics and publications who ranked the film first for that year included [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', [[Kenneth Turan]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' (tied with ''[[The Social Network]]'' and ''[[Toy Story 3]]''), Tasha Robinson of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine, and Kirk Honeycutt of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''.<ref name=\"metacritictopten\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critic-top-ten-lists |title=2010 Film Critic Top Ten Lists |last=Dietz |first=Jason |website=[[Metacritic]] |date=December 9, 2010 |accessdate=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe film's placement in some notable top ten lists:<ref name=\"metacritictopten\" /><!-- arbitrary list? what's the criteria for inclusion here -->\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 [[Richard Roeper]], ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 [[Kenneth Turan]], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' (tied with ''[[The Social Network]]'' and ''[[Toy Story 3]]'')\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Tasha Robinson, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]''\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Kirk Honeycutt, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 [[Peter Travers]], ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;- [[Christy Lemire]], ''[[Associated Press]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 [[James Berardinelli]], ''Reelviews''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Gregory Ellwood, ''[[HitFix]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Lisa Kennedy, ''[[Denver Post]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Bill Goodykoontz, ''[[Arizona Republic]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 [[Stephen Holden]], ''[[The New York Times]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 [[Philip French]], ''[[The Observer]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 [[FX Feeney]], ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n* 4th&nbsp;\u2013 Keith Phipps, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Nathan Rabin]], ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Lou Lumenick]], ''[[New York Post]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Roger Ebert]], ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 Elizabeth Weitzman, ''[[New York Daily News]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Ann Hornaday]], ''[[Washington Post]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Caryn James]], ''[[Indiewire]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 Claudia Puig, ''[[USA Today]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;- David Germain, [[Associated Press]]\n* 6th&nbsp;- Rene Rodriguez, ''[[Miami Herald]]''\n* 7th&nbsp;\u2013 Noel Murray, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n* 8th&nbsp;\u2013  Mike Scott, ''[[The Times-Picayune]]''\n* 9th&nbsp;\u2013 Drew McWeeny, ''[[HitFix]]''\n* 10th&nbsp;\u2013 [[J. Hoberman]], ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n* 10th&nbsp;\u2013 Peter Hartlaub, ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\nIn March 2011, the film was voted by [[BBC Radio 1]] and [[BBC Radio 1Xtra]] listeners as their ninth favorite film of all time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/radio1movies/ |title=Radio 1 Movies Blog |publisher=BBC |accessdate=July 23, 2013}}</ref> ''Inception'' was voted as the third best sci-fi film of all time in the 2011 list ''[[Best in Film: The Greatest Movies of Our Time]]'', based on a poll conducted by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] and ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''. In 2012, ''Inception'' was ranked the 35th Best Edited Film of All Time by the [[Motion Picture Editors Guild]].<ref name=\"editorsguild\">{{cite web|url=https://www.editorsguild.com/magazine.cfm?ArticleID=1101|title=The 75 Best Editied Films |work=CineMontage |accessdate=June 1, 2013 |date=Summer 2013}}</ref> In the same year, ''[[Total Film]]'' named it the most rewatchable movie of all time.<ref name=Rewatchable>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/50-most-rewatchable-movies/inception-2010 |title=50 Most Rewatchable Movies |magazine=[[Total Film]] |accessdate=July 24, 2013}}</ref> In 2014, ''Empire'' ranked ''Inception'' the tenth greatest film ever made on their list of \"The 301 Greatest Movies Of All Time\" as voted by the magazine's readers,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/301/list.asp?page=29 |title=The 301 Greatest Movies Of All Time |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> while ''Rolling Stone'' magazine named it the second best science fiction film since the turn of the century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/lists/the-top-20-sci-fi-films-of-the-21st-century-20140515 |title=The Top 20 Sci-Fi Films of the 21st Century |work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=August 14, 2014}}</ref> ''Inception'' was ranked 84th on ''Hollywood's 100 Favorite Films'', a list compiled by ''The Hollywood Reporter'' in 2014, surveying \"Studio chiefs, Oscar winners and TV royalty\".<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=June 22, 2015 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/100-greatest-films-all-time-714192/84-inception|title=Hollywood's 100 Favorite Films|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> In 2016, ''Inception'' was voted the 51st [[BBC's 100 Greatest Films of the 21st Century|best film of the 21st Century]] by [[BBC]], as picked by 177 film critics from around the world.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=August 23, 2016|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films?ocid=twcul |title=The 21st Century's 100 Greatest Films|work=BBC}}</ref> The film was included in the [[Visual Effects Society]]'s list of \"The Most Influential Visual Effects Films of All Time\".<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=September 16, 2017|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/09/visual-effects-society-top-70-vfx-films-star-wars-blade-runner-citizen-kane-1201875595/|title=Visual Effects Society: The Top 70 VFX Films of All Time Include 'Star Wars,' 'Blade Runner,' and 'Citizen Kane' |work=Indiewire}}</ref> In 2019, ''Total Film'' named ''Inception'' the best film of the 2010s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/decade-best-movies-2010-2019/4/ |title=The 100 best movies of the decade |work=[[Total Film]] |accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref> Many critics and media outlets included ''Inception'' in their rankings of the best films of the 2010s.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The 100 Greatest Movies Of The 21st Century: 10 - 1|magazine=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=January 11, 2020|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/best-movies-century-page-10/|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=September 5, 2019|url=https://mashable.com/article/best-films-of-2010s-decade/|title=The 15 best films of the 2010s|work=mashable.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=November 5, 2019|url=https://medium.com/luwd-media/the-100-best-films-of-the-2010s-d30b2b54903d|title=The 100 Best Films of the 2010s|work=medium.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/best-movies-decade-2010s-list/|title=Best movies of 2010s decade|last=Leadbeater|first=Alex|date=2 March 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=November 5, 2019|url=https://film.avclub.com/the-100-best-movies-of-the-2010s-1839846306|title=The 100 best movies of the 2010s|work=The A.V. Club}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=May 2, 2019|url=https://www.worldofreel.com/blog/2019/4/critics-poll-top-75-movies-of-the-decade|title=Critics Poll: Top 75 Movies of the Decade|work=World of Reel}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' placed the title on its top ten list of the most overrated films. ''Telegraph''{{'}}s Tim Robey stated, \"It's a criminal failing of the movie that it purports to be about people's dreams being invaded, but demonstrates no instinct at all for what a dream has ever felt like, and no flair for making us feel like we're in one, at any point.\"<ref>{{cite web |first1=Tim |last1=Robey |title=10 most overrated films of all time |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/10767345/10-most-overrated-films-of-all-time.html|website=telegraph.co.uk |date=April 21, 2014 |accessdate=June 1, 2014}}</ref> The film won an informal poll by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' as the most overrated movie of 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2010/12/inception-christopher-nolan-overrated.html |title='Inception' wins informal poll as most overrated movie of 2010 (Part 2) |date=December 30, 2010 |accessdate=June 2, 2014 |first1=Steven |last1=Zeitchik |website=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Inception}}\n\nThe film won many awards in technical categories, such as [[Academy Awards]] for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]], and [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]],<ref name=oscars>{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/83/nominees.html |title=Nominees for the 83rd Academy Awards |publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref> and the [[British Academy Film Awards]] for [[BAFTA Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Special Visual Effects|Best Special Visual Effects]] and [[BAFTA Award for Best Sound|Best Sound]].<ref name=BAFTA>{{cite web |url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/2011-film-awards,1572,BA.html |title=2011 BAFTA Awards Nominees |publisher=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] |accessdate=January 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110110061729/http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/2011-film-awards%2C1572%2CBA.html |archivedate=January 10, 2011  }}</ref> In most of its artistic nominations, such as Film, Director, and Screenplay at the Oscars, BAFTAs and [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globes]], the film was defeated by ''[[The Social Network]]'' or ''[[The King's Speech]]''.<ref name=oscars/><ref name=BAFTA/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/nominations/year/2010 |title=68th Annual Golden Globe Awards Nominations |publisher=[[Hollywood Foreign Press Association]] |accessdate=January 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Ap0fVUMt?url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/nominations/year/2010 |archivedate=September 20, 2012  }}</ref> However, the film did win the two highest honors for a science fiction or fantasy film: the 2011 [[Bradbury Award]] for best dramatic production<ref name= Nebulas>{{cite web |url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2011/05/2011-nebula-award-winners |title=2011 Nebula Award winners |publisher=[[Tor.com]] |accessdate=October 16, 2011}}</ref> and the 2011 [[Hugo Award]] for best dramatic presentation, long form.<ref name=Hugos>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/2011/08/2011-hugo-award-winners/ |title=2011 Hugo Award winners |publisher=[[Hugo Awards]] |accessdate=October 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nNumerous pop and hip hop songs reference the film, including [[Common (rapper)|Common]]'s \"Blue Sky,\" [[N.E.R.D]]'s \"[[Hypnotize U]],\" [[XV (rapper)|XV]]'s \"The Kick,\" [[The Black Eyed Peas]]' \"[[Just Can't Get Enough (The Black Eyed Peas song)|Just Can't Get Enough]],\" [[Lil Wayne]]'s \"[[6 Foot 7 Foot]],\" [[Jennifer Lopez]]'s \"[[On the Floor]],\" and [[B.o.B]]'s \"[[Strange Clouds (song)|Strange Clouds]],\" while [[T.I.]] had ''Inception''-based artwork on two of his mixtapes. An instrumental track by [[Joe Budden]] is titled \"Inception.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Zorgel |title=Why do rappers love the movie Inception so much? |url=http://www.aux.tv/2012/03/why-do-rappers-love-the-movie-inception-so-much/ |work=AUX.TV |date=March 8, 2012 |accessdate=December 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611062544/http://www.aux.tv/2012/03/why-do-rappers-love-the-movie-inception-so-much/ | archive-date=June 11, 2016 | url-status=dead  }}</ref> The animated series ''[[South Park]]'' parodies the film in the show's tenth episode of its [[South Park (season 14)|fourteenth season]], titled \"[[Insheeption]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hill|first1=Scott T.|title=South Park Satirizes Inception's Mind-Wipe |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/10/south-park-inception/|website=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=November 15, 2017|date=October 21, 2010}}</ref> The film was also an influence for [[Ariana Grande]]'s video for \"[[No Tears Left to Cry]].\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Willman |first1=Chris |title=Song Review: Ariana Grande's 'No Tears Left to Cry' |url=https://variety.com/2018/music/news/ariana-grande-no-tears-left-to-cry-review-1202770171/ |website=Variety |accessdate=July 6, 2018 |date=April 19, 2018}}</ref> \"[[Lawnmower Dog]]\", the second episode of the animated comedy show ''[[Rick and Morty]]'', parodied the film.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goldberg |first1=Lesley |title=Adult Swim's 'Rick and Morty' Takes On 'Inception' |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/adult-swims-rick-morty-takes-661896 |website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> In an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', named  \"[[How I Wet Your Mother]]\", the plot spoofs ''Inception'' with various scenes parodying moments from the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2012/03/when-the-simpsons-went-inception-48463/|title=When \u2018The Simpsons\u2019 Went \u2018Inception\u2019|last=Willmore|first=Alison|date=March 27, 2020|website=[[Indiewire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The showrunners of the television series ''[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]'' said its season 4 finale was inspired by ''Inception''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2423571/the-flash-showrunner-explains-how-the-finale-is-inspired-by-inception|title=The Flash Showrunner Explains How The Finale Is Inspired By Inception|last=Venable|first=Nick|date=February 7, 2020|magazine=Cinemablend|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> In February 2020, American singer-songwriter [[Taylor Swift]] released a lyric video for her single \"[[The Man (Taylor Swift song)|The Man]]\", which featured visuals bearing resemblance to the film. The song also name-checks DiCaprio in its lyrics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://popcrush.com/taylor-swift-the-man-lyric-video/|title=Taylor Swift's 'The Man' Lyric Video Features a Subtle Nod to Leonardo DiCaprio|last=Reda|first=Natasha|date=February 7, 2020|magazine=[[PopCrush]]|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film inspired the suffix ''[[wikt:-ception|-ception]]'', which can be appended to a noun to indicate a layering, nesting, or recursion of the thing in question.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://neologisms.rice.edu/index.php?a=term&d=1&t=17573 |title=-ception \u2013 The Rice University Neologisms Database |publisher=Rice University |accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n* [[Suggestion]]\n* [[Simulacrum]]\n* [[Dreamscape_(1984_film)|Dreamscape]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book|last1 =Johnson|first1 =David Kyle (Editor)|last2 =Irwin|first2 =William|year =2011|title =Inception and Philosophy: Because It's Never Just a Dream|publisher =John Wiley & Sons|isbn =1-118-07263-4|url-access =registration|url =https://archive.org/details/inceptionphiloso00john}}\n* {{Cite book |last1= Nolan |first1= Christopher (Author)|last2=Nolan|first2=Jonathan|year =2010 |title =Inception: The Shooting Script|publisher=Insight Editions |isbn=1-60887-015-4}}\n* {{Cite journal |last = Crawford |first = Kevin Ray (Author) |title =The Rhetorics of the Time-Image: Deleuzian Metadiscourse on the Role of Nooshock Temporality (viz. \"Inception\") in Christopher Nolan's Cinema of the Brain|publisher=ProQuest LLC |year =2012}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Inception (film)|Inception}}\n{{Commons category|Inception (film)|Inception}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.inceptionmovie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1375666}}\n* {{AllMovie title|480818}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|inception}}\n\n{{Christopher Nolan}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by Inception|Awards for ''Inception'']]\n|list =\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Action Film}}\n{{Empire Award for Best Film}}\n{{Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation, Long Form}}\n{{Nebula Award for